<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS HAVE NO PROBLEM SENDING COWBOYS TO 0-4 IN PRESEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With the NFL cutdown to 65, plus exemptions, coming up
Tuesday, you might say the Cowboys can see dead people.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys players and coaches alike watched in horror last night
as free-agent return specialist Darran Hall fumbled away the
opening two kickoffs in a 36-23 loss to Denver at Mile High
Stadium, and for the Cowboys it was all downhill after that.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (0-4) had its traditional preseason ``dress rehearsal''
go off _ well, a bit rocky _ before 69,143. The Cowboys are 1-13 in
preseason games since 1998, including 1-2 in the next-to-last, or
dress-rehearsal, game.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this preseason, Troy Aikman and the Cowboys'
first-team offense failed to find the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first- and second-team defense _ in other words,
everyone who is going to play this season _ had an even longer
night as the Broncos picked up nearly eight yards a snap (223 yards
on 30 plays) in the first half alone.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be confirmed, but even Todd Helton of Coors Field
fame had a couple of hits off the Cowboys last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, we weren't able to put pressure on their
quarterbacks \RBrian Griese or Gus Frerotte\S. As a result, they
were able to hit some big plays in the passing game,'' Cowboys
coach Dave Campo said. ``Offensively, we moved the ball well in the
early going ... \Rthen\S didn't handle their blitz very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who was 7-for-20 for 95 yards, was sack-free for the
third time this preseason. But he was flattened a half-dozen times
just as he released the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys played without Emmitt Smith (calf strain) and Rocket
Ismail (sprained thumb). Subbing for Smith for the fourth
consecutive game, Chris Warren rushed for 45 yards on eight carries
(5.6 average).
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who played the entire first half, generated pass plays
of 24, 18 and 14 yards on strikes to Wane McGarity, Joey Galloway
and Jackie Harris, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held back with some of our goal-line offense,'' Aikman
said. ``We had some trouble later on when they started sending
everybody on blitzes. With more of a game plan in place, we'll do
some things \Rin the regular-season\S to help out our guys
up-front.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until Arkansas rookie quarterback Clint Stoerner was in the
game did the Cowboys score actual touchdowns: Stoerner to Chris
Brazzell for 21 yards with four minutes, 55 seconds left in the
third quarter and Stoerner on a 50-yard scramble after fumbling the
snap with 7:01 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, however, had taken a 31-6 lead when Stoerner, who
has all but locked up the No. 3 quarterback job, and the Cowboys'
backups started making noise. Stoerner engineered drives that
produced 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys use preseason games to evaluate players, but this
didn't keep Campo from labeling this loss as ``disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely nothing went right for the Cowboys on this steamy
night in the Rockies, unless you applaud a preseason game in which
the front-liners are able to walk off under their own power.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys even managed to whiff against the NFL instant-replay
challenge system. There were two challenges, with both favoring the
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Aikman thought he had his first touchdown
pass of the preseason ... but instant replay took it away.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman hooked up with Galloway on a fade route from the Denver
14 on the Cowboys' second possession. Aikman lofted the ball into
the left corner of the end zone. Galloway ran under it. Cornerback
Terrell Buckley was toast on the play.
</P>
<P>
   To the naked eye, it was a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The replay camera, however, showed Galloway's second foot coming
down barely out of bounds. Broncos coach Mike Shanahan's challenge
was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Although Aikman came right back to hit Galloway on the next play
to give Dallas first-and-goal at the 3, the Cowboys eventually had
to settle for a chip-shot field goal by rookie Tim Seder.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the first half _ which took 1 hour, 50 minutes to play
_ the Cowboys' coaching staff challenged a 21-yard touchdown pass
from Brian Griese to tight end Byron Chamberlain of Fort Worth
Eastern Hills in the left corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the replay camera agreed with the naked eye, and
Chamberlain's TD catch against Pro Bowl linebacker Dexter Coakley
stood up, giving the Broncos a 24-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second half belonged to Stoerner and the Cowboys' offensive
backups. It wasn't much of a moral victory, however.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
