<HEADLINE>
PARK SHOWS NO SIGN OF ILLNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park is proof that what doesn't kill you
will make you stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after being scratched in Florida with a flu bug so
intense he threatened the health of his Los Angeles Dodgers
teammates, Park went the distance in an overpowering 4-1 victory
over the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually felt better from being sick,'' said Park, who
struck out 10 and limited the Mets to just four hits. ``I wanted to
keep going today. They asked me how I felt after the eighth inning
and I didn't even answer them. I was going to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a Derek Bell home run with one out in the first,
Park allowed just three singles and two walks the rest of the way
for the sixth complete game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with Bell's homer you just knew he was on his game,''
Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter said. ``Bell hit a good pitch, and we
knew our offense would get the run back. Chan Ho had a fastball
that was just blowing by hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who had a complete game June 13 against Arizona, now has
allowed three or fewer runs in his past eight starts. Park is 3-3
during that stretch with a 2.68 ERA (16 earned runs, 53 innings
pitched). He has been particularly tough on the Mets, going 2-0
this year with an 0.56 ERA (1 ER, 16 IP).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you throw your fastball when you're ahead in the count,
and then throw your breaking ball when you're behind, it is tough
to make adjustments,'' New York manager Bobby Valentine said of
Park. ``He had good control with both pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Park became ill Wednesday in Florida, forcing the Dodgers to fly
him home ahead of the team and go with right-hander Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Bell always has hit Park well. Entering the game,
Bell was 6 for 14 lifetime with six RBI. ... Despite hitting three
homers in his past two games, Sheffield had been struggling, going
4 for 25 on the Dodgers trip to Atlanta and Florida. ``I told him
to just relax and we will get him some help,'' Johnson said.
``Obviously, he did not take my advice.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros hit his 28th homer in the third inning Saturday, his
first in three weeks. It was the 239th of Karros' career, which is
fourth in Dodgers history. He needs three more to catch Roy
Campanella for third. Duke Snider is first (389), followed by Gil
Hodges (361). ...
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's sellout was the Dodgers' sixth this season. Five have
come on promotional giveaway days and one was opening day. The team
has drawn 2,176,641 through 57 dates and are on a pace to draw
3,093,121. The Dodgers have drawn more than three million the past
four years and 14 times overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers do lead the league in one category. Saturday's
victory was the 39th come-from-behind win of the season. The Mets
are second with 35. ... What does Mike Piazza mean to the Mets'
lineup? In games when Piazza has an RBI, the Mets are 38-13. When
Piazza doesn't, the Mets are two games under .500.
</P>
</TEXT>
