<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKY TIGER RETAINS LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ To almost desperate calls for any semblance of
a challenge, Tiger Woods discovered there were many takers in
Saturday's third round of the 82d PGA Championship at Valhalla Golf
Club. So, for the first time in his summer of utter domination,
Woods's walk into the history books must first hurdle some
competition.
</P>
<P>
   No-name competition, some will say, but it's competition just
the same, said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys with a chance to win and I'm fortunate
to be one of them,'' said Woods, who struggled through some
back-side miscues but birdied the par-5 18th to finish a
2-under-par 70 for a 203 total, enabling him to retain the same
cushion he had started with _ one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Bob May (66) and Scott Dunlap (70) share second place, J.P.
Hayes (68_205) is alone in fourth, and Australian lefthander Greg
Chalmers (66_206) roared into fifth. Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal
moved into a share of sixth by tying the lowest round in major golf
history (63_207) on a day when scoring opportunities were
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   The late slide appeared to frustrate Woods, who owned 54-hole
leads of 10 and six shots in overwhelming wins at the US Open and
British Open. Was it disturbing not to have added some cushion?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' said the man who is attempting to join Ben
Hogan as the only players to win three modern majors in a season,
as well as be the first to defend the PGA Championship since Denny
Shute in 1937. ``Given the fact I wasn't really striking the ball
that good, I'm OK with 70.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13 under, Woods is casting a shadow upon players who forced a
mad dash to the media guides.
</P>
<P>
   May, a 31-year-old PGA Tour rookie who honed his game in Europe,
started at 6 under, turned quietly in 34, then knocked down pins in
a four-birdie, five-par back-side 32.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, 37, has the same number of PGA Tour wins as May and
Chalmers _ that is, zero _ and knew his pairing with Woods had
drawn smirks. ``Probably much like the golfing world, I was
wondering how I was going to do,'' he said after matching Woods
shot for shot, something far more heralded players have not been
able to do.
</P>
<P>
   His goal, said Dunlap _ who had previously made just four cuts
in the majors _ was to ``have enough guts to stand in there and go
toe-to-toe. Today, I passed that test.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods birdied both par 5s on the front (for the tournament, he
has played them in 11 birdies, one par), but so did Dunlap, to stay
just one back. Woods then birdied the ninth, Dunlap settled for
par, and the cushion was two.
</P>
<P>
   But crazy things were going on at Valhalla, and the rush up the
leaderboard was in high gear. Olazabal, most noticeably, was
lighting it up with his birdies (nine) and pars (nine), matching a
mark that has been recorded by six in the PGA Championship, 12 in
other majors.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, marquee names such as Phil Mickelson (31) and
Davis Love (34) made moves on the front to give Woods even more to
stare at as he peeked at leaderboards along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Very surprisingly, Mickelson (69) and Love (72) fell back with
back-side 38s to settle into a group at 7-under 209 and out of the
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   However, gentlemen of far less stature in the world of
professional golf did not follow such a route of reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, for instance. Compared to May, Dunlap, and Chalmers, he
has a rich resume _ the 1998 Buick Classic victory _ but until his
birdie at the 18th sealed a round of 66, many were wondering how he
had come into view. The same could be said for Chalmers, whose
rookie year on the tour has yielded just two top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Trivial matters to Woods, who has stressed all week that he
cares not about historical matters, but only about the matter at
hand. As thousands of spectators filed home, many of them
satisified that some overwhelming underdogs had slapped the giant
with some of his own medicine, Woods was headed to the range.
Memories of some back-side miscues were fresh on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 12th hole, where Woods _ who had gone out in 33 and
birdied the par-5 10th to get to 15 under _ slammed a 3-wood left
into trees, recovered nicely with an 8-iron to the front slope,
then pitched to about 15 feet. ``Hit a good putt, just misread
it,'' said Woods, who turned his third bogey of the tournament into
his first double-bogey when he inexplicably pushed a 2-footer
right.
</P>
<P>
   When Dunlap drained his birdie putt, Woods was on the short end
of a three-shot swing, tied for the lead at 13 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rectified all that in a hurry,'' said Dunlap, who had
missed a handful of short birdie putts leading up to the 12th. ``I
felt like I kind of got let off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   He got back on the hook when he missed the green at the par-3
14th and made bogey, but was back tied for the lead when Woods came
over the top of a 6-iron at the par-4 15th. With arguably the worst
shot he's hit all year, Woods ended up in thick hay well left of
the pin, pitched down a slippery slope, but made bogey to fall to
12 under.
</P>
<P>
   As that sequence was unfolding, May was making par at the 18th
to finish at 12 under. The man whose claim to fame is a
come-from-behind win over Colin Montgomerie at the British Masters
was a stunning addition next to the imposing name of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pressure on me,'' said May with a light laugh when told
that today he'd be paired with Woods. ``He's supposed to win. I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove that he agreed with May, Woods reached the 542-yard
closing hole with a driver and 3-wood, then two-putted for birdie
to put himself in a position that fits quite comfortably. Twenty
times he has built a 54-hole lead. Eighteen times he has held it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of players out there, which is going to make it even
more of a challenge,'' said Woods. ``I am going to have a good time
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was arguing with him. Especially the no-name contenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
