<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREATNESS COMES WITH HIGH PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ As you walk Valhalla Golf Club's grounds with
Tiger Woods, you can see and hear those who are magnets to his
hype.
</P>
<P>
   You see their faces, tanned and sunburned from camping out. They
wait for hours just to get a glimpse. They fight a variety of
annoyances _ dragonflies, bluegrass, photographers, reporters _
that might interfere with their Tiger moment. They are young and
old golfers who dream of being so talented; they are young and old
entrepreneurs who dream of being so rich; they are young and old
women who dream of being his girlfriend. If Tiger were to win every
major for the next decade, it wouldn't be enough to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   But the more you walk with Woods, the more you detect another
strong Valhalla emotion. Fatigue. Tiger Fatigue. There are
thousands of people who are simply tired of him.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of his commercials. Tired of his privileges (he is flanked
by two Jefferson County police officers at all times). Tired of the
way his language has become a sports cliche (remember, he was the
first to say, ``I didn't have my `A' game today''). And,
especially, tired of the way he has turned golf into a soap opera.
That is, you can watch for a few minutes and predict the ending.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the same Sunday during the final round of the PGA
Championship. Woods has a one-stroke lead over Scott Dunlap and Bob
May. He will be paired with May, who used to live a 20-minute drive
from the Woods home in California. When May left college, one of
his first sponsors was actor Joe Pesci. His mother is employed by
the PGA of southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap played with Woods Saturday and will tee off 10 minutes
before him Sunday. He is a thoughtful man who proudly praises
anyone from Ronald Reagan to Woods to Buddy Guy.
</P>
<P>
   May and Dunlap are great stories. They just won't be holding the
$900,000 first-place check. Woods will. When you can make
definitive statements like that in sports, it bothers some people.
The magic in our games is supposed to be rooted in the mystery of
them. But 24-year-old Tiger Woods has become the modern equivalent
of the old Yankees and Celtics. Just fill in the appropriate date
on the championship trophies, because you know they are going to
win them.
</P>
<P>
   That will be the story Sunday, and the contrarians will be
prepared. Dunlap heard some of them Saturday as he walked with
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I heard my name called as much as Tiger's,'' he
said. ``Not everyone wants the favorite. There is always the
rooting for the underdog, but I think the people could feed on the
fact that I was hanging in there and playing well (a 2-under-par
70). And then I fed off them. So it was just a nice relationship
going there.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woods had his own relationships going. One young man
motioned for a policeman to meet him at the ropes lining the
fairways. When the officer arrived, the young man said, ``Can't you
talk to Tiger and ask him to hook a brother up with an autograph?''
The officer said no and went back to protecting Woods. As he stood
there, he heard many fans who were ready to see something new.
Woods was asked about that after his 2-under 70 _ his version of a
bad day. He was asked if he felt like Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm that big, that muscular,'' he said. ``From
the size of Goliath, from what they tell in fairy tales, he is a
pretty big guy. I'm only 6 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious Woods didn't like the question. So he was asked
if he could sense the upset vibe, raging like a groundswell, around
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``People, I think, have an incessant need to yell and be heard,
whether they are yelling for me or yelling for Scott or for Bob or
whomever is playing. They just have the incessant need to yell. I
guess their vocal cords just need to be tested,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods knows he will hear from them again Sunday, for several
reasons. There are purists who don't want to see him threaten the
47-year-old record of Ben Hogan. There are those who like rooting
against corporations and, let's face it, with Nike outfitting him
and Buick taking care of his wheels, Woods is quite a
representative of corporate America. (The only problem I have with
that is this: Tiger is too young for Buick. I haven't seen too many
24-year-olds driving new Buicks. Have you?)
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural some players have tired of Woods. They aren't
irritated with the man as much as they are with the attention he is
given. They are asked about him constantly in interview sessions,
with some questions bordering on insulting, such as, ``Are you
intimidated by Tiger?'' With the emergence of Woods, there has been
less television time for other golfers on the Tour, unless those
golfers are fortunate enough to be in Woods's group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wishes of some anti-Tiger people, Woods will win his
third major this year. He will do it because Saturday was the day
to beat him, and no one could do it. Dunlap missed 4- and 5-foot
putts. Jose Maria Olazabal torched the course with a 63 and is
still four shots behind. May played well, and he will play with
Woods Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After all that, look who is still in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic rises and collapses are both marketable, so the Tiger
backlash is not surprising. But it's a waste of time. As Woods
said, the only thing screaming will change is the screamer's vocal
cords. Sunday, at least, the leaderboard will remain intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
