<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-OLAZABAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL BEAMING AFTER 63 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ For so many months, so many tournaments, so
many rounds of golf, the pleasant smile was missing. Scowls, looks
of befuddlement, and slams of the golf club had taken its place.
</P>
<P>
   Golf, a game he had played with such success for nearly 15
years, had become difficult for Jose Maria Olazabal. ``The
confidence was gone,'' said the 34-year-old Spaniard, whose silky
skills had earned him his second Masters victory in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, but not forgotten, because what Olazabal did Saturday
pumped fuel into a spirit that had been a huge part of the game
since the Ryder Cup Matches of 1987, when he splashed upon the
world golf stage. In Saturday's third round of the PGA Championship
at Valhalla Golf Club, Olazabal posted the lowest score in major
golf history _ a brilliant 9-under-par 63. From hanging over the
cut line after his 76 Thursday, Olazabal this morning finds himself
just four shots behind Tiger Woods, tied for sixth at 9-under 203.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking to find more or less the same game as I had
yesterday,'' said Olazabal, in reference to Friday's 69 that
secured him a spot into the weekend. ``Obviously, as the round went
on, I liked my chances a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Six others have shot 63 in a PGA Championship; 12 others have
posted that number in either the Masters, US Open, or British Open.
No wonder Olazabal, whose woeful work with the driver rendered him
a part-time player at last September's Ryder Cup matches, was
gushing.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied the par-5 second, then made three more birdies to get
to the turn in 32. Nice, but on a day when Franklin Langham would
go out in 31 and others would jump out of the gate just as quickly,
Olazabal didn't have anyone looking through the record books. He
was, after all, just 4 under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just relaxed today,'' he said. ``I was playing with
Blaine (McCallister) and he speaks Spanish, so we were relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   You may find players taking Spanish lessons and begging for
spots with McCallister because Olazabal put on a clinic on the
back. He hit every fairway (13 of 14 on the day) and every green
(15 total) coming in, made five more birdies, including four
straight starting at the par-4 12th, and shot 31.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing to think that this is a guy who shot 81 last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just confidence,'' said Olazabal, who needed just 24 putts,
though quite honestly his crisp, dead-on iron play had him in range
the entire backside. It brought back memories of the 61 he shot at
par-70 Firestone at the World Series of Golf in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this one was as good as that,'' said Olazabal, who won
that tournament by 12 shots. Can he do it again? Shoot another 63
and overtake Woods? ``I think 18 under has a chance,'' he said,
laughing. ``But it is not certain, that is for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
