u s BC-BOX-HAMED-SANCHEZ-BOS     08-20 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HAMED-SANCHEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMED MAKES STAND, TKO'S SANCHEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION, Conn. _ The Prince still
reigns, but it was a hard reign Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   World Boxing Organization featherweight champion Prince Naseem
Hamed hammered out Augie Sanchez with a vicious right-left-right
combination at 2:34 of the fourth round at the Bingo Hall at
Foxwoods Casino. Sanchez was out before he hit the floor, but in
the rounds before he was knocked senseless, Sanchez dropped Hamed
once, wobbled him several times, bloodied his mouth, put a mouse
under his right eye, left a nasty welt under the left, and showed
Hamed to be a flawed diamond at best.
</P>
<P>
   Despite finding himself in the toughest fight of his career,
Hamed never wavered in his search for the perfect opening, however,
and when it came he exploded three punches off Sanchez's face that
drove him to the floor. Referee Michael Ortega knew instinctively
what he had seen. He grabbed Hamed, signalling the fight was over
even though Sanchez was valiantly trying to get up.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Sanchez was up, but his eyes were dead and staring
into a crowd he could not see. Seconds later, Sanchez slumped back
to the floor, one body part at a time, and lay nearly motionless
for long minutes as doctors administered to him. Finally, he came
to, but he still was carried from the ring on a stretcher, a
precautionary measure that made clear the fierce punching power of
the tiny man from Sheffield, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanchez was very lethargic in his responses,'' said ringside
physician Michael Schwartz. ``He was talking slurred. He had some
abnormal neurological responses in the pupils.''
</P>
<P>
   That will happen to you when the tiny Yemeni battler blasts you.
It is why Hamed, despite his many flaws, is 35-0 with 31 knockouts.
But those flaws are also why Sanchez (26-2) was rocking him and
knocking him about with the kind of authority that has to make
Hamed's family management team reconsider proposed fights with
Marco Antonio Barrera and Erik Morales, heavyhanded world champions
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Within three rounds, Sanchez had twice dropped Hamed, although
none was called a knockdown for reasons no one but Ortega could
understand. Sanchez rocked Hamed a third time as well, in the
second round. That Sanchez got no official credit for those
knockdowns was baffling to those who watched, because usually when
one is hit in the head and falls to the floor it is defined as a
knockdown. But apparently not when fistic royalty is involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my feet were off balance, but I thought he should have
gotten the knockdown,'' even Hamed conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's mouth was bloodied as well by then, and although he was
smiling, he was smiling with a face that had a nasty welt under the
right eye. Yet the powerful featherweight was doing damage to
Sanchez as well every round, and by the end of those three rounds,
Sanchez's face was swelling and bloodied and he was clearly
laboring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell when I hit him with my right hook, it really hurt
him,'' Hamed said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when those rights came in a roaring stream with a
left in between them. When they do, people tend to go down. And
that was the case with Sanchez, who later was taken to Backus
Hospital in Norwich, Conn., with what was believed to be a
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an exciting night,'' Hamed said. ``Drama, excitement.
I just hope there's nothing wrong with him. He hit me and he hurt
me a couple of times, but I got up and knocked him out. You do see
Naseem always get up and knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   You saw it Saturday &UR;  &LR; night for sure, because even when Hamed was
bleeding and baffled by Sanchez's attack, he was always looking to
drop bombs on Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   When he did, the lights went out for Augie Sanchez. But while
they were still on, they may have revealed why Hamed has so
judiciously avoided the likes of Kennedy McKinney, Junior Jones,
Barrera, and Morales. According to Hamed, it has been the fault of
all those fighters who chose to avoid him. But after the way
Sanchez battered him before he fell, it made you wonder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
