<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICSTRIALS-     08-20 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON HEADS US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The sport of gymnastics guarantees pain. Muscles are
torn, bones broken, wills shattered. Orthopedic surgeons call to
order their annual convention with a prayer that American kids
never will lose the urge to tumble like salmon hurtling up the
stream to Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the bountiful, unbridled glee that filled the FleetCenter
with the naming of the US men's Olympic gymnastics team
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night _ with no one happier than senior statesman John
Roethlisberger, now a three-time Olympian _ there was also the
obvious pain of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In all, six men were chosen to compete in Sydney, including
26-year-old superstar Blaine Wilson, the five-time national
champion. But the blueprint designed more than a year ago by USA
Gymnastics, establishing the final selection process, made it clear
there were no guaranteed tickets Down Under for anyone placing
lower than fourth after the trials.
</P>
<P>
   For Jamie Natalie, who finished fifth overall, that ultimately
meant making the team as an alternate. Morgan Hamm and
Roethlisberger, who finished ranked sixth and seventh,
respectively, were given the two at-large berths. Natalie will get
to the Games and could perhaps compete, but he left here with the
alternate's ``A'' stitched over his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they changed it,'' said a philosophical and
subdued Natalie, discussing the selection process. ``I mean, it's
been in place for over a year, and I think it worked. I knew it
beforehand, and I'm slightly disappointed at being an alternate,
but . . . it's not like (the process) was made up out of thin
air.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie's name was the first one called when Bob Colarossi,
president of USA Gymnastics, stood on the corner of the floor
exercise mat and revealed the identities of the members of the 2000
Olympic team to the crowd of 13,182. Colarossi then named the Hamm
brothers, Morgan and Paul, followed by Steve McCain,
Roethlisberger, Sean Townsend, and the show-stopping Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   For approximately 40 minutes following the night's final
routine, all 17 gymnasts were held together in a waiting room well
off the floor while the nine-member selection committee reviewed
performance scores and considered the different competitive
scenarios that might await in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   They scribbled on pads, scratched heads, and figured in a way
head coach Peter Kormann said might only be understood by a
gymnastics expert. Sometimes decisions are centered in logic, but
finalized by instinct. Something told the powers that be that a
Roethlisberger-Morgan Hamm ticket could win key votes _ those of
the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty tough,'' said Kormann, describing the selection process
that by definition defines lives and breaks hearts. ``It's a
difficult decision, and no one wants to make it, but we feel we've
assembled the best team possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Roethlisberger, who overcame major knee surgery to return to
competition, wept when his name was called. He badly botched
Thursday's preliminary round, scoring 12th, and began
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's finals lodged in seventh place. He needed to
string together a bunch of 9's, and he knew even that might not be
enough to turn heads. He stood up to the challenge, cranking off
marks of 9.45 (floor exercise), 9.475 (pommel horse), 9.675
(rings), 9.40 (vault), 9.425 (parallel bars), and 9.625 (high bar).
The old man was sailing to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the heart and soul of this team,'' said Townsend,
thrilled over Roethlisberger's inclusion. ``We need him on this
team, I'll tell you right now. If we're down, he'll bring us up.
He's like the father of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, though, Wilson is the star. He was first in
the prelims and finals at the nationals, and he repeated the feat
here in the Hub. Kormann calls him the Tiger Woods of gymnastics,
and he is convinced Wilson could win the all-around competition at
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Pete talks a lot,'' said the selectively brash Wilson.
``I don't like to think what he talks about.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson finished his day by sticking his landing on a vault that
earned a 9.95. His low mark for the day was a pair of 9.65s on the
pommel horse and vault. He's the closest thing the US men have had
to Mary Lou Retton. He only lacks the high-wattage smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to win,'' said Wilson. ``I think we are
going to win it all. Look at the amount of talent we had standing
on the floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
