<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAVE A BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution discovered a winning formula
and revived their playoff hopes Saturday. They stifled Tampa Bay's
Carlos Valderrama and Mamadou ``Big Mama'' Diallo, the most potent
scoring combination in Major League Soccer, taking a 2-1 victory
with an 88th-minute goal by Imad Baba.
</P>
<P>
   Baba collected a clearance about 22 yards from the goal, calmly
controlled it, and slammed a shot just inside the left post for his
first goal in the run of play since May 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, who play host to Columbus Saturday, are tied
with Colorado for the eighth and final playoff spot with 36 points,
with five matches remaining. Tampa Bay has 47 points and is in
first place in the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think quickly in those situations,'' Baba said.
``The ball came out of the defense and I had to decide whether to
hit it or cross it. I went for the shot and caught (Scott) Garlick
standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Garlick, the Mutiny goalkeeper, was not often standing still in
this match. But though Garlick made some excellent stops, this shot
was nearly impossible to save.
</P>
<P>
   The play capped an unlikely sequence of events, ending with a
ping-ponged clearance. Substitute Jamar Beasley bounced a shot
across the goal area, and Garlick attempted to make a diving stop
with his left hand. The shot went over the end line, and linesman
Richard Eddy signaled a corner kick. Garlick disputed the call, and
continued to do so after the match, pursuing the refereeing crew
led by Richard Heron.
</P>
<P>
   John Harkes's corner was cleared to Joe Franchino, who sent in a
right-footed shot that was cleared by Ritchie Kotschau. The
clearance was deflected by Steve Trittschuh, directly to Baba.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution concentrated more on stopping the Mutiny than on
creating offense for most of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Eyre, playing only his second complete game and first game
since July 22, kept Diallo, who was playing as a lone striker, from
adding to his MLS-leading total of 22 goals. Leonel Alvarez helped
stifle Valderrama. And the Mutiny had little else to offer,
partially because of fatigue caused by a 2-1 overtime victory over
the MetroStars Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution closed down the midfield. But the Mutiny seemed
capable of closing the defense, as central defenders Joe Addo and
Trittschuh were seldom threatened until late in the match. The
Revolution's best offensive weapon was the dribbling of Wolde
Harris, who extended his scoring streak to six games, one short of
the league record set in 1997 by Raul Diaz Arce of D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Harris converted his 14th goal of the season after Eric Wynalda
laid off a pass from the penalty arc to Baba on the right. Baba's
cross found Harris unmarked after Trittschuh had dropped off at the
far post.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, though, quickly squandered their advantage, as
they had in a 2-1 overtime loss to the MetroStars last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny earned a free kick in the 78th minute. Harkes and the
Mutiny's Manny Lagos clashed while Lagos was on the ground, leading
to a chaotic scene in which Diallo and Franchino also clashed and
Diallo was cautioned. Valderrama then confronted Rusty Pierce in
attempting to take the free kick, and nearly four minutes after the
foul the kick was finally executed. Valderrama curled the ball to
the far post, and Steve Ralston headed in the tying goal in the
81st minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``One mistake almost cost us the game,'' Revolution coach
Fernando Clavijo said. ``It's mind-boggling to me. It was the same
thing as in New York, and we paid the price for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo's substitutions, though, paid off. Wynalda provided a
reliable presence in the middle of the attack, and Beasley added
dynamism on the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult game because of the pressure they
placed on us,'' Valderrama said. ``Diallo did not score because
they marked him well and they marked me well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
