<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS HOPE TO GET EVEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks plan to get back to
team basketball, the very thing that got them this far, and the
very thing that was missing from the opener of the WNBA Western
Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's about survival now.
</P>
<P>
   After being the aggressors in the regular season, the Sparks
backed themselves up in a corner with their 77-56 devastating loss
to the three-time defending champion Houston Comets Thursday. Now
they must perform today in Game 2 of the best-of-three series or
look ahead to next year. Game 3 will be played at 7 p.m. Monday if
the Sparks even the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win Sunday,'' Sparks coach Michael Cooper, who will
be receive the WNBA Coach of the Year award before the game. ``Once
we do that then we can worry about Monday. We know that they (the
Comets) are going to come in (prepared) because they are the
champions and they know what winning is all about. I like our
chances, having to have a chance to win Sunday at home rather than
down in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The roles are reversed now. In the conference finals last
season, the Sparks won the first game at home and dropped the next
two in Houston. But even for them to do the same they must play a
better brand of basketball than they did Thursday. It was the
Sparks sloppiest game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot ourselves in the foot,'' Cooper said. ``We had 23
turnovers and that is so uncharacteristic of us. Throwing the
basketball away no one is going to get into their rhythm. We were
getting shots. The ones that we were getting were the ones that we
had to take because we felt like it was our time to shoot. And that
is not like us. I think we had something like 10 or 11 assists.
We're the No. 1 team in the league as far as assists. We have to
take care of the basketball. We're a very unselfish team. When
we're doing that we're on top of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the game tape was difficult, Sparks center Lisa Leslie
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe that for such a big game that we came out
with such a lack of intensity and that was probably the most
disappointing part,'' she said. ``It would have been one thing if
we would have made the effort, but we were in quicksand for some
reason. I mean everybody. We just have to come out with much better
intensity level and play harder and get after the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the lack of intensity, part of the problem was allowing
the league's most valuable player Sheryl Swoopes ``to get into her
rhythm,'' Cooper said. Swoopes was 5 of 8 for 10 points in the
first half and finished with a game-high of 22. Also Cynthia Cooper
scored 15 of her 21 points in the first half. He said the Sparks
must contain at least one of the Comets' Big Three players, which
includes Tina Thompson, in order to win.
</P>
<P>
   Houston coach Van Chancellor declined to say what the Comets did
different defensively, but they were doubling down on Leslie and
DeLisha Milton in the low post and doing a great job of setting up
traps. The Sparks shot 36 percent from the field; well below the 44
percent they shot in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said the Sparks loss was definitely a wakeup call for
them and expects a more competitive game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned. I think L.A. has a lot of pride,'' Chancellor
said. ``They will play hard, but I also think we'll play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks guard Tamecka Dixon, one of many who struggled
offensively, going 1 of 9 from the field, said the way to even the
series is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at it it's a very basic thing that we need to do
- control the boards, execute our offense and keep the turnovers
down,'' Dixon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
