<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS UGLY, BUT IT WAS JUST AN EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Cowboys were pushing it last night. Pushing
extremely close to the bare-minimum limits of how NFL exhibitions
must be judged and defined.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of a major injury to a major player (and the Cowboys
escaped again in that area), nothing that happens in the preseason
can normally be classified as a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   This stuff just doesn't matter, be it good or bad. August brings
us such a weak imitation of the real thing, it almost makes a
mockery of where the NFL will be headed by Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   A skinny return man/receiver named Darran Hall has about as much
chance of making the Cowboys' final cut as Jerry Hall _ you know,
the tall lady from Mesquite. The former Mrs. Jagger, to be exact.
But that was Darran last night, fumbling the opening kickoff to set
up a Broncos' touchdown, and then proved the first one was no fluke
by also fumbling the next kickoff to set up a field goal. Jerry
couldn't have done any worse, yet Darran wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Even by exhibition standards, this was a disorganized mess that
despite denials all around, is certain to cause a tad of self-doubt
at Valley Ranch, be it the coaching staff or the players.
</P>
<P>
   A disaster? Only the exhibition label prevents that kind of an
over-reaction. But the Cowboys came in here with every intention of
using the next-to-last preseason warmup as the traditional dress
rehearsal. Instead, they were undressed on offense, on defense and
on special teams. A total failure, you can correctly call it. But
keep repeating after Dave Campo and me, ``it's only preseason ...
it's only preseason ... it's only ...''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't allow the final score to fool you. This was much
worse than 36-23. With the first units playing the first half, the
Cowboys were behind 24-6 at intermission, and as bad as the defense
was, the offense was more disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Emmitt Smith didn't play, and hasn't in the exhibition
season. But the Cowboys have been end-zone shy the past few seasons
with Emmitt, and that's a nasty trend that has continued without
him now that the old offense became the new offense.
</P>
<P>
   Two sharp drives on their first two possessions left the Cowboys
with first-and-goal at the 7, and first-and-goal at the 3 . Rookie
kicker Tim Seder had to rescue both with his toe. On the second
possession, a guy in a striped shirt did raise both hands,
signaling touchdown when Joey Galloway grabbed a nice fade pass
from Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Denver coaching staff watched the replay on the
Jumbotron at Mile High Stadium, they saw the obvious. Galloway had
failed to ``drag'' with his right shoe, and he had stepped on the
sideline. The TD was overruled on the challenge. But the Cowboys
still had a first down at the 3, and didn't come close to a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Aikman was right with this explanation: ``We held
back with some of our goal-line offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who says Denver wasn't ``holding back'' with some of
its goal-line defense?
</P>
<P>
   If Campo had any intention of giving third-quarter time to
Aikman (it was mentioned as a possibility), he quickly forgot that
after what was seen in the first half. Aikman was repeatedly
wearing Broncos defender around his neck, and took many more hits
than Campo could be comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   Denver came with the blitz, and the Cowboys didn't handle it.
Their last two offensive possessions went nowhere, due to the
blitz. Emmitt is missed in these situations. So is starting
fullback Robert Thomas, who sat out last night with a knee injury.
Both are blitz-stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more of a game plan in place, we'll do some things to
help our guys up front when they start sending everybody like
that,'' said Aikman, meaning in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite was the Cowboys' defense. Little if any
pressure was applied to Broncos quarterback Brian Griese. The blitz
didn't work, and the front four couldn't get there.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, rookie cornerback Kareem Larrimore, in particular,
took a pass-coverage beating. A couple of old pros, Rod Smith and
Ed McCaffrey, repeatedly went right at Larrimore, and schooled him
with no mercy. But with the lack of pressure on Griese, Larrimore
became a sitting duck back there. Next question, with answer still
pending: Was the kid's confidence shattered?
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the repeated breakdowns on special teams, and it was an
evening that had disaster written all over it. Except, of course,
that exhibition games don't count. Don't count for anything.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only consolation for the Cowboys.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
