<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7067 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     08-20 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT GETS PERFECT SCORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
(Editors: Van Nuys is an area of Los Angeles.) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a lot of baloney, Kim Todd says, this notion
that kids from lower economic neighborhoods somehow won't receive
the primary education to compete academically with kids who go to
schools in more well-heeled areas.
</P>
<P>
   She'll put her kids from a United Nations mix of families living
in Van Nuys up against the kids from Beverly Hills 90210 any day,
especially that little girl from Trinidad in her second-grade
class.
</P>
<P>
   Her name's Kirsten Pierre and she's perfect _ the smartest
first-grader in the country in math and reading, according to the
Stanford 9 Achievement Test given to California's public school
kids last year.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't miss one question.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine questions in math, 69 right answers. One hundred and
six questions in reading, 106 right answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means 99.9 percent of the nation's first-graders are
below her,'' says Todd, her teacher at Valerio Primary Center _ a
new first- and second-grade school that opened last October because
the primary grades were getting too crowded at nearby Valerio
Elementary School and education leaders believed smaller schools
with only younger kids would produce smarter kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``From every school district in the country, Kirsten's at the
very top, the best,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a kid, now 7, who walks some pretty mean streets in
Van Nuys to get to school every day.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten's a quiet little girl, Todd says. Most of her kids are.
When you have eight different languages being spoken in your
classroom, kids tend to listen a little harder to learn the one
they know they'll need to learn most English.
</P>
<P>
   It bothers this 24-year veteran teacher when people shake their
heads and say what a shame it is. How will these kids ever compete?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's baloney,'' she says. ``I've taught in public and private
schools, and kids are kids. It's how they're taught, and what goes
on in that classroom when the doors are closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the kids are motivated to learn, they'll learn. And these
kids are very motivated. They're incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a little girl from Trinidad to score higher in math and
reading than all the other first-graders in this country, there has
to be a little something extra going on.
</P>
<P>
   That you find inside the home Margaret and Lucien Pierre worked
so hard to buy last year just off Sepulveda Boulevard and Vanowen
Avenue in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to instill in all our three children that
education is very important,'' said Margaret, who was a
schoolteacher in Trinidad for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised in a family with 10 children, six girls and four
boys. My mother told her daughters don't wait to be married, for a
man to take care of you. You take care of yourself. Get an
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we did, every one of us,'' she said. ``I want that same
thing for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't expect it by just saying the words, this mother
says. You have to back them up with action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go inside the classroom, and see what is going on,
even if it's only five minutes a week,'' Margaret says.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten's mom spends a heck of a lot more time than five minutes
a week inside her classroom, Kim says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes in at least once a week to read to the kids, and
she's at school volunteering all the time,'' the 42-year-old
teacher says. ``She is a wonderful mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret understands busy schedules and how tough it is for many
working moms to break away to visit their child's classroom, but
she can't understand the mothers who do have the time but don't use
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many mothers who spend so much time having their
hair or nails done every week, but they don't spend one minute
inside their child's classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no idea of what's going on behind those closed
doors. In your heart to be a good teacher you have to love it, and
I have seen in Ms. Todd's classroom that she loves it. And, in
turn, these kids love her.''
</P>
<P>
   The smartest first-grader in the country said Friday she wants
to become a veterinarian some day, but that might change,
considering she's only 7 and, well, things change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of surprised I got all the questions right on the
test, but my mom says she wasn't,'' Kirsten said. ``She just said
she was proud of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Todd's right. It is a lot of baloney this notion that kids
from the other side of the tracks somehow won't receive the
education to compete with kids from well-heeled areas.
</P>
<P>
   They will, with the help of good teachers and parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
