<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEM0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A burger like no other
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMISBURG, Ohio _ At high noon in Market Square on a sweltering
summer day, the faithful are lined up in front of the city's famed
Hamburger Wagon, waiting for their lunch-hour fix.
</P>
<P>
   No Coke. No Pepsi. No fries. Just plain burgers with salt,
pepper, onion and pickle _ made the way loyal wagon customers have
been craving them since 1913, when founder Sherman ``Cocky'' Porter
first wheeled in his iron skillet to help feed his hungry
townspeople after the devastation of the Great Flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's the flavor,'' said 34-year-old Miamisburg
resident Tracey Caudill, who says she's been hooked on Porter
burgers since the age of 4. ``It's the outside crunchiness (of the
meat) and the salt and pepper mixture, and having the pickle and
onion cut just right. It's the whole package you crave.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough so that customers will drive from miles around to buy as
many as a dozen or more of the petite burgers stuffed into plain
white paper bags. Nobody buys just one, not unless they want some
friendly abuse from the wagon chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Endicott, a 57-year-old day laborer, usually buys four
whenever he drives up from his home in Middletown. ``I've been
coming here the last 40 years. I never miss the wagon,'' Endicott
said. ``It's a different taste than any other hamburger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamburger Wagon is the city's ``No. 1 attraction'' and has
been a focal point on Market Square for decades, said Bobbye Sweny,
president of the Miamisburg Historical Society. The burgers are so
much a part of the town identity that former residents who return
to visit Miamisburg ``can't go home again until they've had a
Porter burger,'' she said. ``It's always one of the first things
they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Dick Church credits the Hamburger Wagon with helping him
win office in 1992. ``The owner agreed to put one of my stickers in
the (wagon) window, and I knew then I was going to be elected
mayor, because everybody in town goes to the Hamburger Wagon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Current owner Gary Jestice, whose wife, Judy Ladd Jestice,
bought the Hamburger Wagon from Sherman Porter's grandson in 1970,
will talk at length about the wagon's history and its meaning to
the community. But don't ask the 58-year-old Miamisburg resident to
reveal the hamburger's secret recipe _ one that Cocky handed down
to his grandson and, in turn, to Jestice, who started working in
the wagon when he was just 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it the old-fashioned way. That's an overused word, I
know, but we're not just paying lip service, like that other guy
who's always advertising,'' he said. Jestice manages the wagon from
his home, where he cares full time for his wife, now bedridden with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sherman Porter himself, who earned his nickname ``Cocky''
by carrying his 5-foot-2-inch frame with Napoleonic bearing, Porter
burgers are small but mighty. At 85 cents for a single and $1.70
for a double, they're still a bargain by the bag full, Jestice
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we raise the price, we hear from people. But, listen,
we'll keep the quality the same,'' Jestice said. ``If I have to go
out of business, I will. But I will never cheapen the product.''
</P>
<P>
   James Morton, a 71-year-old who has been coming to the wagon
since the 1940s, said he suspects the secret recipe is much like
the one used by his own mother. ``Back in the days when there
wasn't much food, you put bread in there to make it spread,'' he
said. ``She used to make her hamburger with onion and everything
mixed right in it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1913 Flood, when hundreds of Miamisburg residents were
homeless and hungry, ``Cocky'' Porter, then a painter and a
handyman, approached the local Red Cross with an idea. ``He
volunteered that he had a recipe of his own that could stretch the
hamburger back then and feed more people,'' Jestice said.
</P>
<P>
   When the flood waters subsided and life in Miamisburg returned
to normal, residents found they couldn't live without Porter's
burgers. They pressured him to start selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Porter had no intention of going into the hamburger business,
but ``when people kept asking and asking, he said, 'What the heck.'
He bought enough (ingredients) for 500 hamburgers, priced them at 5
cents apiece and darned if he wasn't sold out by noon,'' Jestice
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jestice won't reveal how many hamburgers are sold at the wagon,
which is open 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. seven days a week (it closes an
hour earlier in winter). ``I can sell as many as I make _
literally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger assembler Troy Brennan would say only that the wagon
slices through 350 pounds of large onions each week. Both pickle
and onion are freshly sliced and placed on an open bun just before
serving. The instant the cooked meat comes from the grease-filled
skillet, the finished burger is slapped together, stacked and
stuffed into paper bags.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rucker, 55, drove his Dodge Ram 1500 pickup from
Centerville to the wagon, where he buys anywhere from three to six
Porter burgers at a time. He says part of the attraction is the
teasing he gets from wagon employees. ``If I say I need three, they
look at me and say, 'Hey, you need six of them, not three,' ``
Rucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Hess, 18, recently discovered this banter on his first
visit to the wagon, after he was dispatched from Serra Chevrolet to
pick up an order for his fellow workers, including a burger without
onion and pickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fixins'?'' the cook railed. ``What am I supposed to do with
them?''
</P>
<P>
   Jestice put new wheels on the wagon when his wife purchased it
in 1970. Then in 1980, he had the carriage frame and running gear
rebuilt by an Amish carriage works. ``These things were not
designed to last 85 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Porter burger was, and it will continue to flourish as
long as people crave something fresh and a little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unique,'' said 23-year-old Miamisburg resident Craig
Suttman. ``It's not like McDonald's or Burger King. You can't get
this anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
