<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SHAKESPEARE0821-COX     08-20 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE0821-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The play's the thing _ for managerial lessons
</P>
<P>
   By Amy Martinez
</P>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach Gardens author John Whitney has
some advice for anyone who wants to be a good leader: All you ever
need to know, you learned in English class.
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare, the greatest of all English playwrights _
whose 400-year-old tragedies, comedies and histories might still be
on the shelf with your old yearbooks _ can help solve any problem
you have.
</P>
<P>
   Want to boost morale? King Henry V shows how at the Battle of
Agincourt, when he convinces his troops, who are outnumbered by the
French 5-to-1, that their small number is to their advantage. The
troops rally for battle and win.
</P>
<P>
   Not sure how to approach a hostile board member or employee?
Consider Mark Antony's funeral speech for Caesar, in which he
redirects the crowd's loyalty to himself from their beloved Brutus,
the assassin. He assures them, ``I come to bury Caesar, not to
praise him,'' and defers to Brutus just enough so that his
listeners never know they're being persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, a popular business professor at Columbia University in
New York, believes The Bard is ideal for today's executives and
middle managers.
</P>
<P>
   He has co-written a new book, ``Power Plays: Shakespeare's
Lessons in Leadership and Management ``(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26),
with Tina Packer, the founder, president and artistic director of
Shakespeare &AMP; Co. in Lenox, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He uses excerpts from Shakespeare, and his own experiences as a
so-called turnaround expert, to teach good management practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare wrote more forcefully about leadership and
management issues than any writer before or since,'' Whitney, 72,
said last week in a phone interview from New York. ``The
fundamentals of human nature haven't changed much. The struggle for
power and the requirements for leadership are much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney says ``Henry V `` shows the monarch's willingness to
listen closely to his troops. ``Othello `` illustrates the danger
of passing someone over for promotion. ``Hamlet `` teaches us about
analysis-paralysis, the failure to create and maintain a strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney draws parallels between the shortcomings of
Shakespeare's protagonists and those of today's business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Macbeth and James Robinson, former chairman and
chief executive of American Express, have much in common. Like
Macbeth, Robinson became obsessed with power for power's sake and
lost his edge by indulging in the perks of corporate power, Whitney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Dunlap, former chief executive of Boca Raton-based Sunbeam,
is a lot like Coriolanus, a successful warrior who is banished from
Rome because he fails to realize that power shifts, and that
military prowess does not necessarily translate into political
power, Whitney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot build a company with a chain saw and ax,'' he said.
``All managers today face the problem of balancing between the
short term and long term. What Dunlap was looking at was just the
short term. He had no view of the long term at all.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Texas Instruments lost out to start-ups during the
personal computer boom of the 1980s and early '90s because they
became complacent, Whitney said. In other words, they stopped
listening to the Jack Falstaffs of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Falstaff, friend and adviser to Prince Hal, the future Henry V,
is innovative and unafraid to say what he thinks. Whitney believes
all leaders need Falstaffs to keep them honest and competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people who'll say 'The emperor has no clothes.' You
have to nurture that, and I think it's more important today than in
Elizabethan times because the information flow is better and the
opaway from the command-and-control thing, which is so
comfortable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, who commutes between New York and Palm Beach Gardens,
where he lives with his wife, Marcia, in PGA National, received a
bachelor's degree in literature from the University of Tulsa.
During his senior year there, an English professor turned him on to
Shakespeare, and he's been a devoted fan ever since.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma native, Whitney owned a successful advertising
agency and consulting firm in Tulsa before enrolling in the
advanced management program at Harvard in 1966. Four years later,
he became associate dean of the Harvard Business School, and in
1972 was hired by Pathmark Supermarkets to turn around the New
York-based chain.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark's stock was trading at $2 a share when Whitney signed
on. Five years later, when Whitney left, the chain was turning a
profit and the stock was on its way to commanding $100 and up a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney said he learned from ``Henry V'' to visit with employees
in the field at least three times a week and from Iago, the valiant
fighter in ``Othello'' who becomes vindictive, to beware of people
passed up for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime an outsider comes in to run a company, he or she
should realize the sharp knives are going to be out,'' he said.
``It's just something that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, who still does consulting work for Fortune 500
companies, said he's encouraged by what he sees of today's leaders,
namely Jack Welch, GE's chief executive, who requires training
programs for everyone, including executives, and encourages
commitment to the company's mission through pay incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think leadership in corporate America is the best it's ever
been,'' Whitney said. ``Just look at how well we're doing compared
with the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
