<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GEM _ At high noon in Market Square on a sweltering summer day,
the faithful are lined up in front of the city's famed Hamburger
Wagon, waiting for their lunch-hour fix. No Coke. No Pepsi. No
fries. Just plain burgers with salt, pepper, onion and pickle _
made the way loyal wagon customers have been craving them since
1913, when founder Sherman ``Cocky'' Porter first wheeled in his
iron skillet to help feed his hungry townspeople after the
devastation of the Great Flood. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS _ The booming Latino population is creating new
challenges in ministry and highlighting a void in Hispanic
theological education that seminaries nationwide, including all
three in Austin, are trying to address. (Perkins, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PET-INSURANCE _ Basel the sock-eating dog has taken her owners,
Erin and Sean McGould of Palm Beach Gardens, on an emotional roller
coaster. But the McGoulds' medical insurance policy on their
80-pound Bernese mountain dog has softened the financial blow of
Basel's antics. The McGoulds pay $297 a year for a pet insurance
policy, a type of insurance that's gaining popularity with
consumers and insurers. In all, McGould said, pet insurance has
covered more than $3,000 in medical treatment for Basel.
(Ostrowski, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVCOLUMN-HOLLOWAY _ Political conventions are over, and voters
are still lethargic. ``Survivor'' is almost over, and viewers
desperately need a new reality fix. How about a ``twofer,'' a new
reality show that would pit the two presidential candidates' teams
against each other in a contest that would decide the election?
We'll call it ``Who Wants To Be the Big Survivor?'' (Holloway,
Austin American-Statesman) 20-22.
</P>
