<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Developments in efforts to salvage
the Kursk, the submarine that sank a week ago in the Barents Sea.
By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-XENOPHOBIA (Dessau) _ Anti-immigrant incidents have
reached a critical point in Germany, particularly in the former
communist east, where a decade of unsettling change has spawned
youths who blame foreigners for taking their money, their jobs,
just about everything. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-MODERNIZE (Samsat) _ Up and down the Euphrates and Tigris
Rivers in southeastern Turkey, villages inhabited since the
beginning of civilization are being flooded into watery oblivion by
a vast dam system. The destruction is the price of progress. The
Turkish government is in the final years of its largest public
works project, an ambitious effort to quench an insatiable appetite
for electricity, irrigate arid land and bring jobs to this
impoverished region. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-COMMUNIST-PAST (Warsaw) _ In an interview, the former
head of the Polish secret services talks about the continuing
security risks of hidden collaboration with the former communist
government. He testified against Lech Walesa, the anti-communist
hero and Nobel peace prize laureate, in a trial that charged and
eventually cleared Walesa of collaborating with the communist-era
secret services and reporting on the activities of his friends and
fellow shipyard workers. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-YOUTH-DAY (Rome) _ Journal: About 2 million young
Christians gathered in Rome on Sunday as part of the Catholic
church's jubilee celebrations, making it possibly the largest such
gathering ever in Europe. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   ORE-LOGGING (Coos Bay, Oregon) _ Logging restrictions in the
Pacific Northwest have hit lumberjacks hard, especially in Oregon's
central coast. But in Coos Bay, they are fighting back. Out of work
loggers are being trained to answer phones for support-services
lines, creating 350 new jobs, and maybe 200 more to come. But that
kind of work is a far cry from the tough-guy work they are used to
and has brought many lifestyle changes. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SPY (Albuquerque) _ Of all the unusual aspects of what
is shaping up to be one of the most important espionage case of the
post-Cold War era _ the trial here of Wen Ho Lee, a former Los
Alamos National Laboratory nuclear scientist _ none is more
striking than the fact that it is not an espionage trial at all. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-FAMILIES (Dateline to come) _ On how the Democrats selected
the theme of working families and how they plan to promote it on
the campaign trail. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-SOUTH (Atlanta) _ Several prominent Southern democratic
politicians have been keeping their distance from Vice President Al
Gore as they begin their own general election campaigns. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CANCER (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ How quick action may have saved
the life of Sen. John McCain. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-NOTEBOOK (Dateline to come) _ Vignettes from the
campaign trail. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
