<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-RDP (Undated) _ Developments concerning the Verizon
phone strike. By Simon Romer.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES-SHAKEOUT (San Francisco) _ Despite falling revenue
and earnings at Electronic Arts, the world's largest independent
video game company, the mood at the company's Silicon Valley
corporate headquarters is one of great optimism. Part of the reason
is that executives believe they have emerged relatively unscathed
from a cyclical, and expected, downturn as the industry is moving
to a new generation of consoles. At the same time, executives
assert they have made key investments they say will take the
company to new levels of prominence. Whether they have succeeded
will become clearer in the next 60 days. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DICTIONARIES (Undated) _ As dictionaries expand into the
digital world, various companies _ including Microsoft _ are
angling to define the future of definitions. By David D.
Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-FUTURE (Undated) _ Disregarding skepticism that the
wireless Internet might never live up to its hype if consumers get
turned off by today's bland offering of applications on mobile
devices with tiny screens, more than two dozen New York wireless
Internet companies have been spawned within what has become a
Darwinian environment for firms solely focused on the Web. New York
is emerging as the nation's center for wireless Internet
applications, financing and advertising. Eager to expunge the
dot-com taint, much of Silicon Alley is reinventing itself,
wirelessly. There is even a new buzzword to describe the scene:
``unstrung.'' By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNLOADER-FREELOADERS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Two scientists have
surveyed the behavior of anonymous music downloaders on the
Internet and have found that rather than demonstrating a ``from
each, to each'' ethos, most Internet users are instead only taking
files and not giving back to their electronic community. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: The digital
age embraces all activities _ even the making of fiberglass boat
hulls. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: E-mail
marketing campaigns: the pros and cons. By Susan Stellin.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSCORP-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Why News Corp.'s deal to
acquire Chris-Craft and its TV stations has had minimal impact on
the shares of News Corp.'s tracking stock, Fox Entertainment. By
Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   AMBUSH-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ It's called ``ambush marketing,''
and it refers to advertisers' attempts to capitalize on a
sponsorship event without actually becoming sponsors. And with
official sponsorships for the Summer Olympic Games selling for
stratospheric sums, it is hardly surprising to officials at the
U.S. Olympic Committee that the Games frequently have been ambush
targets. By Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
</P>
