<HEADER>
A7188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HISPANICS0821-COX     08-20 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Efforts underway to broaden seminary curriculum for Hispanics
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The booming Latino population is creating new
challenges in ministry and highlighting a void in Hispanic
theological education that seminaries nationwide, including all
three in Austin, are trying to address.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching theology and addressing spiritual needs means
understanding the Hispanic culture, history and vision for the
future, which are not an integral part of the regular seminary
curriculum. As a result, seminaries are developing or housing
programs that can fill the gap, helping seminarians develop their
role as educators, counselors and community activists.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Presbyterian Theological Seminary will be home to the
new Center for Hispanic Ministry in a collaborative effort with the
Episcopal Theological Seminary of the Southwest and the Lutheran
Seminary Program in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   With a $470,000 grant from the Teagle Foundation of New York,
programs are being assembled for the ecumenical center. Seminarians
from the three schools will use the program to learn how to
minister in Hispanic communities.
</P>
<P>
   While the center takes shape, the Asocacion para la Educacion
Teologica Hispana, will be in full swing at the Presbyterian
seminary beginning today, having moved from Columbia Presbyterian
Theological Seminary in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The association is supported by 37 seminaries in North America
and Puerto Rico and includes Roman Catholic, Pentecostal, Baptist
and all mainline denominations. Officials said the association
moved its administrative staff to Austin because of its central
location and to be closer to Southwest states with larger Hispanic
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main purpose is to support Hispanic theological education
on a national level,'' said Ebenezer Negron, the association's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the association hosts the Hispanic Summer Program, an
intensive two-week theological and worship program. Besides
offering theological education, the program breaks down barriers
between people of different faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of encounter is one of the major contributions that
we make,'' said Ismael Garcia, the Hispanic program dean and
professor of Christian ethics at the Austin seminary. ``What we are
doing is finding common ground so that pastors can do their
ministry together rather than in competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, which brings together some of the nation's premiere
Hispanic theologians with seminarians, is held at sponsoring
seminaries around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The association also provides other educational opportunities
and makes Hispanic theological books available. Many of its members
also are in the process of writing theological textbooks and
reference books.
</P>
<P>
   Part of its work involves training faculty and staff at
non-accredited Bible institutes, helping the small schools to put
together a well-run, credible theological education. ``We are a
forum for Hispanic theological education,'' Negron said.
</P>
<P>
   The association, which was founded in 1991, is underwritten by a
$1.5 million grant from the Pew Charitable Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
