<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0821     08-20 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who wants to pick a president without getting off the couch?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ By George, I've got it. The ultimate ``twofer''
_ the solution to low voter turnout and the burning need for
another red-hot reality show.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The political conventions are over, and the presidential
campaign has begun in earnest. But if we are to believe Gallup and
other national polls, the majority of Americans don't care. They
don't particularly give a fig who's running, and they aren't likely
to vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   People aren't watching politics, but they are watching reality
shows such as CBS's ``Survivor,'' which will leave fans desperate
after Wednesday night's sure-to-be blockbuster finale. We need a
replacement that will keep us glued to our sofas for a couple of
months, when real series such as ``ER'' and ``Friends'' return, and
we need it quick. Millions still find ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' satisfying, and ``Big Brother'' is out there, but
neither show is as hot as ``Survivor.'' Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the answer to America's political lethargy and couch
potato yearnings: ``Who Wants to Be the Big Survivor?'' This
fabulous new reality show will entertain and amuse and give us a
new president to boot. No revolting animals will be consumed in the
execution of this program. And it has the added benefit of making
me, its creator, a multimillionaire. For that swell feat, I welcome
your kudos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Survivor'' will pit teams of politicos and hangers-on led
by George W. Bush and Al Gore in weekly challenges that will help
determine the grand prize of four years in the White House and
$800,000. (That's how much the president earns during a term, in
case you've forgotten.) Each team will include first lady wannabes
Laura Bush and Tipper Gore and vice presidential candidates Dick
Cheney and Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   To make this work, we need a better host than the ridiculously
melodramatic Jeff Probst of ``Survivor.'' We don't want anyone
telling us in somber tones, ``The voters have spoken. Extinguish
your torch.'' Offered big bucks and a showcased spot in network
prime time, Bob Dole surely will agree to be our man. He's smart,
funny and politically savvy. He looks good in a suit and won't
embarrass the nation when the winner is sworn into office. And he
has TV experience as a star on cable's Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be determined by the challenges, but if the
competition is close, viewers will vote on their favorite
participant. This election will be decided primarily by the
candidates themselves, but the goal is to make viewers interested
enough to pay some attention to their oft-ignored democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore and Bush teams _ or ``Bore and Gush,'' as some have
taken to calling them _ will compete on the campaign trail in a
variety of political and nonpolitical events. Special debates will
feature questions about taxes, education and which state capitals
are north of the Mason-Dixon Line and east of the Mississippi. (If
Dole asks anybody about ``final answers,'' he will be fired on the
spot.) A balance-the-budget-in-10-minutes segment will point out
just how easy ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' questions have
been.
</P>
<P>
   More fun-filled challenges will include a rubber chicken-eating
contest with actual rubber chicken on the menu. No rats or bugs.
That's been done. Speed of consumption and amount ingested will
determine the winner. An obstacle course could provide some
excitement _ a foot race from the Capitol to the White House in
rush-hour traffic, an up-and-down climb of the Washington Monument.
You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, viewers will thrill to hidden-camera
shots of the candidates as they travel the nation's highways and
byways.
</P>
<P>
   How long does it take Gore to cover his bald spot? Does Bush
practice nonsmirking facial expressions in his mirror? We'll find
out as we watch the candidates watching themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the campaign trail, candidates occasionally will be
blindfolded as they arrive at their political events and asked to
guess where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Fund raising will not be part of the contest. We've seen enough
of that already, and it might detract from the relatively paltry
grand prize at the end of the road. Viewers may be asked to vote on
personality, personal appearance and best sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Survivor'' just might be the next big thing in TV and
politics, an ``event program'' for the masses that will actually be
good for the country _ a bridge to the 21st century leaving no man,
woman or child behind, a thousand points of light illuminating
thousands of Nielsen homes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
