<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR OLD DAD IS A ROCK STAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright San Francisco Chronicle 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Flea &LR;  of the Red Hot Chili Peppers writes in Jane magazine that
he wasn't interested at first when the band was asked to play the
Experience Music Project in Seattle. Then his 11-year-old daughter,
 &UR; Clara &LR; , said, ``` &UR; Eminem &LR; ! Eminem is playing that show? You've got
to do it, Papa! Eminem is the coolest, can I come, please?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When the band last toured, writes the rock star, his daughter
had said, ```You guys are old and boring, the Foo Fighters are fun
and great. You guys sit in your dressing room doing yoga and
lighting candles, the Foo Fighters jump around and have fun.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter was introduced to Eminem before the show. The Chili
Peppers did their thing, &LR;  and, says Flea, ``busted out the socks
for the first time in ages.'' (For persons even un-cooler than
Personals, this means they performed wearing nothing but socks,
which weren't on their feet.) ``It embarrassed the hell out of
Clara, but the crowd seemed to like it and we had a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   The high point, he writes, was running into Eminem after the
show. The rapper told Flea, in front of his daughter, that he was a
``crazy m_,'' ``for which I would like to thank him because that
scored me huge points with my daughter. She didn't think I was a
big dork for at least an hour after that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPREADING LIKE STARBUCKS  &LR; The Guggenheim Museum at  &LR; in Bilbao,
Spain, has been such a success, reports the Times of London, that
six cities in Italy _ Bari, Genoa, Milan, Palermo, Turin and Venice
_ have applied to have Guggenheim branches, and a branch in South
America seems to be in the future.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers are squabbling over a 40-story tall  &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Gehry &LR; -designed Guggenheim branch on the East River (in addition to
the mother ship on Fifth Avenue); and a Venice outpost will open in
2005 if fund raising goes according to schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The new museums are spurred, says the British newspaper, by the
quickly growing number of acquisitions. The Guggenheim now owns
8,000 paintings, sculptures and installations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOK LEARNING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - According to  &UR; Tony Hendra &LR; 's ``Gigawit Dictionary of the
E-nglish Language'' (Gigawit; $12.95), a Palm Pilot is a ``handheld
computer whose tiny keyboard thankfully makes typing
stream-of-consciousness e-mail all but impossible''; and Hitler is
a ``World War II German leader without whose crimes against
humanity no chat-room discussion could ever be conducted.''
</P>
<P>
   - The first trick of improving one's memory ``is exaggeration,''
says an antique document quoted in  &UR; Jennifer &LR; 
 &UR; McKnight-Trontz &LR; 's ``Yes You Can:; &LR;  Timeless Advice From Self-Help
Experts'' (Chronicle; $14.95). ``Don't be content to imagine an
ordinary ear with a proportionately sized pencil tucked behind it.
Make your image very large. Magnify the objects in your mental
picture until they are far bigger than natural-size. Make them
unusual!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH  &LR;  - PetsMart is selling Shareables Purified Drinking
Water, a water bottle that includes a sports cap for human drinking
and a detachable dog dish; coconut-scented sun-block spray for
dogs; and GoDogGo, an automatic tennis ball-tossing machine.
</P>
<P>
   - A San Francisco woman who attended a recent Mensa get-together
at Good Vibrations overheard one stroller, browsing through the
merchandise, say to her companion, ``How remote is remote?''
</P>
<P>
   - NAACP President &UR; Kweisi Mfume &LR;  will appear on an episode of
``Moesha'' in November.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Marianne Gingrich &LR;  said that her memoir wasn't going to be a
tell-all, but  &UR; Thomas Dunne  &LR; of St. Martin's, who just bought the
rights _ for a six-figure amount _ told Publishers Weekly that she
will not only dish Newt but will shine a light on other Washington
marriages. ``Women in Washington tend to hang together no matter
how their husbands relate,'' he said. ``This will be all about
those relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: Should I trim or wax my bikini line before I go to the
gynecologist? A: You don't get your car washed and detailed before
you take it to the mechanic, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   -  &LR;   &LR; Glamour magazine answers a pressing question, citing the
research of Dr. Jack Lenox of Rockford, Ill., who ``performed a
complete search of the world's literature'' on the subject and
``couldn't find a single instance of a doctor expressing a
preference.'' It is unclear whether the ``world's literature''
refers to the Journal of the American Gynecological Association or
Penthouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
