</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-FUTURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS INTERNET CASTS ITS SHADOW (AND SUBSTANCE) IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the plates of spicy raw tuna and wasabi-crusted
tofu were cleared from the table of a Greenwich Village restaurant
one recent evening, discussion turned to probably the hottest topic
among New York entrepreneurs these days: the wireless Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the talent?'' asked Tyler Daines, a venture capitalist
who is backing a wireless Web start-up with offices in Manhattan
and Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the killer app?'' asked Gordon Gould, chief executive
of a mobile communications company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why isn't this discussion taking place in California?'' asked
Andrew Seybold, a Silicon Valley wireless consultant and
industry-newsletter publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to all these questions lies in New York, which is
emerging as the nation's center for wireless Internet applications,
financing and advertising. Eager to expunge the dot-com taint _ the
volatile stock valuations based on questionable, pure-play Internet
business models _ much of Silicon Alley is recasting itself in a
wireless role.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a new buzzword to describe the scene: unstrung.
</P>
<P>
   The unstrung are undaunted by some experts' gloomy forecasts
that the wireless Internet might never live up to its billing if
consumers are turned off by the current, bland offerings of e-mail
or sports scores _ served up as scanty lines of text on the tiny
screens of cellular phones and other mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, more than two dozen New York wireless Internet
companies have been created in the last year or so. The rookie
lineup includes Savos, which delivers Internet music and other
Web-based audio to mobile phones; SmartRay, a portal seeking be the
wireless Yahoo; and Upoc, which focuses on Internet text-messaging
services intended for young wireless phone enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast remains the locus of wireless technology
development. And there are many more wireless Internet services and
applications already up and running in Europe _ eagerly embraced by
people weary of balky wired telephone networks. But it is New York
that has become the fertile breeding ground for new uses and
services through wireless hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the impetus is geographic. ``Manhattan has the potential
to be the center of deals between the U.S. and Europe, where the
wireless phenomenon is much stronger,'' said Mark Caron, chief
executive of MobileSpring, a so-called incubator company in New
York that is focused on wireless start-ups. What's more, he said,
``the level of creativity here is unequaled.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is New York's standing as a major
money center. A host of financiers with operations in New York are
focusing on the wireless Internet, with big players including
Flatiron Partners, a venture capital firm that has had ties with
Chase Manhattan and Softbank of Japan. Others, like Nokia Venture
Partners, the investment arm of the Finnish mobile phone giant
Nokia, are preparing to set up New York offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is getting hot very quickly,'' said Tom Kenney, a
principal at Nokia Venture Partners, who plans to move the firm's
East Coast base to New York from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The field is so new and so much in flux that no one pretends to
have firm figures on investments, jobs created or even the number
of new wireless Internet companies in New York. But many with money
agree that the mobile Internet is one of the few Net-related areas
that continues to solicit strong interest among entrepreneurs and
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were among the first to carve out a space in the area,''
said Seth Goldstein of Flatiron Partners.
</P>
<P>
   The New York wireless scene is buzzing, so much so that an
online magazine has been created to cover it all: the magazine,
Unstrung, seeks to blend the sophistication of Wallpaper, an
architecture and design magazine, with the attention to detail of
trade publications like Wireless Week. Unstrung's motto is ``tied
to nothing but the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the cusp where the kids in sandals at the dot-coms
are turning their attention to wireless,'' said Josh Newman, a
former schoolteacher in the South Bronx, who help found Unstrung
and serves as its top editor. ``The opportunity to cover this
potentially huge niche was looking us right in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoking Newman's hope that Unstrung can hit it big was a panel
discussion about the wireless Internet last month held by the New
York New Media Association at NYU. The event's organizers had to
turn away about 200 people after the crowd reached the fire
marshal's limit of 1,100.
</P>
<P>
   Many were employees at Silicon Alley dot-coms who were hoping to
learn more about what was being touted as the next big thing. A
good many others were from other walks of life _ just curious about
a subject that true believers discuss with equal parts grandeur and
jargon. (``Talk spurt'' and ``location-based services'' are two
favorites in the unstrung lexicon.)
</P>
<P>
   Some people in New York's wireless Internet scene, think that
the buzz surrounding the young industry _ including the verbiage _
is risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that the hype level, combined with the lack of
knowledge about the limitations of the wireless Internet, could
turn people off in the same way pure Internet plays are falling out
of favor,'' said Brian Bodell, head of marketing strategies at
Mobile Metrics, a company providing advertising services for
wireless users. ``That's why you rarely see a wireless Internet
company with a dot-com in their name and why many companies want to
show they're not betting all their chips on wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   But certainly some established Silicon Alley Web development
companies see advantages in having a stake in wireless. For
instance, Razorfish and Agency.com, two players with international
reach that help companies develop and roll out their Web
operations, are expanding their New York wireless operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until six or eight weeks ago, we had no concrete wireless
plans for North America'' said David Eastman, Agency's head of
mobile business for Europe, during a recent trip to New York. ``But
now, we're ready to promote a knowledge bleed from London to New
York because this is where the action is.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the pure-play mobile Internet start-ups, New York's best
known so far may be Vindigo, which provides maps and information
from publications like the Zagat restaurant guides, for use on Palm
hand-helds and other portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   The service is not yet a true wireless Internet application,
because users must download the material through a standard,
land-line Internet connection. But the information is formatted for
relatively easy searching and reading on a hand-held device, and
the company plans to offer wireless updating as network technology
evolves.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100,000 people have downloaded the company's city guides
in six months in New York and four other urban regions, making
Vindigo one of the first applications of its kind to show potential
of spreading ``virally'' _ by word of mouth, or mouse _ and with
little formal advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating the technology which will allow content
providers to extend their brand to the wireless realm,'' said Jason
Devitt, 31, who left a job selling derivatives at D.E. Shaw, a
technology-focused investment bank, to become Vindigo's chief
executive last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around,'' Devitt said, pointing to the frenzied activity
in Vindigo's disheveled headquarters in a gutted building in the
garment district. ``We have no time to pause and think about
whether we're going to be a big part of the location-based services
segment because we're already there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Vindigo offers a glimpse of an industry poised for
takeoff, most wireless Internet companies in New York are in the
early stages of development _ ``stealth mode,'' as people familiar
with the start-ups put it. Few have advanced beyond the first
stages of financing provided by venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sense that new applications can evolve well beyond
stock quotes or short e-mail has some people believing that local
companies have a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Connolly, director of Ericsson CyberLab, a research and
development company set up in New York's financial district by the
Swedish telecommunications giant Ericsson, said that ``with the
mobile Internet, it seems the transition from technology to
services is happening faster than it happened on the Web, and thus
the services focus that New York has plays a large role.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the advantage of being close to the television,
publishing, telecommunications and financial industries of New York
is a lure for anyone seeking to hop on the wireless Internet
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   But given the industry's current limitations, there is a chance
that companies focusing on applications for the wireless Internet
might be in for the rough road traveled by many a struggling
content provider for the hard-wired Web.
</P>
<P>
   After all, there are two definitions of ``unstrung'' in the
American Heritage Concise Dictionary. One is ``having the strings
loosened or removed.'' The other is ``emotionally upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ROCK-RADIO-MEDIA-ART-     08-20 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-RADIO-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS MODERN ROCK RADIO GETTING OLD? 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLEA SIMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From New York's K-Rock to Los Angeles' KROQ, FM radio stations
with a so-called modern format have flourished the last few years
by promoting the cutting-edge sounds of grunge, electronica and the
latest hip-hop and rock hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   These and stations like WBCN in Boston and WKQX (called Q101) in
Chicago say that they provide an alternative to traditional rock
outlets, or that they broadcast, as the Dallas station KDGE likes
to put it, on ``the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is it, between all the slogans stressing up-to-the-minute
hipness, that many of the songs are several years old from bands
like Pearl Jam or Nirvana, while others _ like the razor-guitar
blasts from Limp Bizkit or Korn _ can also be heard on hard-rock
stations?
</P>
<P>
   As it nears its 10th anniversary as a format that the radio
industry has assigned its own charts and demographic surveys,
so-called modern rock is at a crossroads. Modern, also called
alternative, is the style that established itself as first to play
new music. But it has begun to sound commonplace, leading listeners
to ask what exactly is modern rock radio an alternative to?
</P>
<P>
   ``The lines are more blurred than they've ever been,''
acknowledged Steve Kingston, program director for K-Rock _ WXRK in
New York, which has used the modern format since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is a problem programmers will have to face soon or risk
losing their claim to the specific ``hip'' _ 18- to 34-year-old
professionals _ audience favored by some advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the modern format has nearly blended into its nearest
competitor, hard or so-called active rock, which plays many of the
same current rap-rock stars, like Papa Roach, Limp Bizkit and Korn.
The overlap in active and modern playlists rose from 44 percent in
1998 to 54 percent last year, according to Airplay Monitor, a trade
journal published by Billboard. More striking, 62 percent of both
categories' top 10 lists were identical in an average of all of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   And Airplay Monitor's group editor, Sean Ross, notes that 15
songs from a recent week's modern top 20 were also on the active
rock charts, which means that any new tracks from acts that merge
hip-hop and metal, like Kid Rock and Rage Against the Machine, can
expect to jump into both formats' heavy rotation as soon as they
are released.
</P>
<P>
   The few self-described modern rock stations not leaning toward
the active format, notably WLIR on Long Island and WPLY in
Philadelphia, find themselves mixing established Top 40 stars, like
Sting and Madonna, with melodic newcomers like Nina Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to program against K-Rock,'' said Gary Cee, program
director of WLIR, which transmits from Garden City, N.Y., and has a
large geographic overlap with Manhattan-based K-Rock. ``And I want
to do a cutting-edge radio station that still appeals to the
mainstream.'' The result is a sound that borders closely on the
existing adult contemporary format.
</P>
<P>
   If modern rock seems to lack focus, industry experts say, the
blurring has a long history. ``Nothing is static in the music
industry,'' said Jim Kerr, an editor at the trade publication Radio
and Records. ``Over time, it's very difficult to put a very rigid
definition to such a thing as a format. The music changes. The
approach changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called underground radio of the early 1970s _ FM stations
playing bands like the Doors in stereo _ became the industry
standard later that decade. By the 1980s, smaller stations began
breaking away from this album-oriented rock format with New Wave
artists like Talking Heads and U2.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, this experimental mix was recognized as a separate
format, usually called alternative in those days, with new charts
to track such adventurous stations as WLIR, which switched formats
in 1982, and WFNX in Boston, which began broadcasting in 1983.
These were small stations, however, playing what Kingston calls a
boutique format and often more akin to free-form college radio than
to their markets' big-money rock establishments.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed in 1992. Early that year, the guitar-heavy
``Nevermind'' by Nirvana _ a band that only alternative stations
had played before _ knocked Michael Jackson out of the top slot on
the Billboard album chart. Other grunge and punk groups like Pearl
Jam followed Nirvana's success, and stations began switching en
masse to the suddenly popular _ and lucrative _ alternative, or
modern, format.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution from Aerosmith and the J. Geils Band to REM and
the Pixies was gradual for many stations. But between 1994 and 1996
several major outlets, notably K-Rock in New York and WBCN in
Boston, both owned by the giant Infinity Broadcasting, jumped from
the old-style rock to the new. ``Alternative didn't change,'' Kerr
said. ``The mainstream moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the music was flooding the charts, the business of radio
was going through a radical reorganization. The Telecommunications
Act of 1996 cleared the way for corporations to own and manage
multiple stations in a market. That change not only drove up the
prices of FM stations, but also created big companies like Viacom,
which now owns Infinity, and Clear Channel, which controls several
stations in cities like Boston, New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Such cluster ownership at first provided a spur for the new
format, as group owners sought ways to remove internal competition.
``Companies didn't need three Top 40 stations someplace like Omaha,
so they took one and tried the new alternative format,'' said
Daniel Behring, the program director of WFNX.
</P>
<P>
   Such experimentation was short-lived. Higher station prices
raised the ante for profitability. And compared with the smaller
pioneer stations, the 50,000-watt powerhouses new to the format
needed much higher ratings and advertising billings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pay $75 million for a good-size FM, you're going to
program it in a way that brings you back the best return on your
investment,'' said Paul Heine, executive editor of the Friday
Morning Quarterback group of media trade publications.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston of K-Rock agrees. ``The landscape changed,'' he said.
``You need to be more of a specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   Because women are seen as more likely to switch to pop stations
_ particularly the increasingly trendy adult-contemporary stations,
which specialize in melodic pop artists like Sheryl Crow and Bonnie
Raitt _ men became the most readily accessible rock demographic.
And most of the formerly free-wheeling alternative stations pursued
them with a harder-sounding, more tightly formatted playlist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the alternative stations have gone decidedly male,''
Kingston said. ``They're playing Metallica and Limp Bizkit and Papa
Roach.''
</P>
<P>
   And what remains of the old alternative in today's modern format
is the focus on new material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stations are much more current-music focused than the old AOR
stations,'' said Behring, referring to album-oriented rock. He
worked at the old-style rock station WSAQ in San Antonio before
arriving in Boston in November 1997. ``We were less than 25 percent
current,'' he said, referring to the Texas station. Now, in Boston,
``a station like ours _ or K-Rock or 99X in Atlanta _ is 75 or 80
percent current.''
</P>
<P>
   That quest for the new may keep the modern format from losing
more of its identity, said Jim McGuinn of WPLY in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's a preponderance of heavy music,'' McGuinn
said. ``But it's too early to tell if this is a paradigm shift,
like grunge was, or if this is a trend and there'll be a reaction
against it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-POPULARITY0821-COX     08-20 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULARITY0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good news for kids: Changes in schools make it easier to be
popular
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fashionable baggy red shorts that scrape his
shins. The skinny arms folded in defiance. The sullen scowl that
breaks only briefly when someone begs him just once to smile for
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Jemario King's gangsta cool body language says it all: ``I don't
care if you like me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Decatur, Ga. resident, who returned to classes
last week, isn't interested in becoming Mr. Popular. ``To me, being
popular doesn't really matter,'' he says. ``It's a state of mind .
. . I'm just going to do what I gotta do anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As another wave of youngsters head back to class today, it might
be tempting to suggest, as Jemario does, that popularity doesn't
matter. After all, the rugged individualist is an American icon.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as most of us wish that popularity doesn't count, we
know otherwise. It does matter, even _ and perhaps especially _ as
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   As Sally Field once gushed when she accepted an Oscar as best
actress: ``You like me!''
</P>
<P>
   Popularity rules. People who play the popularity game
effectively often become leaders in government or business, movie
stars, advertising pitchmen, the president of the local garden
club, the person on everybody's guest list.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Two summer TV shows, ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' revolve
in part around popularity. Each week, contestants vote to banish
one of their own, and in one case the public makes the final call.
The eventual winner on both shows is likely to be the person who is
most well-liked. Another show, ``Popular,'' follows a high school
clique whose members struggle to fit in.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Center for Creative Leadership, a business
consulting group based in Greensboro, N.C., discovered that the
biggest reason that executive careers derail is the inability of a
leader to be popular.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore said last week during
his acceptance speech at the Democratic National Convention that
the ``presidency is more than a popularity contest. It's a
day-by-day fight for people.'' But any political pollster or
consultant can tell you that this year's presidential race will
focus only partly on issues. It will ultimately, as in past
elections, become a popularity contest. People vote for people they
like.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE IT OR NOT, IT MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   It's been 64 years since Dale Carnegie published his book ``How
to Win Friends and Influence People,'' which has sold at least 14
million copies. And the Dale Carnegie Center of Excellence, based
in Atlanta, helps 2,000 people here annually with their ``people
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know how to make people like them have a tremendous
advantage in life,'' said Rogier van Bakel, an editor with the Ad
Age Group, a New York-based collection of advertising and marketing
publications. ``People want to work with them. People want to hire
them. . . . I think that rugged American individualism is a bunch
of crock.''
</P>
<P>
   Popular people don't even have to be particularly good at what
they do, van Bakel said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian tennis player Anna Kournikova has never won a singles
title on the professional tour. Yet Forbes Magazine lists her as
one of the richest athletes in the world, because her attractive
looks make her a sought-after commercial endorser. In fact,
Kournikova earns more each year than Martina Hingis, the top-ranked
woman's player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because she is incredibly hot, she makes more money than
Martina Hingis,'' van Bakel said. ``Likability is the name of the
game in advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Likability is such an important commodity that one company
actually has invented a formula designed to gauge a person's
popularity. New York-based Marketing Evaluations/TvQ uses random
surveys to measure the popularity and likability of not only public
figures but also brand-name products such as Fila sportswear and
cartoon figures like Bart Simpson. A measure of a subject's
popularity is called a ``Q score.'' The higher the score the more
appealing _ and marketable _ a person is to television and
advertising producers.
</P>
<P>
   THE EMPATHY FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   The business world has created its own informal ``Q score''
system. The more popular an executive, research suggests, the
greater the chance of success. A 1996 study by the Center for
Creative Leadership, seeking to learn why some business executives
succeed while others fail, determined that most executives who
failed to advance failed because they lacked ``people'' skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these managers were good,'' said Jean Leslie,
co-author of the study. ``They knew the ins and outs of their job,
but they were considered demanding, aloof. They isolated themselves
from others and didn't have empathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful business executives displayed ``interpersonal
savvy,'' she said. They were good listeners, made themselves
available to others and were supportive of other people's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the work of more senior executives is
relationship-oriented,'' Leslie said. ``The technical skills become
less important than the interpersonal relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the sharpest managers can fall when they lose favor with
those they manage or their bosses. Lee Iacocca, the former
president of Ford Motor Co. and by all measures an excellent
business executive, was fired after helping launch the fabulously
successful Mustang. When Iacocca asked his boss why, Henry Ford II
reportedly replied, ``I just don't like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultivating popularity is crucial in politics as well. Perhaps
no other American president in recent years has been lauded as much
as Ronald Reagan. But Alan Abramowitz, an Emory University
political science professor, said Reagan was widely considered to
lack knowledge of policy and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have popular support, no matter how good your
ideas, no matter your knowledge, you're not going to be able to
lead Congress or lead the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Did you get that, Al and George W?
</P>
<P>
   MAKING CONNECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   But if a person is liked, he or she can often influence others,
change the way they think and how they live their lives. Such a
person can even make or break entire industries.
</P>
<P>
   Talk show host Oprah Winfrey has revolutionized the publishing
industry in recent years, making unknown authors hugely successful
by picking their books to be part of her book club. And John F.
Kennedy almost killed the hat industry when he refused to wear a
top hat at his inauguration as president four decades ago. The
dress hat industry has never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   A popular person doesn't even have to be a celebrity to exert
tremendous influence, says Malcolm Gladwell, author of ``The
Tipping Point'' ($24.95, Little Brown), a book that explores the
power of ordinary people and events to spark social
transformations.
</P>
<P>
   Such people _ Gladwell calls them ``connectors'' _ wield
tremendous power, he thinks. That's the reason Paul Revere, not
William Dawes, is remembered today, he said. Both men took a
midnight ride on the same night in opposite directions to warn
people that the British were coming. But nobody listened to Dawes
because he was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``People listened to Paul Revere because they all knew him,''
Gladwell said. ``He had the biggest Rolodex in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
