<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BLOOM-NOVEL-NYT &LR;      08-20 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOM-NOVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITING FROM THE HEART BUT DRAWING ON THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Bloom is a psychotherapist. She is also a writer whose first
book of short stories, ``Come to Me,'' was a finalist for the
National Book Award in 1993 and whose most recent collection, ``A
Blind Man Can See How Much I Love You,'' was recently published by
Random House to critical praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the traits that led me to be a psychotherapist are the
ones I find in myself as a writer,'' Bloom said. ``I've spent a lot
of time listening to people, and I am endlessly intrigued by
relationships, particularly by the gap between what people say and
what they truly feel, and the gap between what they do and what
they really want.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Maslin, reviewing the new collection in The New York
Times, said that Bloom, in her ``sharply wrought stories,'' writes
``warmly and astutely, with arresting precision,'' about the
tangled webs of human connections.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said her career as a writer essentially began about a
decade ago, when she was returning home from an appointment with
the man who was to train her as a psychoanalyst. A graduate of
Wesleyan University who also has a certificate in social work,
Bloom, then in her mid-30s, was a mother of two young children and
a psychotherapist in Durham, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was about to undertake the several years of
additional training to become a psychoanalyst, she was ``still not
entirely sure,'' Bloom, 47, said in a telephone interview from
Provincetown, Mass., where she was teaching a workshop on writing
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``After one session the plot of a mystery came to me, and I
started scribbling it on a McDonald's box from one of my kids. When
I got home, I wrote up my notes. I had 15 pages, and I thought,
`That's interesting.' I sent a note to the training analyst that I
wanted to hold off. And he said: `If you change your mind, let me
know. Otherwise, good luck with your writing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Good luck she has had: Her stories have appeared in The New
Yorker, Antaeus and Story, among other publications, and were
selected for the 1991 and 1992 ``Best American Short Stories''
collection and the 1994 O. Henry Prize anthology. Her first novel,
``Love Invents Us,'' was published in 1997 to excellent reviews.
And ``The Story,'' a tale from her new book, has been chosen for
this year's ``Best American Short Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   She also wrote that mystery novel. ``When HarperCollins bought
`Come to Me,' it also bought the mystery,'' Bloom said. ``But about
a year or two later, after `Come to Me' came out, I thought better
of it and bought the mystery back. I just didn't think it was good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Maslin, in her review of ``A Blind Man Can See How Much I Love
You,'' said Bloom's stories focus on ``exotic intimacies'': unusual
relationships, unconventional liaisons, connections that take place
on the edge. The title story, for example, concerns the closeness
between a woman and her daughter, who is soon to have surgery to
make her a man.
</P>
<P>
   In two stories, ``Night Vision'' and ``Light Into Dark,'' Lionel
and Julia, a black man and his much older white stepmother, deal
with the sexual encounter they had one night years earlier. And
``Rowing to Eden'' is about the relationships of a woman undergoing
chemotherapy for breast cancer, with her husband and with her best
friend, a lesbian who has had a mastectomy herself.
</P>
<P>
   But Bloom said, ``The aspect of a story that is unusual is often
not the thing that catches my eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Rowing to Eden' came out of my interest in a longstanding
friendship between two women,'' she added. ``And that was combined
with my having encountered, as everyone does, lots of breast cancer
in friends and friends of friends. So I didn't think that there
could be something unusual here. The story just grew out of what
the characters came to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The only story in the collection that strikes her as unusual,
she said, is the title one, ``because not that many people are
transsexual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what drew me to that story,'' Bloom said, ``was
thinking about the way a good mother is devoted to her daughter,
and the way in which mothers and daughters try to spare each other
certain kinds of pain, and inevitably cause each other certain
kinds of pain. I had encountered families with transsexuals, and I
knew I couldn't tell the story from the point of view of the
transsexual. That's not in my range. But I knew what it was like to
be a devoted mother, trying to take care and offering your best
self but grieving as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said that the characters in the stories casually
break various taboos. ``In the world people do break all sorts of
taboos,'' Bloom said, ``although they mostly don't like to talk
about it. All of us have lines we have crossed at least once in our
lives that we would just as soon not mention to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom grew up in Great Neck, N.Y., ``which,'' she said, ``was
probably not the town to which I was best suited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' she said, ``if you're going to be a weird
little kid like I was, I'm not sure if any town would be suited to
you. I was definitely one of nature's observers. I loved to read a
lot of 19th-century literature, which probably didn't do a lot for
my playground skills. From the time I was a little kid I was
waiting to grow up. At 9, for my birthday, I was asked what I
wanted, and I said, `My own apartment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her life eventually got better. ``Like most bookish little kids
I was always very interested in what other people were doing,'' she
said. ``I didn't develop an adequate set of social skills until my
early teens. I was one of those rare people for whom adolescence
was an improvement over childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year at Boston University she transferred to Wesleyan,
in Middletown, Conn., and became a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing has made me less available as a therapist,'' she said.
``I had to make a decision on whether to go on having a full-time
practice or to write more. I now have a very small practice. I
didn't end treatment with people who were in the middle. But when
people ended, I didn't fill those hours. I guess I've had two
careers I've really loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's children are ``all more or less big people now,'' she
said. She has a 35-year-old stepson and two daughters, 21 and 18.
She is somewhat circumspect about her own relationships. ``I have
been divorced, and I am happily living with someone,'' is all she
will say.
</P>
<P>
   She still lives in Durham, ``a very small town,'' she said, not
far from Wesleyan. ``I originally wanted a nice town with a good
school system, and my former husband was teaching at Wesleyan,''
she explained. ``Now my children say, `Mommy, you can move where
you want.' But I find myself thinking, `I like the library, I like
the back yard, I like the garden.' I've become enamored of
small-town life.''
</P>
<P>
   And she remains enamored of writing. ``I'm working on new short
stories,'' she said, ``and a couple of them are linked to two in
the new collection. There will be two more stories in the Lionel
and Julia group. There are certain characters I'm just not done
with, or they're not done with me.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also working on a nonfiction book for Random House, about
female-to-male transsexuals. It is based on an article she did
several years ago for The New Yorker, itself an inspiration for the
title story in her new collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a larger look at people who occupy complicated
gender territory,'' she said, ``as well as other people in their
lives: surgeons, psychiatrists, makeup artists, people who run the
clothing stores that cater to cross-dressers.''
</P>
<P>
   After that book, she said, she will write another collection of
stories. Her love for therapy has, at least for now, been overtaken
by her love for words. ``I hope to be writing,'' she said, ``for
another 40 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
