<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC BUYS STAKE IN IEXPLORE 
FINANCIAL TIMES OBJECTS TO PORTRAYAL OF REPORTER
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society is venturing into new terrain;
it is buying a stake in an online adventure travel company.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit society, created in 1888 for the ``increase and
diffusion of geographic knowledge,'' plans to announce Monday that
it will buy 30 percent of iExplore Inc., a privately held Internet
company that sells adventure and ``experiential'' vacation tours in
152 countries. Experiential travel includes things like culinary
tours and Antarctic cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, National Geographic will incorporate
iExplore's travel information and database of trips into its own
four-year-old Web site, www.nationalgeographic.com. It will promote
iExplore in its magazines, which include National Geographic,
National Geographic Traveler and National Geographic Adventure. And
the society will give iExplore marketing access to its members.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, iExplore will add National Geographic Expeditions,
the society's own tour program, to iExplore's tour offerings.
National Geographic content will also appear on iExplore's Web
site, which will also carry a National Geographic logo, and allow
visitors to chat online with National Geographic experts.
</P>
<P>
   IExplore, which has had its site since February, is backed by
investors that include Soros Private Equity Partners. The company
has had sales of less than $5 million so far, according to its
founder and chief executive, George M. Deeb.
</P>
<P>
   John M. Fahey Jr., National Geographic's chief executive and
president, said the society had considered developing its own
online travel business and had been pursued by several companies
besides iExplore.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Harteveldt, a senior analyst with Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., said getting the nod from National Geographic was
``extremely impressive'' for iExplore and would give it an edge
over competitors like the Gorp.com Web site and tour operators like
Mountain Travel Sobek. ``You can't really buy National Geographic's
endorsement,'' he said. ``It's like the Good Housekeeping seal of
approval.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE LEVERE
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL TIMES OBJECTS TO PORTRAYAL OF REPORTER
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, The Financial Times gave the producers of ``Bull,''
TNT's new series about Wall Street, permission to use its image in
the program.
</P>
<P>
   John Lizars, the newspaper's vice president for marketing,
described it as ``the standard permission that we and all people
engage in product placement: that the product may be used in a
setting appropriate to the product and in no way denigrates the
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 99 times out of 100, that works out quite nicely,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This was one time it did not.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks before the program made its debut last Tuesday,
Lizars said, executives at the newspaper were startled to read in
news reports that one character in the premier episode was a
Financial Times reporter who behaves unethically.
</P>
<P>
   In return for a scoop, the reporter character, Johnny Walker,
agrees to disperse misleading investment information to one of his
source's business associates to trick the man into making a
high-stakes deal.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the sort of behavior the newspaper condones, Lizars
said. ``We had no idea that they were going to interject a
character in the program purported to be an FT reporter,'' he said.
``I can assure you, we took the attitude that this person
denigrated the image of our journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Lizars said the newspaper immediately made its displeasure known
to executives at Warner Bros., which produces the program. The
newspaper's lawyers followed up. In response, executives at Warner
Bros.'s ``were quite accommodating,'' Lizars said.
</P>
<P>
   So, at the end of the program, the studio added the following
disclaimer: ``The character portrayed as a Financial Times reporter
is fictitious and does not imply that Financial Times journalists
have ever engaged in improprieties. The Financial Times is a
world-renowned newspaper and is respected for its quality and
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The glowing disclaimer has gone over well at The Financial
Times, which is owned by Pearson PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our agreement was very quick and very amicable,'' Lizars said.
``This was a misunderstanding that was very quickly resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. and TNT had no official comment. Executives
familiar with the story said they were under the impression that
the newspaper had received a copy of the script much earlier and
had raised no objections.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected the Financial Times character to show up
again in a later episode of the program, Lizars said, ``I don't
think that would be in their interest or ours.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
