<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMBUSH-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-20 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMBUSH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 ADVERTISING: AD REJECTED FOR COASTING ON MOMENTUM OF OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD STAMLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's called ``ambush marketing,'' and it refers to advertisers'
attempts to capitalize on a sponsorship event without actually
becoming sponsors. And with official sponsorships for the Summer
Olympic Games selling for stratospheric sums, it is hardly
surprising to officials at the U.S. Olympic Committee that the
Games frequently have been targets of ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Examples abound, involving advertisers large and small. American
Express, for example, told viewers in 1992 that they ``didn't need
a Visa'' to visit Barcelona, Spain, where the rival credit-card
company Visa was an official sponsor of the Summer Games. And
Wendy's used former Olympic athletes to push its burgers during the
1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, where the official fast-food
sponsor was McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Such shenanigans have consistently drawn the ire of the Olympic
committee. But they do not typically cause an ad to be pulled from
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   With the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia, only weeks
away, however, that is exactly what happened to a small company
called PacificHealth Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   PacificHealth, a 5-year-old publicly traded health-food company
based in Woodbridge, N.J., tried to run an ad in a special
``Olympic Glory'' section in the Aug. 3 edition of USA Today,
promoting Endurox R4, a sports drink. The cost of the ad, prepared
by PacificHealth's agency, Alan Taylor Communications, would have
been ``a large chunk'' of the company's annual advertising budget,
according to Dr. Robert Portman, PacificHealth's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Olympic committee, which got wind of the ad from a
PacificHealth press release, objected. And on Aug. 1, USA Today
decided not to publish the ad. The decision touched off a debate
between PacificHealth and the committee about how far non-Olympic
sponsors can go in their efforts to harvest a bit of Olympic glory
without paying for the right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not very clear.
</P>
<P>
   By federal law, the committee owns the rights, including the
licensing rights, to all the various Olympic trademarks, including
the words ``Olympics,'' ``Olympiad'' and ``Paralympic,'' as well as
the five interlocking Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   To protect those rights, the so-called Ted Stevens Olympic and
Amateur Sports Act _ the law that charters the U.S. Olympic
Committee and which was last revised in 1998 _ allows the committee
to bring civil actions against nonlicensees for the use of ``any
combination or simulation of those words tending to cause confusion
or mistake, to deceive, or to falsely suggest a connection'' with
the committee or the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, of course, is a vigorous defender of its rights.
The reasons are obvious: According to Mike Moran, the committee's
spokesman, the money it receives for commercial sponsorships
provides some 70 percent of the committee's revenue, amounting to
roughly $70 million this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   No one pays that kind of money without an exclusive, and
presumably that is what Coca-Cola Co. thought it was getting when
it agreed to pay for its Powerade to become the official Summer
Olympics sports drink.
</P>
<P>
   So what of the ad for Endurox R4, another sports drink?
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it features a replica of the three-step
stand where winning athletes receive their medals. The stand is
emblazoned with the words ``Sydney 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has an endorsement from the ``Olympic triathlete''
Jennifer Gutierrez and an offer of free product samples to ``the
600 U.S. Athletes going to Sydney.'' The ad makes claims about the
efficacy of the drink as a performance-enhancer, saying that its
use would allow athletes to ``go for the gold every day.'' Still,
the word ``Olympics'' is never used. Nor are the Olympic rings
depicted.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't matter, according to Moran. ``We absolutely believe
that the ad infringes on our rights,'' he said, adding that the
rights of the Sydney Organizing Committee to the words ``Sydney
2000'' may also have been violated. At the very least, he said, the
ad skirted Rule 45 of the International Olympic Committee charter,
which bans athletes like Gutierrez from endorsing nonofficial
products during the time that Olympic Games are being held.
</P>
<P>
   Portman of PacificHealth said this is nonsense. He contends that
the USOC is grasping at straws, having at first objected to the ad
on grounds that Endurox contained substances that were banned by
Olympic rules. (Moran, the USOC spokesman, acknowledges that the
drink contains no such substances, despite the committee's initial
concerns.)
</P>
<P>
   And though Portman acknowledged that the ad was ``very close to
the line,'' he insisted that PacificHealth and Endurox did not
cross it. ``The copy for the ad was consistent with copy guidelines
regarding product advertising and the Olympics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no such guidelines, said Moran, only the Ted
Stevens Act. And the ad was not acceptable, he said, in light of
that law's provisions.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be enough to satisfy Portman. But apparently it
was enough for USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never comment on what we do with any specific ad,'' said
Steve Anderson, a spokesman for the newspaper. ``But if we think an
ad is libelous, fraudulent or just in poor taste, then we are not
going to accept it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
