u f BC-PATENTS-NYT     08-20 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL BAZAAR HAGGLES WITH ONLINE SHOPPERS; NEW, CATCHIER CD
PACKAGING 
</HEADLINE>
  By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the struggle to show a profit, Internet retailers seek any
advantage that might make them stand apart in the competition to
convert ordinary consumers into online shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to attract customers with a sales tool that will make
them more comfortable with e-commerce and boost the entertainment
value of shopping online, Robert Solomon, from Cos Cob, Conn., has
won a patent for a system that he calls ``haggling in a bazaar-like
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The central novelty of Solomon's design is a virtual merchant,
an on-screen character that a buyer can talk to and attempt to
manipulate in a subtle negotiation that mimics the rituals of a
souk. The cartoon merchant might be grouchy or generous, based on
how it ``feels'' about a return customer or how a new buyer manages
to manipulate its mood.
</P>
<P>
   If the Wizard of Oz turned out to be just a man behind a
curtain, the virtual merchant is only a graphical character backed
by an algorithm. Solomon has designed software that generates
responses to a customer's dialogue with the virtual merchant based
on a variety of factors stored in advance in its database.
</P>
<P>
   They include a customer profile, a history of the customer's
previous negotiations and purchases, basic rules of sales and
business practices, product inventory and brand information. A
customer at a retail site would enter personal information such as
an address and credit card number. He'd pick a product category,
like computers or sports equipment, and then click on a virtual
merchant character _ a computer geek or athlete, for example. This
virtual merchant's mood may already be set if the buyer is a return
customer _ it might not be ``happy'' to see someone who browses but
rarely buys, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Once the customer selects an item, the merchant would name a
price. That initiates the negotiation phase of the program. The
customer could then counteroffer and start a ``dialogue intended to
get the merchant into a favorable emotional state,'' Solomon writes
in his patent.
</P>
<P>
   The merchant might respond with promotional offers, or efforts
to ``up-sell'' by adding features to the product.
</P>
<P>
   During the haggling, the virtual merchant can also ask the
customer questions that help build a demographic profile for the
database, to be used the next time the customer shops. The answers
would also immediately be factored into the virtual merchant's mood
during the on-going sale.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the shopper would try to manipulate that mood by
gauging three behaviors: the merchant's facial expression, the
dialogue text, and the offer it makes. If the merchant is ``sad''
or ``angry,'' its face will convey that and its offer will be less
generous. Solomon says its up to the customer to interpret the
merchant's mood to cinch the best possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon sets this up in the database like a chart with the
merchant's mood in horizontal rows and the customer's potential
responses in vertical columns. Each intersects with the other at
some point on the chart, and that point tells the system what the
merchant's mood will be.
</P>
<P>
   That mood is then combined with factors like the price the
customer is offering to pay, the time the haggling has gone on, the
number of offers and counteroffers, and even the results of the
virtual merchant's last haggling session with a different customer.
</P>
<P>
   And each time the customer submits a new bid, the database
evaluates it based on how it compares to the expected value of the
product, the customer's response time, or even the amount of
traffic on the site at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon also suggested in his patent that his system would have
extra features like an ``eavesdropping'' function so potential
customers could listen to other shoppers during their negotiation
sessions, and a tutorial section where buyers could practice their
haggling. He received patent 6,035,288.
</P>
<P>
   Packaging can increase sales, and several years ago the music
industry lost a major promotional tool when environmental concern
led it to abandon the long, thin boxes in which compact discs were
sold. The wasteful boxes were twice the size of the CD's, but
manufacturers liked them because they provided lots of space for
art, graphics and information about the recordings.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, jewel boxes, the thin plastic containers that
protect CD's, have very limited surface area for such material. To
remedy that, three inventors have won a patent for an optical
technique that makes it possible to see different information
through the surface of a jewel box simply by looking at it from
different angles.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say studies have shown that sales are lost when
customers become frustrated at searching for titles on the thin
spine of jewel boxes and having to flip the boxes over for further
information.
</P>
<P>
   In their invention, Stephen Fantone, Anthony Gelardi and John
Gelardi use conventional paper inserts already included inside CD
jewel boxes. But their inserts are imprinted with graphics and text
in ``interlace'' fashion, meaning alternating lines of different
images or symbols. The interlace images can also be printed on the
interior surface of the jewel box, or directly on the CD itself.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic of the box is made with panels in a horizontal and
vertical arrangement. Thus, when someone looks at the box, the
alternating images come together to create separate impressions
when viewed from top to bottom or right to left, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The effect increases the amount of information available on the
same jewel box surface. Fantone, from Lynnfield, Mass., Anthony
Gelardi, from Cape Porpoise, Maine, and John Gelardi, from
Kennebunkport, Maine, won patent 6,010,292.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
