<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NORWEGIANS SAYS AIR REMAINS IN SUB, BUT FAIL TO OPEN HATCH
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Norwegian naval divers failed Sunday to find a way into
the shattered Russian nuclear submarine, but said that breathable
air could remain inside the vessel, contradicting official Russian
statements and adding a new layer of confusion to relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian citizens prolonged their vigil for the
118-member crew of the Kursk, lighting candles and saying prayers
in churches around the country for the men the Russian navy says
were probably killed immediately after the Aug 12 disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk nuclear submarine plunged 384 feet to the bottom of
the Barents Sea, probably after an explosion inside the vessel,
according to Russian naval officials. But more than one week of
unsuccessful rescue and salvage operations, the cause of the
accident _ and reliable information about the event _ are still
sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   A Norwegian crew, the first foreign divers to participate in the
rescue operation, failed Sunday after repeated attempts to open the
rear escape hatch on the Kursk, the only portion of the 500-foot
Oscar-class submarine Russian officials say might not be flooded.
</P>
<P>
   However, Norwegian officials told reporters that despite what
the Russian military has asserted, the hatch is not too damaged to
be opened and oxygen was still present within the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   They denied reports on Russian television that a body had been
found in the escape chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divers have found that the outer hatch of the rear emergency
exit from the submarine is not damaged,'' armed forces spokesman
Kjell Grandhagen told Norway's NRK public radio. ``They have also
found that there is air inside it.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials had no immediate response to this news.
Earlier in the day, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, the
official in charge of the rescue operation, repeated his
government's pessimistic view of the situation, saying damage was
so severe that opening the hatch through conventional means would
be very difficult. He said that the decision had been made to pry
off the opening with a crane located on a Norwegian rescue ship.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials told Reuters news agency that the hatch
could be opened with foreign assistance, specifically with the
British mini-submarine, the LR-5
</P>
<P>
   ``The hatch is not destroyed and is in a fair condition,'' John
Espen Lien, spokesman for the Norwegian armed forces in Oslo, told
Reuters. ``We think it should be possible to open it with a British
or a Russian rescue capsule.''
</P>
<P>
   This statement outraged many Russians already frustrated and
angry with their government's handling of the rescue operation,
which many characterize as bungled and overly hostile to accepting
international aid due to the still-lingering Soviet mentality in
both the military and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they think this is, the 1970s?'' complained Andrei
Kazakov, a retired army colonel, who along with his family has
spent hours in front of his television watching the drama unfold.
``May God forgive them if they did not exhaust every possible
solution to save the crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, slammed for inaction in a
crisis that has become a national tragedy, spoke to Russian
Orthodox Church leaders Sunday. In an emotional speech, Putin said
the rescue effort would continue to ``the last moment'' in the hope
someone might be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``With sorrow in our hearts and, I do not exaggerate, tears in
our eyes, we are following all that is happening in the Barents
Sea,'' he said. ``The sailors are doing everything they can to save
their comrades.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, late Sunday there was no definite word as to when the
next course of action would commence.
</P>
<P>
   Klebanov said the Norwegians would attempt the crane operation
``soon,'' after their team rehearsed the maneuver on land. He did
not mention using the British LR-5 rescue sub at all, saying
instead that because of the damage to the sub's hull the vehicle
would be useless.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Britain's Ministry of Defense said the British
sub would remain on standby until the Russians had ``given up all
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk was designed as a spy and attack vessel during the
Cold War. Like the Titanic, it was thought to be unsinkable, and
served as a symbol of national pride for a nation hit hard by
economic and political chaos during the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Only after days of failed attempts to dock with the sub, a
situation Russian officials blamed on the damaged hatch, did the
Kremlin grudgingly agree to foreign help.
</P>
<P>
   Former military officers and analysts both say that the rescue
attempt has been compromised by the fact that Russia's military
chain of command are veterans of the Soviet mentality that honored
silence as patriotic and the dispersal of information as
traitorous.
</P>
<P>
   This legacy, coupled with the fact that Putin, himself a former
KGB operative, has filled his government with other veterans of the
spy service, makes it a difficult call as to whether the situation
signifies a deliberate cover-up or extreme incompetence, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Russian (and Soviet) officialdom traditionally
suppressed facts about nuclear disasters, and bad habits die
hard,'' analyst Pavel Felgenhauer wrote in the daily Moscow Times.
``But the total confusion in statements after the sinking of the
Kursk may also be explained by a fit of panic that hit the
military-industrial establishment'' about compromising submarine
and nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a lack of official information, speculation ran wild in
Russia's daily newspapers as to the cause of the crash, with
theories ranging from a collision with a WWII-era mine or an ice
breaker stationed near the Arctic Circle to a missile launched from
a nearby American submarine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Norwegian authorities detected two explosions in the
area last Saturday at the time the Kursk went down. The United
States has said that two of its subs were in the area of the Kursk
at the time of the explosion, but has denied engaging the sub.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Admiral Yegor Tomko, a retired Russian Naval Command
officer, dismissed these theories and said it was more likely there
was an accident in the submarine's torpedo room, with one warhead
detonating the others, a course of events the Russian naval command
has offered as likely.
</P>
<P>
   But, Tomko conceded that the truth would only come slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know for sure until she surfaces,'' he said of the
Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   For relatives of the Russian crewmembers feared dead, many of
whom traveled for days and at great expense from their homes across
Russia to the western seaport of Murmansk _ near the sub's base _
to await word, the lack of information was an additional hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can a mother do but cry,'' Irina Vasilievna told Russian
television at the end of a packed Sunday service at Murmansk's main
Orthodox church.
</P>
