<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEWSCORP-MARKETPLACE-     08-20 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSCORP-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH'S SPINOFF OF FOX SHARES HAS BEEN BETTER FOR SOME THAN
OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's no business like show business.'' At least that is
what the News Corp.'s chairman, Rupert Murdoch, was trying to
convince investors of when the company spun off 20 percent of Fox
Entertainment Group, its entertainment unit, to the public in
November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp.'s shares were depressed at the time. By spinning off
a chunk of entertainment operations, Murdoch wanted to demonstrate
to shareholders that the company's entertainment assets were more
valuable than investors were giving News Corp. credit for.
</P>
<P>
   Did it work? Maybe better for News Corp. shareholders than for
Fox shareholders. Since the spinoff on Nov. 11, 1998, stock in Fox
Entertainment has climbed 20 percent from its close on its first
day of trading, a far smaller increase than other media stocks,
including Viacom, The Walt Disney Co., Time Warner, Seagram _ and
News Corp. itself, which has risen 85 percent during that period
and closed last Friday at $52.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Though the spinoff of Fox has helped News Corp., analysts say
the company's share price has also benefited from other actions,
including the merger of its TV Guide unit with Gemstar Inc. The
stock also got a vote of confidence last year when the cable mogul
John Malone increased his investment in News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   So what's eating Fox Entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the school nurse who is always issuing excuses,''
said Jeffrey Logsdon, a media analyst at WR Hambrecht &AMP; Co. ``Every
quarter, it's something else. There's always a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the quarter that ended June 30. Though revenue rose 25
percent, to $2.47 billion, the company reported earnings before
income taxes, depreciation and amortization of $235 million _ down
4.4 percent from a year earlier. The company attributed the decline
to the box-office failure of the movie ``Titan A.E.'' For the full
year, net profit was down to $145 million, or 20 cents a share,
compared with $205 million, or 33 cents a share, in the period a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's key assets include 20th Century Fox, which produces both
films and TV programs, and Fox Television, which includes the Fox
Network and TV stations, and cable services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have talked as if good results are around the corner,''
said Christopher Dixon, an analyst at PaineWebber. ``Maybe this
time they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Syndication sales from reruns of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
and other TV series should begin to swell corporate coffers a year
from now, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. claims that its problems at the Fox film studio are
over, now that there is a new management team in place under the
co-chairmen Tom Rothman and Jim Gianopulos.
</P>
<P>
   Besides looking for Fox's performance to put a dollar value on
News Corp.'s entertainment assets, the company may have hoped to
use Fox's stock to make acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   There was precedent for such optimism. In 1998, CBS spun off
what was then 20 percent of its Infinity radio and outdoor
advertising business. The spinoff let CBS use Infinity stock to buy
additional radio stations and outdoor advertising companies,
notably Outdoor Systems, which it bought for $6.5 billion. At that
time shares in CBS, perceived as a slower growing network business,
traded at a lower multiple than stock in Infinity, whose high cash
flow and faster growth made it more attractive to radio station
operators and other target companies.
</P>
<P>
   But since then CBS has merged with Viacom, and that stock has
done exceptionally well. So there is no further need for the
Infinity currency _ which explains why Viacom said last week it
would buy back the Infinity shares it did not already hold.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. has not had such good fortune with the Fox spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, target companies apparently prefer News
Corp. stock to Fox stock. Last week when the TV station owner
Chris-Craft Industries sold out to News Corp. for stock and cash,
Chris-Craft got stock in News Corp. News Corp. plans to swap the
stations to Fox for newly issued Fox stock.
</P>
<P>
   An acquired company will want shares of the parent company
because ``they want the ownership at the level of the guy who runs
the company,'' said a News Corp. investor who contends Fox stock
has not achieved its goals. ``And they like the asset mix at News
Corp. much better.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fox's performance improves, the bulls will feel vindicated.
But if Murdoch were to decide to buy back stock, those who want to
bail out may not like the price.
</P>
<P>
   There are several cases of media companies spinning off assets
and then trying to buy back the shares at a price investors do not
find acceptable. Some analysts said last week that Viacom, which is
controlled by Chairman Sumner Redstone, might have to raise its bid
for Infinity's remaining shares slightly above the equivalent of
about $40 a share it offered last week.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone himself has been on the other side of such
transactions. When he owned a stake in MGM Home Entertainment, a
company controlled by the financier Kirk Kerkorian, he went to
court to sue for a higher price when Kerkorian tried to buy back
the shares at a price Redstone considered inadequate. Redstone won.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Murdoch has revealed no plans to buy Fox shares. But
should he decide to make such a move, investors presumably will be
comparing his offer not only to the market price at the time, but
to the bold predictions he made in November 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
