<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PURPLE-BOOK-REVIEW-81     08-20 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURPLE-BOOK-REVIEW-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PURPLE CANE ROAD': BORN ON THE BAYOU, DYING THERE TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the beginning of this new police mystery by James Lee
Burke, a man with the exotic name Vachel Carmouche is hacked into
his constituent body parts _ all clearly identified by Burke _ by a
woman wielding a mattock.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, the body of a state official named Jim Gable is
found, wrapped in a plastic wardrobe bag, in the trunk of a car.
This scene, too, is described with graphic succinctness by Burke:
``He had inhaled the bag into his mouth, so that he looked like a
guppy trying to breathe air at the top of an aquarium.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many other imaginative murders in ``Purple Cane
Road,'' and lots of bruising, bludgeoning, hacking and slicing in a
novel that tries hard to be atmospheric, hard-boiled, charged with
brutality. Set in the racially troubled, Creole-accented Louisiana
backwoods, Burke's novel comprises several intertwining stories of
sexual abuse, political corruption, murder and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The characters range from a prostitute named Little Face
Dautrieve to an ambitious attorney general, Connie Deshotel, to a
drunken private eye, and they are an aromatic group, each giving
off a highly individual smell.
</P>
<P>
   But redolent of the bayou as it is, ``Purple Cane Road'' remains
a meandering contrivance, a set of apertures in which Burke makes
visible about as much seediness and mortality as is reasonably
possible to cram into a mere 341 pages.
</P>
<P>
   He provides a tingle here and there and a luscious sense of Deep
South iniquity, but his book's psychedelic straining for ever more
stylized killings perversely robs it of the plausibility and
unexpectedness that are necessary for genuine suspense.
</P>
<P>
   The main character and narrator will be familiar to readers of
Burke's previous books. He is Dave Robicheaux, a homicide detective
in the sheriff's office in Iberia Parish. Robicheaux is a
recovering alcoholic and a good guy, even if he is prone to
clubbing people from time to time with his heavy fists. He only
does this when he is angry and when people really deserve it, but
he is angry often and many people seem deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Robicheaux's first concern is that Letty Labiche, a former
prostitute and the murderer of Vachel Carmouche, was abused by her
victim for years while she was growing up with her twin sister in
the house next door. As the action gets under way in ``Purple Cane
Road,'' Letty has been on death row for eight years, and her
execution is approaching, unless Robicheaux can find some
extenuating circumstances to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   As Robicheaux interviews prostitutes and pimps, trying to get
something new on the Carmouche murder, someone tells him that his
own mother, who disappeared mysteriously years before, was murdered
by police officers because she had seen them do away with somebody
else.
</P>
<P>
   Robicheaux investigates, asking about his mother's disappearance
and learning of seedy connections between the police and the
Giacano organized-crime family. But soon, out of nowhere, the man
who told him about his mother's death, a wiry pimp named Zipper
Clum, is shot dead by a hired assassin.
</P>
<P>
   The same assassin then goes to kill Little Face Dautrieve,
though he seems to change his mind at the last minute, showing that
he is an assassin with, possibly, a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants these people dead? Who killed Mae Guillory,
Robicheaux's mother? And can Letty Labiche be saved from lethal
injection?
</P>
<P>
   Robicheaux assiduously works on all three questions at once,
helped by Clete Purcel, his alcoholic sidekick who has no interest
in overcoming his drinking problem, or, for that matter, his own
inclination to beat people up. Sometimes alone, sometimes in
Purcel's troubled company, Robicheaux tours the Louisiana
underbrush, winging about by car and by boat.
</P>
<P>
   As the deaths accumulate, everybody seems to be vaguely suspect,
including Deshotel; Gable, a police liaison officer; Gable's
wealthy, semi-invalid wife, Cora; and Cora's creepy chauffeur,
Micah.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems capable of knocking someone else off in this
book, and several of them do so, but most of the murders are
committed by the hired killer who blew away Zipper Clum (after
hacking off his arm with a machete). This is Johnny Remeta, a smart
maniac who torments Robicheaux by charming his impressionable
teen-age daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Burke's plot is as thick and tortuous as a
Louisiana swamp, and while there is certainly nothing wrong with
that, some matters _ like motivation and the trail of evidence _
seem at times to disappear in the murk.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Burke leaves large holes in the logic, but rather
that the degree of mayhem does not seem justified by the stakes
involved. Remeta, the murderer in chief, is a psychopath and maybe
doesn't need motivation, but his appearances out of nowhere have a
Wizard of Oz quality and seem out of place in a novel whose sense
of rootedness is likely to be important to its author.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robicheaux, with a terse sort of solidity, is a man of a few
well-chosen words. He speaks to his colleagues in something close
to code, with about as many metaphors for knocking somebody off as
there are people knocked off in this novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the chance to plant one in Johnny Remeta's cauliflower
and didn't do it,'' he tells his chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``You froze?'' the chief asks him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him set up,'' Robicheaux says. ``I was going to cut all
his motors.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Robicheaux may be laconic, he discloses plenty about
his interior life, including his dreams, his moods, his despair,
his sometimes clumsy efforts to set things right. He is very human,
and he gives this novel, despite its nonstop violence, its strong
moral sense.
</P>
<P>
   Burke also entertains with his knack for the underside of the
human experience and with his characters' jaundiced disregard for
the corrupt human heart.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Purple Cane Road'' is so stylized, so devoted to its own
appearances, that it comes across as almost a commentary on itself
rather than as something real, a novel whose characters genuinely
cry out when they are hurt.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PURPLE CANE ROAD'
</P>
<P>
   By James Lee Burke.
</P>
<P>
   341 pages. Doubleday. $24.95
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
