<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOX SPINOFF HAS BENEFITED SOME MORE THAN OTHERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Rupert Murdoch, the chairman of the News Corp., spun off 20
percent of Fox Entertainment Group to the public in November 1998,
he was trying to convince investors that the company's
entertainment assets were more valuable than investors were giving
News Corp. credit for.
</P>
<P>
   The move has been better for News Corp. shareholders than for
Fox shareholders. Since the spinoff, stock in Fox Entertainment has
climbed just 20 percent, a far smaller increase than other media
stocks, including Viacom, Walt Disney, Time Warner, Seagram _ and
News Corp. itself, which has risen 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN MODERN SOUNDS LIKE OLDIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it nears its 10th anniversary as a radio format, so-called
modern rock is at a crossroads. Modern, also called alternative, is
the style that established itself as the first to play new music,
like that of Limp Bizkit, led by Fred Durst. But the format has
begun to sound commonplace, leading listeners to ask: What exactly
is modern rock radio an alternative to?
</P>
<P>
   MORE TAKING THAN GIVING ON THE WEB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Software programs like Napster and Gnutella have achieved a
reputation for fostering a communal spirit of sharing among
millions of music-loving computer users. The reality may be more
selfish. Two scientists at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center have
surveyed the behavior of anonymous music downloaders and have found
that, rather than demonstrating a ``from each, to each'' ethos,
most Internet users are only taking files and not giving back to
their electronic community.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC VIDEOS ARE GOING DIGITAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of music videos are being produced
specifically for the Internet. To suit its intended medium, the
video's creators use software that crams its saturated colors and
lively animation into a relatively compact file for fast
downloading. The cost is compressed, too, with a budget far below
that of a full-scale music video.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETING ENTERS THE E-MAIL ERA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet companies struggling to retain customers, e-mail
marketing is seen as the next best thing to being on the home page
each time a customer goes online. E-mail is a relatively
inexpensive marketing tool, provides immediate results and can be
measured. But conducting an effective e-mail campaign is
complicated, with challenges ranging from basic privacy issues to
technical hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL MAKER TURNS TO TECHNOLOGY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Irwin L. Jacobs, who became wealthy by taking big stakes in
Fortune 500 conglomerates in the 1970s and 1980s, usually with the
goal of unlocking value by breaking them up, never seemed overly
fascinated by new technology. A company left over from his
corporate raider days, Genmar Holdings, is the nation's
second-largest leisure boat manufacturer, a labor-intensive segment
that has been slow to invest in new technology. But now Jacobs
plans to hold an open house at a factory to show off a compact,
enclosed computer-controlled manufacturing system that can be
remotely operated over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   SODA MAKER SEEN ON AUCTION BLOCK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Britvic, one of Britain's largest soft-drink manufacturers, is
for sale as part of a strategy by Bass to focus on its hotel
business, executives said. Analysts say the company could be sold
for more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   A MAKEOVER FOR FOREIGN POLICY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No longer will Foreign Policy, the 30-year-old publication of
the the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, concentrate on
relations between governments, on military policy, or on the
domestic politics of an important American ally. Instead, the
magazine, remade from its elegant slim size into a bigger, flashier
format that resembles the celebrity magazine Talk, will concentrate
on ``global politics, economics and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
