<SLUG> BC-TV-FUGITIVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FUGITIVE' FINDS A HOME IN SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Daly, who makes his home in Providence, R.I., knew nothing
about Everett, Wash., when told his new fall series, ``The
Fugitive,'' would be based there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will admit to you that when I first heard about Everett, I
thought it was a person,'' the former ``Wings'' star said Saturday
at a news conference in Everett's picturesque Harborview Park.
``When I found out it was a town, I was particularly thrilled to
know it was not in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not as thrilled as Suzy Kellett, director of the
Washington State Film Office, who has seen dozens of film and TV
productions choose Vancouver, B.C., over Western Washington because
the U.S. dollar buys more key grips in Kokanee country. Everything
else being equal, particularly the geographical blessings that
allow the U.S. Northwest and Canadian Southwest to pass for
anyplace imaginable, Vancouver usually wins because of the dollar
thing.
</P>
<P>
   But not this time.
</P>
<P>
   CBS and Warner Bros. Television are putting a checkbookful of
expectations behind this remake of ``The Fugitive,'' which will air
Friday nights at 8, beginning in October. One of its competitors is
NBC's ``Providence,'' which has succeeded in attracting viewers to
a time slot not considered the most attractive on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The producers want viewers to believe Daly's character, Dr.
Richard Kimble, is constantly changing locations in his search for
the one-armed man who murdered his wife, while staying a step ahead
of the cop who believes Kimble is the killer. While 85 percent of
the series will be produced in and around Everett, parts of each
episode, for authenticity's sake, will be shot in You Name It,
U.S.A., requiring cast and crew to pack up every few weeks and
temporarily relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The producers couldn't legally crisscross the States with a
Canadian crew. ``So there was never any thought of going to
Canada,'' said executive producer R.L. Goodwin, who spent five
seasons producing ``The X-Files'' in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Just how ``The Fugitive'' settled on the greater Everett
metroplex isn't very mysterious, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyzed everywhere,'' Goodwin said, ``and there's no place
in the country with this variety of locations, plus a mild winter,
where you can pull off a show like this.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that the ``Fugitive'' soundstage, a converted
warehouse in Mukilteo, is about 45 minutes from Goodwin's home on
Chuckanut Drive near Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   And so Everett becomes a Chicago suburb. The nearby town of
Snohomish fills in for a town in the South. Seattle's Pioneer
Square is Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Everett Mayor Ed Hansen wouldn't mind if Everett actually played
Everett one of these days. (Goodwin says it's a possibility.) But
he's just as happy for the economic boost. Kellett's office
estimates the trickle-down from production of a series like ``The
Fugitive'' is one heck of a trickle: somewhere between $700,000 and
$1 million each week.
</P>
<P>
   The series is committed to 12 episodes through December, with an
option for 11 more, but Hansen told Daly and Goodwin that he can
put up with with thestreet closures and the other minor disruptions
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that you upset our lives for many years to come,'' the
mayor said, ``... and we hope you never catch the one-armed man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
