<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Record chill will greet parts of the Great Lakes and Northeast
Monday morning as a large Canadian air mass settles over the
region. Temperatures at daybreak will be as low as the 30s from the
high plateau of West Virginia to the valleys of central New
England. Under bright sunshine, temperatures will rise 30 or more
degrees by noon. An exception will be Maine where patchy clouds and
sprinkles will form.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with tropical air will be active with clouds and
showers from southern Georgia to the southern Appalachians.
Thunderstorms will erupt in the sultry air across Florida and the
Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A few storms will precede a series of fronts moving through the
upper Mississippi Valley. Slightly cooler air will reach the
northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon thunderstorms will form over the Rockies, but much of
the West will be sunny and warmer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MUD STORM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A barrage of bad weather replete with high winds, heavy rain,
hail and blowing dust occurred in Tucson, Ariz., on Saturday. Flash
flooding closed some of the downtown streets as traffic along
Interstate 10 came to a halt for a short time when the thunderstorm
rolled through around 6 p.m. The violent storm, spawned by
vestigial moisture from tropical storm Beryl, produced winds of 60
miles an hour. The gusty winds initially raised a huge cloud of
dust, which was overtaken by torrents of rain and small hail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
