<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-CZAR-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.D.)  
 NEW HIGHWAY SAFETY CZAR IS A NATURAL FOR THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sue Bailey, the government's new highway safety
czar, insists she is not obsessive when it comes to safety on the
roads. ``I'm not at all an anxious person,'' she says. ``I'm not
compulsive.''
</P>
<P>
   So who, then, was that young mother in Philadelphia in the early
1970s who hired a mechanic to install a seat belt for her son on
the bus that ferried neighborhood kids to preschool? And who, back
at a time before child-restraint seats, made one of her own by
cutting holes in a plastic child seat so that a seat belt could be
looped through it to keep her toddler daughter safe?
</P>
<P>
   Her son, now 31 and an emergency-room physician in suburban
Washington, ``will tell you that he still remembers that he was the
only one on that little schoolbus who had to buckle himself in,''
says Bailey, a psychiatrist, neurologist and public-health
specialist who begins work Monday as the administrator of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested way before anybody else seemed to be
interested in how to make yourself safe in a vehicle,'' she says,
recalling that three decades ago, Americans rarely used seat belts,
and that her neighbors ``thought I was crazy'' to be so concerned
about her children's safety in the car. ``I was probably ahead of
Ralph Nader.''
</P>
<P>
   When the White House announced her appointment to lead the
traffic safety administration, ``my family and friends were all
laughing,'' she explains. ``They said, `This is perfect. She's
driven us crazy for years about these safety issues in automobiles.
Now she can do something about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who has overseen health policy at the Defense Department
for the last two years, will have no time to ease herself in to her
new job at NHTSA, which is responsible for the safety of the
nation's highways, automobiles and tires.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is under scrutiny after the announcement that
millions of Firestone tires are being recalled because of evidence
that they are prone to shredding; 62 deaths have been linked so far
to separation of the treads on tires that were installed as
original equipment on some Ford vehicles. NHTSA has been criticized
by public-safety advocates for failing to properly track accidents
involving the tires, and for not forcing Firestone and Ford to do
more, faster.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey says it is too early for her to discuss the recall in
detail. But without making judgments about the agency's
performance, she says she will review the methods used to monitor
tire safety. ``I'm so hesitant to speak about this because this was
before my tenure,'' she says. ``But I do want to review our ability
to track in a timely fashion, which is part of how we serve the
American public.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not new to controversy. During her tenure at the Pentagon
_ she was assistant secretary of defense for health affairs from
1998 until this summer, the first woman to oversee the military
health system _ she directed a program to inoculate troops against
the deadly anthrax virus despite claims from some soldiers that the
vaccine was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   She has no apologies for the program, which had to be
dramatically scaled back because of vaccine shortages and
mismanagement at the company licensed to produce it. ``I knew what
we were doing was right,'' she says. ``Anthrax is easily
weaponized, it's as deadly as the ebola virus, and you need
protection. We had a safe vaccine. It would have made me
uncomfortable to think that there were body bags coming back that I
could have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, 57 years old, was born Patricia Sue Bailey in Rapid
City, S.D., the third of four children. Her father, a physician,
dabbled in engineering, and during World War II he worked at a B-17
base in Rapid City and invented a type of compass still common in
aircraft today. ``By all rights, my family should be very rich'' on
the basis of that invention, she says. ``But we're not, because he
did it for the public good. I respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was three, the family moved to Washington, so her
father could continue his engineering work at Andrews Air Force
base. Of his children, Sue was the one most likely to help her
father under the hood of the family car. ``I was the one who worked
on machinery with him, whether it was the car or the lawnmower or
the furnace,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She followed her father into osteopathic medicine, which
stresses holistic treatments. She graduated from the Philadelphia
College of Osteopathic Medicine and completed her residency in
psychiatry and neurology at Johns Hopkins in Baltimore. She worked
in private practice in Washington, raising two children. She is
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong, politically active Democrat, she returned home
Friday from the party's convention in Los Angeles. She is an eager
supporter of Vice President Al Gore. Gore, she says, will continue
the economic expansion that is helping to make cars safer. ``It's a
luxury to make policy that provides for safety,'' she says. ``If
you have a sound economy, corporations are going to be more willing
and more able to embrace techniques to make cars safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into a car at the airport late Friday night for the
ride home, she first _ of course _ fastened her seat belt. And she
looked disapprovingly when she noticed that another passenger had
failed to buckle his.
</P>
<P>
   She announced _ only half in jest, it seemed _ that the car
would stop until he buckled up. ``You're being a danger not only to
yourself but to the other people in this car,'' she explained, all
but shaking her finger. ``You could be a flying object that would
endanger the driver. I'm not going to participate in this ride if
you don't put that seat belt on.'' The passenger hurriedly obeyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
