u e BC-MUSIC-LARKIN-REVIEW-H     08-20 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LARKIN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEW OF PATTY LARKIN'S REGROOVING THE DREAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
``Regrooving the Dream'' 
Patty Larkin 
Vanguard
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singer-songwriters ultimately give away more about themselves
than their subjects when trying to document other people's troubled
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Tori Amos' ``From the Choirgirl Hotel'' was a quirky collection
on women bearing scars. The album mimicked her own personal
afflictions. For years, Suzanne Vega has been writing coffeehouse
lyrics about passers-by who mirror herself.
</P>
<P>
   New England folkie Patty Larkin's new ``Regrooving the Dream''
can be added to this confessional line by female artists. The album
is a studied look at the independent highs and desolate lows of
change.
</P>
<P>
   Cut up into clear sections and partitioned by short instrumental
buffers, it's bound to strike a chord with anyone who has faced the
prospect of leaving a safe situation for the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin's autobiographical giveaway is her penchant for musical
change as a metaphor within the album's rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   From the Afro-Brazilian samba beat of ``Only One'' to the
Appalachian folk of ``Hotel Monte Vista,'' she appears in search of
something within each song's structure. It's almost as if exploring
different types of world music were her highly personalized form of
self-help.
</P>
<P>
   Following the staggered steel-blues beginning of ``Anyway the
Main Thing Is,'' Larkin casually states, ``I took the train just
for the view. I took my boyfriend's last name for something to
do.'' It's a strong line that offers discontent and unwise choices
as a continuing theme.
</P>
<P>
   Over the repetitious warped notes and soup-stirring drum brushes
of ``River,'' Larkin talks about the loyalty of a dog in a voice
unsatisfied because it has little else. ``Only One'' purposely
emphasizes the hollow echo of the recording studio to heighten an
ambience of solitude.
</P>
<P>
   The reward in ``Regrooving the Dream'' is when Larkin actually
finds serenity for both her fictional muses and herself. ``Mink
Coats'' is an endearing display of unconditional affection over a
lap steel and guitar roll stolen from the Velvet Underground's
``Sweet Jane.'' And ``Just a Few Words'' is a folk recollection so
rich in small-town detail it's hard to imagine she didn't
experience it herself.
</P>
<P>
   It really doesn't matter whom the stories are about. By the end,
listeners will be in on the catharsis and applying the change to
their own lives. &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
