<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ITALY-YOUTH-DAY-TRIMS     08-20 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-YOUTH-DAY-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SAYS MASS BEFORE 2 MILLION TO END WORLD YOUTH FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In the largest youth gathering ever held in the West,
more than 2 million young people prayed, sang, swayed and got
sprayed with water hoses Sunday at a Mass celebrated by John Paul
II on a hot, dusty, trash-strewn field in a suburb of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The youth Mass closed a six-day World Youth festival timed to
coincide with a Roman Catholic Holy Year. The Italian press dubbed
the gathering ``The Catholic Woodstock'' _ a teeming love-in
without the sex, drugs or rock 'n' roll, but with much of the same
enthusiasm and abandon.
</P>
<P>
   At an overnight vigil held Saturday night before Sunday's Mass,
one overwrought young girl burst through security lines and hurled
herself into the frail pope's arms as if he were a pop star, and he
gently patted her head as she wept on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a rock concert in some ways, huge masses of people
getting really excited, but really, it's about spirituality, not
entertainment,'' said Claire Heyne of Dallas, who graduated from
college in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the festival, which drew hundreds of thousands to packed
prayer services at churches throughout the city, mass confessions
at Circus Maximus, and the Stations of the Cross at the Colosseum,
was as much a Special Olympics of the soul _ a huge, often grueling
effort by young Catholics to show the world that not all of today's
youths live in a secular, morality-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main principles of this whole thing is to prove to
people that the new generation still believes,'' Etienne Corpechot,
18, a high-school student from Paris, said as he squatted amid a
sea of rumpled sleeping bags and cardboard boxes in scorching
98-degree heat waiting for the pope to begin Mass. And his was a
point that John Paul, who turned 80 last May, welcomed with visible
relish and relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society desperately needs this sign, and young people need
it even more so,'' the pope said in his homily Sunday, ``tempted as
they often are by the illusion of an easy and comfortable life, by
drugs and pleasure seeking, only to find themselves in a spiral of
despair, meaninglessness and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnout for this World Youth Day, the 15th since John Paul
created the event in 1984, exceeded even Vatican expectations,
which hovered at 1.5 million. It was the largest papal event ever
held in Europe, drawing 2 million people, according to city
officials, and topping the previous World Youth Day, which gathered
more than 1 million in Paris in 1997. Only the World Youth Day in
Manila in 1995, which drew up to 4 million people, was larger.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims began streaming in on Tuesday, staying in convents,
priories, hostels and public school buildings, which the city began
planning to make available two years ago for the event. But on
Saturday night more than 1 million people slept on sleeping bags,
cardboard boxes and plastic bags in the open air of a vast, arid
field belonging the University of Rome in preparation for the
pope's Mass Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The huge numbers, and a lapse in organization, brought the day
to a chaotic end. Pilgrims, who were supposed to leave in scheduled
waves, instead left en masse, swarming into the one metro stop near
the field, flooding highways and bus stops and overwhelming the
transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the event was a personal triumph for the pope,
who prides himself on his rapport with young people and has long
viewed the Holy Year of the new millennium as a cornerstone of his
papacy. Frail, and shaking from the symptoms of Parkinson's, the
pope nevertheless beamed throughout Saturday night's three-hour
candlelit ceremony, tapping his armchair to the music and at the
end swaying both arms above his head as if joining a human wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I return, rejuvenated,'' he told Saturday's cheering crowd,
noting approvingly that ``Rome has never heard such a noise
before.''
</P>
<P>
   But there also were some tears of fatigue and frustration, as
young pilgrims, who invaded a deserted Rome, found themselves
walking for miles in tight packs, or crammed into trams and buses
in stifling heat. Many were lodged on the floors of empty school
rooms, modestly donning bathing suits to take outdoor showers.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, young people from Europe, Latin America, Africa
and Asia sang as they walked, cheerfully shrugging off discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am used to the heat, and I have no right to be sleepy if the
pope can make it,'' Sabin Sonhaye, 29, a student from Togo, said at
the Saturday night vigil. He saw the pope in his own country in
1984, when he was 14, but said he had wanted to experience a World
Youth Day ever since viewing a video cassette of the Paris event.
He, like others, expressed a desire to renew their faith with
like-minded young people. Others said they reveled in a city that
for a week seemed doused with religious feeling.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are as many churches here as there are gas stations in
Los Angeles.'' Lucy Kim, 22, of Gardena, Calif., marveled.
</P>
<P>
   The huge masses left their mark. This week so many young
pilgrims wanted to pass through the Holy Door of St. Peter's, a
Holy Year ritual, that the Vatican opened a second one for the
first time in church history. After 500,000 people walked with
candles to recreate the Stations of the Cross along the Via dei
Fori Imperiali, next to the ancient Forum, the entire street was
closed off for four hours the next day so sanitation workers could
scrape up the melted wax on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To reach Sunday's Mass at Tor Vergata, a suburban campus of the
University of Rome, many pilgrims had to walk more than 6 miles
from the end of a subway line under a broiling sun, carrying boxed
meals and six-packs of bottled water. At least 2,000 people were
treated in first-aid tents Saturday and Sunday, and ambulances,
which ominously circled the area like buzzards, took more than 40
people to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even the pope's opening greeting at St. Peter's on Tuesday,
which drew 300,000 into St. Peter's Square, was a trial for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on point, it was insane,'' said Jesse Randall, 16, of
Seattle, explaining how he had led his Catholic youth group into
the teeming square. ``It was fun,'' he said. ``I was born for it.
It was like a mosh pit, except nobody was wielding chains.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Roman merchants who stayed in town and witnessed the
youthful invasion were less than enthusiastic about pilgrim
spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in 10 at a time, and only one bought anything,''
Fabrizio Sagnotti, who runs an eye-wear store on Via del Corso,
groused to the Italian news agency Ansa. ``They created a big
confusion, and that is all.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   RAI, Italy's largest network, covered the major events of the
festival live, and the Saturday night vigil won a 28 percent share
of the television audience. Some intellectuals expressed diffidence
about the lavish, doting attention the Italian media paid to the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are a million and a half or even 2 million young people
touring Rome in the Jubilee worth more than the more than 2 million
crowding Adriatic beaches without crosses and litanies?'' Eugenio
Scalfari, the retired editor in chief of La Repubblica, asked in a
front-page editorial of his paper on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims, however, expressed no regrets. ``Getting here was an
incredible hike, and at times I have asked myself why did I make
this trip,'' Linda Muraski, 46, of Knoxville, Tenn., said as she
and her 16-year-old daughter Allison kneeled by the cot of their
group leader, Patrick Donovan of Wilmington, Del., who had fainted
from heat stroke and lay inert and hooked up to an IV in a Red
Cross tent on Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you get into the middle of the most beautiful Mass,''
she added, ``and there is the pope, with you, and it is so moving
you forget all you went through to get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
