<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-0821-COX     08-20 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'FUN AL' EMERGING AS DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL NOMINEE SURGES IN
POLLS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, Iowa _ If you think you know Al Gore, you should have
seen him just around midnight this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After an impassioned speech late Saturday night, the denim-clad
Gore suddenly grabbed his wife Tipper and boogied on stage as a
local rock band cranked up a hot blues number and confetti rained
down upon the dancing couple.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which had gathered hours earlier, roared its delight.
Some in the crowd marveled: Who is this guy?
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in accepting the Democratic Party's presidential
nomination last week, assured voters that he is his ``own man'' and
that in the coming weeks they would see ``who I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fun-loving Al Gore that has rocked the Mark Twain
campaign riverboat down the Mississippi River the last three days
is somewhat of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun Al'' first appeared Friday morning as he and running mate
Joe Lieberman boarded the Mark Twain for a four-day, 400-mile trip
down the Mississippi River through five Midwestern swing states.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters asked him whether he was trying to send any kind of
signal to the voters with the lingering kiss he gave Tipper just
before his acceptance speech the night before in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to send Tipper a signal,'' he replied,
mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early Saturday afternoon, Gore burst unannounced into the
press section of the campaign riverboat to catch a group of
television producers and camera operators in a game of poker.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed mock horror and, tongue-in-cheek, demanded
``campaign journalism reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, during an evening birthday party for his wife on the open
top deck of the boat, Gore occasionally used a bullhorn to make
small talk with campers and other people in sparsely populated
areas along the banks of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice shirt,'' he called to one person in the river darkness, a
scene reminiscent of Bill Clinton's microphone chit-chat _ ``I like
your dog!'' _ with people who lived along the tracks his
slow-moving campaign train took through the Midwest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need your help,'' Gore shouted to another group in the
darkness of the river. Then, with the bullhorn off, he added,
almost in a whisper: ``The boat is sinking.''
</P>
<P>
   And even later Saturday, when his campaign boat pulled into the
dam and lock just north of this Iowa city, hundreds of well-wishers
looked a bit surprised when they heard the Rolling Stones's
sexually suggestive song ``Brown Sugar'' and its famous ``just
around midnight'' refrain blaring from the boat's sound system.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing prepared Gore's campaign entourage for the sight of
Al and Tipper boogie-ing on the stage in Clinton. No one, not even
longtime aides to the vice president, could recall him ever dancing
at a campaign event _ at the Clinton-Gore inaugurations, sure, but
not at a campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is finding his own voice,'' campaign spokesman Chris
Lehane deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with his presidential campaign stumbling, Gore got
unsolicited advice from Clinton: ``Have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And ever since embarking on his Mississippi trip, Gore appears
to be having the time of his political life.
</P>
<P>
   A big contributor has been the unprecedented bounce he has
received in the polls since the convention, such as the CNN-USA
Today Gallup poll released Sunday. That poll had Gore at 47
percent, Republican nominee George W. Bush at 46 percent, Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party candidate
Pat Buchanan at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 697 likely voters taken Friday and Saturday had an
error margin of (+/-) 4 percentage points. That same poll right
before the convention showed Bush 16 points ahead of Gore, 55
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush communications director Karen Hughes, appearing on ``Fox
News Sunday,'' cautioned against putting ``too much stock in the
instant polls taken in the immediate aftermath of a convention.''
She noted that Walter Mondale surged ahead of Ronald Reagan in 1984
in some polls but eventually lost the race.
</P>
<P>
   History aside, Gore's newfound giddiness in the trail is
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   During his speeches, Gore works in the messages from homemade
signs he sees in the crowd into his remarks. Sometimes, he engages
members of the crowd in a brief conversation before going on to the
issue of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the speeches, he remains as long as his
schedule will allow to shake hands, reaching deep into the crowds
that have swelled with each day of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   He slaps hands with children and toddlers and tweaks the noses
of babies.
</P>
<P>
   He poses for pictures and signs autographs.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike previous campaigns, he hugs and hugs and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be fired up,'' said Julia Heinzelman, a
middle-aged high school teacher in Dubuque, Iowa, one of the
riverboat stops. ``So much politics happens on TV, and TV is
supposed to be a cool medium. But I'm tired of the coolness. It's
time to get hot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting warmed up,'' Gore remarked to one crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's closest friends have long insisted that the vice
president is fun-loving and funny, but the American public has
rarely gotten a glimpse of ``Fun Al.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Gore insists that the presidential contest with
Texas Gov. George W. Bush is not a personality contest, you can
expect to see more of ``Fun Al'' after his life on the Mississippi
is over.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's E-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
