<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SODA-BRITVIC-OFFER-NY     08-20 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODA-BRITVIC-OFFER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SODA BOTTLER OFFERED FOR SALE BY BASS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britvic, one of Britain's largest soft-drink
manufacturers, is for sale as part of Bass PLC's strategy to focus
on its hotel business, executives close to Britvic said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Britvic, which owns Tango and other popular British soft drinks,
is 90 percent controlled by a joint venture of Bass, Allied Dome
and Whitbread, in which Bass has a 50.1 percent majority stake.
PepsiCo owns the other 10 percent as part of deal that allows
Britvic to manufacturer and distribute Pepsi in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder Salomon Smith Barney has been hired to sell Britvic,
which analysts say will probably raise about 350 million pounds, or
$522 million, as part of Bass' strategy to sell its noncore assets
and focus on its hotel business, the executives said. Bass is one
of the largest hotel operators in the world, with nearly 3,000
hotels under the Holiday Inn, Inter-Continental and Crowne Plaza
names.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Sir Ian Prosser, Bass' chairman and chief executive,
sold the company's brewery operations to Interbrew, a Belgian
company, for 2.3 billion &UR;  &LR; pounds, although that deal has come under
scrutiny by British antitrust authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A Bass spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Possible bidders include PepsiCo, although the company's
strategy of spinning off bottling assets runs counter to a purchase
of Britvic.
</P>
<P>
   Britvic has attractive operating cash flow, which surged 36
percent in 1999, to 41 million pounds. For the first six months of
this year, the company had an operating profit of 9 million pounds
on sales of 270 million pounds. That compares with operating profit
of 8 million pounds on sales of 254 million pounds in the period a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The auction would not be the first attempt at a change of
ownership for Britvic. Last autumn, Allied Dome tried to sell its
Britvic stake to Punch Taverns, which was also buying Allied's pub
business. Whitbread, which lost out to Punch in the bidding for
Allied's pubs, used its pre-emptive rights to eliminate the Britvic
stake from the deal. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0071 </DOCNO>
