<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PET-INSURANCE0821-COX     08-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-INSURANCE0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurance that's gone to the dogs
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Basel's unusual eating habits have gotten her
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Basel, an 80-pound Bernese mountain dog, has swallowed
socks, which veterinarians surgically removed. Once, she gulped
down a corn cob, which meant another trip to the surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Basel's antics have taken her owners, Erin and Sean McGould, on
an emotional roller coaster ride. It would have been an expensive
ride, too, except that the couple had taken out a medical insurance
policy on the dog that has softened the financial blow.
</P>
<P>
   Medical treatment for pets has grown sophisticated _ and more
expensive _ so perhaps it's logical that Fluffy and Fido now have
their own insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Medical insurance for pets is gaining popularity, and
veterinarians and financial planners say that's good news for pet
owners who consider their dogs and cats full-fledged family
members.
</P>
<P>
   Pet insurance has been around since the 1980s, but only about 1
percent of American pet owners buy policies. Insurers see an
untapped market; in Sweden, for instance, nearly half of pet owners
have policies.
</P>
<P>
   Family Security Insurance Services, an independent agency, this
month began selling pet insurance issued by Aegon, a large Dutch
insurer. St. Petersburg-based Home Shopping Network this year began
offeri00 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for pet insurance has increased as veterinary medicine
has advanced, said Robin Itzer, spokeswoman for Veterinary Pet
Insurance of Anaheim, Calif. Now dogs and cats get kidney
transplants, pacemakers, chemotherapy and MRIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 15 years ago, people would have just said, `Fluffy had
a good life,' '' Itzer said. ``In the last 10 years, veterinary
medicine has drastically changed. Everything is state of the art.''
</P>
<P>
   Policies sold by Family Security Insurance cost $234 a year for
puppies and kittens, said Vice President Bob De Benedetto. For dogs
and cats 5 to 8 years old, the annual premium is $286.
</P>
<P>
   Only canines and felines are eligible; no birds or iguanas need
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Pet owners pay vets for services, then ask the insurance company
for reimbursement. The Aegon policies cover 80 percent of drugs,
shots or surgery. There's a $50 deductible and maximum
reimbursement of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County vets say only a tiny percentage of pet owners
have insurance.
</P>
<P>
   There have been setbacks for pet insurers. Some have gone out of
business, and some pet owners have become discouraged by the
requirement that they pay and then wait for reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cases I've seen, I thought it was kind of a waste of
money,'' said Dr. Jack Liggett, a vet at Clearlake Animal Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But other vets are more encouraging. Pet owners should consider
insurance if they don't have enough cash to cover a major illness,
said Dr. Robert Bonitzer of Town and Country Animal Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   John Potter, a certified public accountant and president of the
Gold Coast chapter of the Financial Planning Association, agreed.
Pet owners, especially those who have strong bonds to their pets,
can be blind-sided by big bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will go out and mortgage their house,'' Potter
said. ``If you're that type of person, pet insurance is good to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The McGoulds pay $297 a year for a pet insurance policy from
Veterinary Pet Insurance. They bought the coverage when Basel, now
3, was a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   The policy has paid off, Erin McGould said. Aside from the socks
and corn cob incidents, Basel also broke a bone in her paw while
running in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the McGoulds said, insurance has covered more than
$3,000 in medical treatment for Basel.
</P>
<P>
   The McGoulds paid $1,200 for their purebred dog when she was a
puppy, and they would have paid for Basel's surgeries without
insurance, Erin McGould said. But, she added, the policy turned out
to be a wise financial move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has been one of the best investments we've made.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
