<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SHAW-FURNITURE0821-CO     08-20 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAW-FURNITURE0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet company brings family business to ruin
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sherrill Shaw returned to his hometown of
Randleman, N.C., in 1956 after serving in the Air Force and took
over his father's business, Shaw Furniture Galleries. He ran it for
more than four decades, built a national reputation, then sold it
last year to an upstart from Austin so he could retire.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Shaw Furniture Galleries shut its doors, as did the
fledgling company that bought it, Austin's living.com Inc. As early
as this week, both will file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   A North Carolina newspaper wrote that it took living.com just 13
months to destroy what the Shaw family had spent nearly 60 years
building up.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``new economy'' town like Austin, dot-com disasters have
become as common as the dog days of August. Last week alone,
Mall.com and CarOrder.com also laid off big chunks of their staffs
and acknowledged that they were running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   But in Randleman, population 3,100, Shaw Furniture Galleries was
the most prominent business in town _ and a profitable one at that
_and in its place, there is only bitterness about how the new
economy has failed one of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost feel like something's been taken away from us,''
said David Caughron, executive director of the Randleman Chamber of
Commerce. ``I even hate it for the Shaw family, since their name is
still attached to the company. They had a very sound reputation and
business for 60 years.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Shaw's 63 employees were laid off and perhaps hundreds of
orders that had not been delivered to customers have been stranded.
Living.com's bankruptcy attorneys estimate that there are between
2,500 and 3,500 claims on the company's assets, about two-thirds of
which are from customers of it and Shaw Furniture Galleries. They
don't yet know if any will get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's traumatic and it's frustrating,'' said Sherrill Shaw, who
is contemplating suing living.com over money he says he is still
owed from the sale. ``All of the problems that are being addressed
today are the result of the management of the company. They have
not sought our advice one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   People who know Randleman know it for two things: being the home
of stock car legend Richard Petty and the home of Shaw Furniture
Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The store occupied one of the town's most historic buildings,
the Randleman School, built in 1904. Billboards drew shoppers from
Interstates 40 and 85, which run near town, and a catalog spread
the company's name and generous discounts around the country. It
didn't hurt that Randleman, in the Piedmont region of central North
Carolina, sits just 15 minutes from the self-described furniture
capital of the world, High Point.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill Shaw, who lives on a street named for his family,
estimates that the company had 300,000 to 400,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   That success attracted living.com, which as it was preparing to
launch its online furniture store last year was looking for an
experienced partner that could lend it credibility in the
close-knit furniture industry and help it ship orders around the
country. The sale took many people in Randleman by surprise. And it
did not take long before it started to rub some of them the wrong
way.
</P>
<P>
   Some Shaw workers were transferred to living.com's operations in
nearby Greensboro, one former employee said. Others complained that
they had to run every decision through living.com, jeopardizing
relationships with manufacturers. And many in town believed that
unprofitable living.com was draining money from a profitable
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought living.com was more important than Shaw
Furniture,'' said Heather Siler, who worked at Shaw for five years
before losing her job Tuesday. ``I think if living.com had never
purchased us, everything would have been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, claims about botched orders and shipping delays started
arriving at the Chamber of Commerce and the local Better Business
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably within this past year I've had more phone calls from
customers (of Shaw) and I think that had a lot to do with
living.com,'' said Caughron. ``They were questioning the way some
of their shipments had been handled.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Shaw announced that it would go back to managing its
own operations. And although they had heard rumors of living.com's
coming demise, employees believed it when Shaw's management said
that the store would be bought and stay open.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday afternoon, they were told that the store was
closing. Caughron fielded 52 calls about living.com that day and
the city manager talked of trying to estimate the sales tax revenue
that Randleman would lose without Shaw, not to mention the business
its customers gave restaurants, gas stations and shops in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (people) are disheartened and disgusted because not
only was Shaw Furniture a major furniture company, it was a part of
the community,'' said Jeff Freeman, owner of Freeman Florist and
Gift on Main Street, down the block from the Shaw store. ``You take
(that) many billboards off the interstate promoting your town _
wouldn't you think that would hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   And people in Randleman haven't forgotten the swagger with which
living.com carried itself in its early days, a bluster typical
among Internet startups. Executives were quoted saying that the
furniture industry was broken and that the Internet would fix it,
making living.com a multi-billion company in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming statements that living.com kept coming out
with about what a terrific company they were . . . I'm sorry, when
it comes down to it, that doesn't amount to a hill of beans,''
Caughron said. ``I think they had a great promotional and marketing
strategy to be able to promote themselves so well. They actually
had people believing that this was the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many people in this part of North Carolina
don't think there's anything wrong with the way furniture is sold
now and don't think the Internet is the way to go. One of the most
important characteristics of a piece of furniture is ``hand,''
industry jargon for the way it feels, and no technology can yet
convey that on a computer screen. Many people in Randleman say that
the demise of living.com proves that. They just wish that Shaw
Furniture Galleries hadn't gone down with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that in the beginning,'' said Sherrill Shaw. ``But
they didn't believe me. They thought they could get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
