<P>
   COX-GORE _ CLINTON, Iowa _ If you think you know Al Gore, you
should have seen him just around midnight. After an impassioned
speech late Saturday night, Gore grabbed his wife Tipper and began
to boogie on stage as a local rock band cranked up a hot blues
number and confetti rained down upon the dancing couple. The crowd,
which had been waiting for hours for the arrival of the Gores,
roared its delight. Some marveled: who is this guy? Gore, in his
acceptance speech last week, had assured voters that he is his
``own man.'' But Al Gore, a rocker? Who knew? With daily
developments. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 7:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   POPULARITY _ ATLANTA _ The fashionable baggy red shorts that
scrape his shins. The skinny arms folded in defiance. The sullen
scowl that breaks only briefly when someone begs him just once to
smile for the camera. Jemario King's gangsta cool body language
says it all: ``I don't care if you like me.'' The 16-year-old
Decatur, Ga. resident, who returned to classes last week, isn't
interested in becoming Mr. Popular. ``To me, being popular doesn't
really matter,'' he says. ``It's a state of mind . . . I'm just
going to do what I gotta do anyway.'' As another wave of youngsters
head back to class today, it might be tempting to suggest, as
Jemario does, that popularity doesn't matter. After all, the rugged
individualist is an American icon. But as much as most of us wish
that popularity doesn't count, we know otherwise. It does matter,
even _ and perhaps especially _ as an adult. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
