<HEADLINE>
AS JOBS DECLINE IN OREGON MILLS, LOGGING ON IS REPLACING LOGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and 12, and a map, are being sent to NYT
photo and graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOS BAY, Ore. _ Zeldon Linn has worked on the railroads and in
a sawmill. He has been a sergeant in the Army and a mechanic in a
garage. At times for the last 15 years he has found work as a
fisherman, crabbing and catching salmon in the Pacific Ocean off
this struggling blue-collar town along the Oregon coast. At other
times, he has found no work at all.
</P>
<P>
   All of which, he conceded with a laugh the other day, seems like
odd preparation for his new job, where he sits in a cubicle each
day, fires up a computer, dons a headset and swings into action on
the first ring of the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning,'' Linn says. ``Thank you for calling MSN
Technical Support. My name is Zeldon. May I have your e-mail
address, please?''
</P>
<P>
   For Linn and 345 other people here in remote Coos County, where
the historical economic pillars of logging and fishing have been
severely battered and where the unemployment rate was in the double
digits as recently as last year, an improbable savior has emerged,
mushrooming in a matter of months into the second-largest private
employer in the county.
</P>
<P>
   As high-tech companies face an acute shortage of workers in many
urban areas, they have begun to branch out to areas of the country
that had been passed over by the boom, bringing jobs and training
and making inroads on the ``digital divide'' between America's
urban and rural regions.
</P>
<P>
   Here in southern Oregon, the company is CyberRep.com, a Virginia
concern that has contracts to provide phone and Internet services
for well-known corporate clients. CyberRep workers like Linn answer
the toll-free help lines for the Microsoft Corp.'s MSN online
service and for Barnes &AMP; Noble.com, the online division of the
bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   For places like Coos Bay, once the largest wood-products
shipping port in the world, there are some painful twists. These
are the back-office jobs of the ``new economy,'' paying $8 to $9 an
hour and offering no stock-option bonuses. There is a graveyard
shift, because the help lines need to be staffed 24 hours a day, 7
days a week. Even with CyberRep set to surpass the Mill Casino,
owned by the Coquille Indian tribe, as the area's largest source of
private jobs, it will still represent just a fraction of the 3,200
jobs in the wood-products industry that local officials say have
been lost in the last 20 years. In many cases those jobs paid, in
constant-dollar terms, twice as well as the new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these are jobs, offering health benefits and computer
skills that many workers say they believe are the perfect entry to
more lucrative employment. And most of the workers, like Linn, seem
grateful for the work, though they often express ambivalence about
the nature of the work and the sweeping economic forces that have
taken them out of the woods or off the seas and placed them in
small workstations in a boxy warehouse building up the street from
the local airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the ocean,'' said Linn, 43, a burly, bearded man who
still wears work boots to his job. ``There's a feeling of freedom
you get there like no place else. Now here I am, confined to this
little cubicle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' he said, his face brightening, ``this is
the first job I've ever had where I go to work clean and I come
home clean. I've never had a job where I didn't come home smelling
like fish or oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Linn and other workers at CyberRep described the kick they get
from helping frustrated or even irate callers from around the
nation facing trouble with their dial-up adapters, modem
connections, configuration schemes and all manner of other software
and Internet problems. Some callers simply need old-fashioned help,
like directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving through Kansas right now,'' said a woman named
Peggy, speaking on her cell phone, after she called Barnes &AMP;
Noble's 1-800-THE-BOOK help line and reached Stella Smith, 62, the
wife of a retired logger, at her workstation here. ``I'm driving
across the country. Do you have a bookstore anywhere near Topeka,
Kan.? I'd really like to go to a bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith instantly used her computer mouse to navigate the ``find a
store'' function of the Barnes &AMP; Noble site to locate the store in
Topeka and give Peggy the directions.
</P>
<P>
   These jobs are not for everybody. Some who have worked around
trees or at the port all their lives said they could not imagine
being cooped up all day, staring at a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put me indoors and I'm lost,'' said George Sjostrom, 59, a
wiry man with a chain saw and a hard hat, who shook his head when
asked if he might want to trade his job as a log-yard worker for
that of a computer-support specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out of my world,'' continued Sjostrom, who tags and sorts
giant logs all day with the help of enormous claw-equipped machines
that move the logs around the yard as if they were toothpicks,
readying them for placement aboard ships at the nearby port or in
machines that turn them into wood chips bound for pulp mills. ``I
wouldn't have any idea what to do with a computer. If I could
figure out the `on' button, that'd be a big accomplishment for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At CyberRep, though, many of the workers said they enjoyed
computers and several, including Linn and Mike Armijo, 38, who lost
two jobs in recent years when local mills closed, said they had
initially taught themselves how to use the machines.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs have their stressful aspects, perhaps chief among them
the constant pressure to satisfy customers while sticking to an
average time of roughly nine minutes a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk a fine line,'' Armijo said. ``You've got to be as
caring as you can, but you've also got to get them off the phone as
quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers here trade horror stories about their longest service
calls _ 82 minutes here, 74 minutes there _ often involving
customers who have completely fouled up their software settings in
a bid to solve what began as a much simpler problem. Men are
generally more difficult than women, workers of both sexes agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are much more likely to think they know something about
computers when they don't,'' Linn observed. ``But women, I've
found, are more willing to say something like, `I really don't
know, I need help.' They'll really listen to you more. So they take
less time.''
</P>
<P>
   Several elements came together to culminate in the deal that
brought CyberRep to the call-center building, which is part of the
airport office park in North Bend, the neighboring town to Coos
Bay. The idea started last year in the mind of John Stadter, then
the chief financial officer of 800 Support, a company based in the
Portland suburbs that was recently acquired by CyberRep. Stadter
grew up on the Oregon coast and had a vacation home near here, in
Bandon. So, he explained, he knew something about the area and
convinced his initially skeptical colleagues that there was a
large, willing and able work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the smartest people in my high school class went to
work in the woods, because that's where the big money was,'' said
Stadter, now the general manager of Coos Bay operations for
CyberRep. ``And they're still around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon International Port of Coos Bay, which helps broker
economic development deals, put together a package of tax
incentives and agreed to lease the building. The local Southwestern
Oregon Community College provided computer training classes.
</P>
<P>
   Coos Bay's wood-shipping industry, as well as its fishing, has
declined in the face of foreign competition and heightened
environmental regulations. While 300 million board feet of lumber
were shipped out of Coos Bay annually a decade ago, the number last
year was 13.5 million, said Ingvar Doessing, the manager of a local
stevedoring company and a member of the port commission.
</P>
<P>
   The region, 80 miles away from the nearest interstate highway,
is remote by many measures. Local officials have sought
unsuccessfully to attract a steel mill, a pulp mill and a
fish-processing plant. They say they are thrilled to have landed a
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area has never really participated in the economic boom
of the 1990's,'' said Allan E. Rumbaugh, the port's general
manager. ``It certainly participated very strongly in the recession
of the early 1980's. So this deal has given us a real sense of
optimism that we're not the pariah we sometimes worry we are. We
can attract a company to come here from out of town. That feels
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Armijo, the CyberRep support technician, expressed more caution:
``It's been my sad observation that nothing lasts forever around
here as a source of jobs. I've never seen anything that permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for now,'' he said, using an analogy that looks back to
what was once an economic mainstay, ``I think it's a godsend that
this company has come in here. It's kind of like a guy going
fishing and reeling in a 1,300-pound tuna. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
