<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GYMNASTS BRAVED AUDITION RATHER THAN TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is never fun to be cut. In high school basketball,
the process can be as simple as scanning a list posted on the
gymnasium wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait. Maybe Coach misspelled my name.'' Right.
</P>
<P>
   In the arcane world of men's gymnastics, they do it in public.
With the cameras turned on. On Saturday night, officials marched
all the athletes back into the arena for one last round of
applause, and then the fun began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who is going to Sydney, take one step forward. Not
so fast, Abernathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night it would happen to the women, but at least the
leaders planned to do it in private, a few seconds before escorting
everybody back into the center ring.
</P>
<P>
   People were paying big bucks for something billed as the
``Olympic Team Trials,'' but the real trial was being held by Chief
Justice Karolyi and his colleagues in chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The operative word is ``team.'' There is now more emphasis on
specialists in gymnastics, which means the committee had more
mandate to pick and choose.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday night, the top six were Elise Ray, Kristen
Maloney, Amy Chow, Jamie Dantzscher, Morgan White and Vanessa
Atler, with the golden oldies Dominique Dawes and Shannon Miller
very much on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   In all sports, bad news sometimes arrives at the last moment.
Some hapless relief pitcher gets cut on the last day of spring
training, and has to retrieve his stuff from the team truck.
Playpen. Suitcases. Golf clubs. Then he tries to reach his wife on
her car phone. Honey, when you get to Jacksonville, turn left.
</P>
<P>
   It happened this way for the men on Saturday evening. Paul Hamm
figured he was safely ensconced in second place but his fraternal
twin, Morgan, was in a quite precarious sixth, right ahead of good
old reconstructed John Roethlisberger, a very ancient 30 and
everybody's big brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous,'' Morgan said. ``If I didn't make the team,
we'd be separated for really the first time in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   What was the rationale for making the athletes get the word in
public? It came from Peter Kormann, the team coach, who thought
that the fans in the upper reaches of the sprawling Fleet Center
deserved to find out at the same time as the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Kormann, it should be noted, is a true son of New England, where
they used to put people in the stocks and burn alleged witches.
When he means ``karma,'' it comes out ``comma.'' He is also a very
interesting guy with a flair for the dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're men,'' Kormann repeated Sunday. ``They're warriors.
They walk out here and raise their hand and get on the pommel
horse. They can handle this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe yes, maybe no. In front of a packed arena, Paul Hamm heard
the announcement that Jamie Natalie had been consigned to
alternate. This could only mean that Morgan had made the top six.
Paul patted Morgan on the back. They were going to Sydney together.
Natalie is still playing good soldier about his very public
demotion.
</P>
<P>
   It's rough getting cut. In professional football, the team
functionary known as The Turk sidles up and demands the playbook,
but at least The Turk operates behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes don't get to this level without learning to deal with
direct competition. There is something very finite about the way
track and field does it. Dan O'Brien aced nine events in the
decathlon trials in 1992 but he could not get over the bar in the
pole vault and was thereby denied a trip to Barcelona, where he
very well could have won a gold medal. No note from his doctor
would alter the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But in gymnastics there is a growing emphasis on teamwork. Under
the new rules, the men will send six competitors, but only five
will be entered in each of the six events, and only the top four
scores will count.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, there was already lineup strategy. Kormann claims he
was pressured by two public officials from one state to enter their
favorite son in every event so he could qualify for the all-around
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pretty ugly,'' Kormann said with a grin, relishing the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Now more than ever, Kormann and Karolyi are both looking for
specialists. Gymnastics is getting to be like the real team sports
_ nickel backs on passing defense, setup relievers in baseball,
short-handed specialists in hockey, expendable lummoxes who hack
Shaquille O'Neal six times and foul out.
</P>
<P>
   The action here was in the back room. For all the money it paid
for the television rights, NBC undoubtedly wanted its cameras
rolling during the selection meeting. Bela waving right index
finger. Bela pacing room. Bela shouting, ``Is how we did it in old
country.''
</P>
<P>
   If they can capture the men hearing their fate, they can film
the women getting the news in the locker. The Turk goes live. Next
time.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
