u a BC-CLINTON-FAN-NYT &LR;      08-20 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S SIGNATURE IS A LITTLE TOO EXCITING FOR ONE WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ A young woman who joined hundreds of excited
onlookers on Main Street on Saturday night to catch a glimpse of
President Clinton stripped off her T-shirt in glee after the
president signed it.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, wearing a bra was immediately surrounded by law
enforcement officials, who handcuffed her and questioned her until
Clinton left the scene. She was later released.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a big deal,'' said an officer with the Lake Placid
Police Department. ``She was questioned but that's it.'' The
authorities did not release the woman's name.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at about 11:30 p.m. as Clinton, Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Chelsea Clinton stopped for ice cream on Main
Street of this small resort town in northern New York after a
birthday dinner for the president, who turned 54 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, Clinton had signed numerous T-shirts of both men
and women before he reached the young woman, who pulled out the
bottom of her T-shirt for him to sign and enthusiastically hoisted
the shirt over her head after he signed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He signed the bottom of her shirt and he turned away, and then
she did a Brandi Chastain and ripped off the shirt,'' said a White
House spokesman, Jake Siewert, referring to the U.S. soccer star
who took off her shirt and ran around in her sports bra after her
team won the World Cup last year.
</P>
<P>
   After the commotion Saturday, Clinton briefly turned back toward
the woman before heading for his motorcade. Mrs. Clinton and
Chelsea were nearby. Siewert called the incident ``less risque than
a Sunday Times Magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as he emerged from dinner, the president revealed his
birthday wish: that both his wife and Vice President Al Gore win
their electoral bids.
</P>
<P>
   On his lapel was a ``Hillary for Senate'' pin.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons were spending the weekend at the private home of a
local real estate developer, Arthur Lussi, whose grandfather was an
Olympic gold medalist. Lake Placid was the host of the 1932 and
1980 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after Clinton finished a round of golf and Mrs. Clinton
made a campaign appearance in Buffalo, the family went to their
house in Chappaqua, where they established residency last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
