<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      08-20 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRUMAN-LIKE STYLE, GORE AND LIEBERMAN PROMISE BROADER HEALTH
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. _ Comparing his increasingly populist pitch to that
of Harry S. Truman, but leaving his running mate to
``give-them-hell,'' Vice President Al Gore vowed Sunday to fight
drug companies and health maintenance organizations in bringing
broader and fairer health coverage to all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   At the first of four appearances Sunday in Illinois and Iowa,
all of them in towns along the Mississippi River, Gore said he
would push for a patients' bill of rights to protect HMO consumers
and for adding a prescription drug benefit under the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, we will flat make it
happen,'' Gore promised a crowd of about 3,000 in downtown Moline.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of
Connecticut, used their speeches here to draw on the Trumanesque
imagery that has enthralled Democrats for more than half a century.
But Gore left it to Lieberman to assail the health care record of
his Republican opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore made only passing references to the Republicans,
Lieberman charged that 1.4 million children in Texas do not have
health insurance, that Texas leads the nation in the percentage of
residents who are uninsured and that it ranks next to last in
health care for women.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Bush often responds to criticisms of his state by
saying ``don't mess with Texas.'' But, he asserted, ``when it comes
to health care, it's a mess in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day riverboat tour down the Mississippi, Gore left
the slow-moving ship and traveled by bus Sunday so he could make
all four cities on his schedule. Gore and his wife, Tipper, were
rejoined by Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, who had left the trip
in Wisconsin on Friday to observe the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates clearly have been buoyed by polls showing they
received a significant boost from last week's Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles, and they have been received
enthusiastically by sizable crowds. ``I'm no expert as to what to
make of it,'' Gore told reporters, ``but it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   As in his convention speech on Thursday night, Gore accepted
credit Sunday for the economic health of the Clinton years but said
there was more work to be done. He noted, for instance, that 15
percent of all Americans are still without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some serious problems in our health care system,''
he said, his voice still hoarse from his convention speech, ``and
we've got to fix them without undermining the good things about our
health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would move incrementally toward a system of
universal health care, starting with guaranteed coverage for every
child by 2004. And he said the country owes its older citizens a
prescription drug benefit, a proposal estimated to cost $253
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people have bills for pills that are more than their
Social Security check,'' Gore said, ``it is wrong for our country
to put seniors, the generation that won World War II, in a
situation where they have to choose between food and medicine when
the drug companies have the biggest profits of any industry in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies, Gore said, do not support such plans because
they fear that drug prices will come down. ``Well, they need to
come down,'' he said. ``They need more competition.'' He added:
``I'll be like Harry Truman. I'll tell them the truth and they'll
just think it's hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then switched targets from the drug companies to HMOs that
he charges with making financial decisions that usurp medical
recommendations. ``Some bean counter behind a computer terminal who
doesn't have a license to practice medicine and surely does not
have a right to play god overrules the doctor because the HMO or
the insurance company doesn't want to shell out the money, even
though you've been paying the monthly premium,'' Gore said. ``What
is that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal for a patients' bill of rights, campaign aides
say, would assure access to specialists, would guarantee emergency
room care regardless of when and where the need arises, and would
provide either a right to sue or an alternative appeals process if
insurers deny coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign criticizes Bush's proposed bill of rights
because it would cover only those Americans in federally governed
health care plans, a restriction that Gore aides say would exclude
135 million people with private insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MYSTERIOUS-REVIEW-     08-20 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERIOUS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYSTERIOUS WAYS': A FLUKE, ANGELS, ALIENS, OR NONE OF THE ABOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's halfway between ``Touched by an Angel'' and ``The
X-Files''? It's ``Mysterious Ways,'' a new series that NBC has been
previewing on Mondays this summer, ahead of the show's run starting
Tuesday night on the Pax network, NBC's family-friendly corporate
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The X-Files'' this drama features an appealingly
mismatched man and woman trying to explain the unexplainable. But
in these tales the unknown forces are unimpeachably good, not evil;
they come not from Mars, but from another celestial address.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Mysterious Ways'' does not explicitly invoke God, as
``Angel'' does, the new show is built upon the same conviction that
earthly problems yield to divine solutions. Like ``Angel,'' and a
thousand pop pieties from Hollywood and Tin Pan Alley, ``Mysterious
Ways'' is a one-size-fits-all exercise in faith without any of the
responsibilities or requirements of actual religion.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the show isn't pleasant entertainment. It
won't stir your soul, but it might warm your heart.
</P>
<P>
   The series' central characters are Declan Dunn, an anthropology
professor, and Peggy Fowler, a psychiatrist. Declan (played with a
bit of goofy charm by Adrian Pasdar) has made a sideline of
investigating what he calls ``miraculous phenomena'' since he was
unaccountably rescued from an avalanche by a boy on a snowmobile
who appeared out of nowhere and quickly vanished.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot episode, which Pax is showing Tuesday, he meets
Peggy (Rae Dawn Chong) at the hospital where she works. Declan has
come there to check on a boy who fell into an icy lake and was
saved from sure drowning by an unseen hand. Declan and Peggy, the
hunter after miracles and the levelheaded scientist, are opposites
that attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perplexed by you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   He replies, ``Get in line.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern for the series, which was created by Peter O'Fallon
and Carl Binder, is established as Peggy joins Declan and his
quirky graduate assistant, Miranda (Alisen Down), looking for every
reasonable explanation for the boy's survival. Was it a miracle?
What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night on NBC, which will broadcast new episodes weekly
through Labor Day, the investigators go to a town where a bus load
of schoolchildren were killed 10 years earlier in a collision with
a train at a rail crossing. The locals, who have never gotten over
the tragedy, believe that the children's ghosts now protect the
crossing; any car that stops there is somehow pushed off the tracks
to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The story takes a clever turn or two, although the dialogue and
much of the acting, especially among the townspeople, is wooden.
More problematic is the relationship between Declan and Peggy. They
seem to kind of like each other, but there's no electricity there.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting character remains Miranda, the unsmiling
but brilliant graduate student. She dresses in black, rides a
motorcycle and locates elusive data when she should be grading
Declan's anthropology exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get her,'' Peggy says of Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   Declan replies: ``What's not to get? Take your IQ, double it,
add black velvet, and you're halfway there.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there an implied conflict here: the shadowy Miranda versus
the good Dr. Peggy? And what happens back on campus, when Declan is
alone with his sultry assistant? Must he endure some devilish trial
by temptation?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. This modest little show couldn't support that kind of
weight. Besides, in this realm of convenient, plot-resolving
miracles, heaven can triumph with no competition from hell.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MYSTERIOUS WAYS'
</P>
<P>
   Spirit Junction
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Monday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Tuesday on Pax
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Fallon and Carl Binder, creators and executive
producers; Jonathan Goodwill, producer; Melissa Byer, Treena
Hancock, Dawn Ritchie and Keri Young, co-producers. Produced and
distributed by Lions Gate Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Adrian Pasdar (Declan Dunn), Rae Dawn Chong (Peggy Fowler)
and Alisen Down (Miranda).
</P>
</TEXT>
