<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POLAND-COMMUNIST-PAST     08-20 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-COMMUNIST-PAST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAND'S FORMER SECRET SERVICE CHIEF FIRM, IF RELUCTANT, WITNESS
AGAINST WALESA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ Piotr Naimski, the former head of the Polish
secret services, has some moral qualms about what he is doing, but
he believes that Lech Walesa, anti-communist hero and Nobel Peace
Prize laureate, has a moral problem.
</P>
<P>
   Walesa, who is running a quixotic campaign to be elected once
more as Poland's president, was cleared on Aug. 12 of charges that
he collaborated with the communist-era secret services and reported
on the activities of his friends and fellow shipyard workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Naimski, one of the first members of KOR, the Worker's
Defense Committee that led to the Solidarity trade union, believes
that Walesa did collaborate, and testified against him in the
closed vetting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski said he did so reluctantly, and with a heavy heart. In a
long interview, he said first that what bothered him most was the
continuing security risk of hidden collaboration. But it became
clear that what really seemed to bother him was hypocrisy. He said
he believes Walesa could have easily confessed to youthful
collaboration without harming his political standing or his
historical reputation _ and, in fact, could have enhanced both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walesa has failed a moral hurdle,'' Naimski said. ``He has
made a mistake by not going openly to the public, and he has missed
an important chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It all ``seems bizarre,'' Naimski said, staring into space.
``Walesa will go down as a positive historical figure and as a
Polish president _ what else is there? But still ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Is Walesa lucky in the verdict of the court? Naimski smiled
thinly. ``He's lucky, yes.'' He laughed. ``And the rest is left for
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Poles have come late to the vetting game, now 11 years after
Communism collapsed, and the process has been clumsy. Perhaps like
the French after World War II, there is a popular desire to assume
that everyone was really part of the resistance and that the same
pressures put on East Germans, Czechs and Hungarians to collaborate
with Moscow and the communist secret police were better resisted
here.
</P>
<P>
   This process has not been smooth or particularly successful
anywhere in the former Soviet bloc, in part because of the ease of
faking or manipulating files built on the products of spies and
informers. Still, the issue of who cooperated with the secret
services and who did not is a moral touchstone. The problem is
deciding _ for certain _ who is innocent and who is guilty, and
proving that someone is lying when they say they did not do what
certain documents indicate they did.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski, a biochemist and anti-communist, ran the Polish secret
services, now known as the State Protection Office, in 1992, when
the process to screen people suspected of being communist
collaborators began. He helped prepare a list of 64 people that
year who were listed as spies in the police records, including
Walesa, then the Polish president. Walesa's name was included on
the list, Naimski now says, after a wrenching internal debate about
the virtues of honesty versus political discretion. But a
parliamentary committee later concluded that Walesa had signed no
agreement with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the world, Naimski has seen Walesa's file, where
the former Gdansk shipyard electrician is alleged to have been an
agent, code-named Bolek, who spied for the secret police in the
early 1970s _ before Walesa rocketed to fame in 1980 as the feisty,
salty leader of Solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   No one contends that Walesa collaborated during the Solidarity
period or afterward, and during the closed trial the secret
services revealed a 1985 Interior Ministry report that documents
had been faked in 1982 to try to prevent Walesa from winning the
Nobel Peace Prize, which he was awarded in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   While these fakes were said to have been important in the
clearing of Walesa, Naimski says that he was aware of them in 1992
and that what troubles him are other, earlier files.
</P>
<P>
   Walesa, now 57, has regularly denied charges of collaboration at
any time. After he was cleared, he called the whole affair ``an
incredibly repulsive game.'' At the same time, he bemoaned the fact
that the vetting trial _ in a process known as lustration, after
the Czech term _ did not seem to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little sick at heart because I had trusted in the
lustration,'' Walesa said. ``Now I see it has no point because the
whole operation did not convince anyone.'' And Walesa is
particularly angry at Naimski and former Interior Minister Antoni
Macierewicz, who both testified against him in the secret hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trusted that at least one of them would shift one way or
another,'' Walesa told Polish Radio. ``But it turns out that it was
all too hard. Their money, their books, and their entire philosophy
and existence is based on this conviction. Now they can't go back
on this. Would they give the money back to those whom they tried to
deceive?''
</P>
<P>
   These charges pain Naimski, a thin, ascetic-looking man of 49,
who is now teaching foreign and security policy at a private
business school in the southern town of Nowy Sacz. Naimski is also
an adviser on the staff of Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek, a member of
the Solidarity coalition who heads a minority government. But
Naimski denies that the government or the Solidarity leader Marian
Krzaklewski, also running for president, manipulated the legal
process in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski said he favors lustration, and would like the entire
process to be ``transparent, open and public,'' unlike its current
secrecy, and yet understands that any vetting system that relies on
informants and secret service files must be ambiguous and subject
to manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, these are moral questions, not legal ones,'' he
said. ``The courts are not the best way to answer moral
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 law requires the vetting of those seeking high public
office. It is not a crime to have collaborated. But anyone who
denies it and is found to have lied is banned from political life
for 10 years. This presidential election is the first time the law
has been used.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski said he believes the special court that cleared Walesa
did so on special, technical grounds. He says that the court did
not find certain original documents sufficient proof that Walesa
was lying, and he said that many other documents have been
destroyed since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski said he has other concerns, which are about state
security. ``This is not a problem of collaboration, but of
counterintelligence,'' he said. Secret collaborators may still be
blackmailed, he said, especially by former Communist Party
apparatchiks and secret service officers who have moved, almost
seamlessly, into the new economy. Many, Naimski said, still have
strong connections to their former colleagues in Russia, many of
whom have also moved into the market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Poles like to talk of a ``Russian party'' of influence, which
lately has been trying to win Polish approval of Russian plans to
build a second natural-gas pipeline to Western Europe that will go
through Poland and Slovakia, cutting out Ukraine, a Polish ally
that Moscow is trying to bring back under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you surprised that Russia treats Central Europe as a lost
jewel?'' Naimski said. And he pointed out that it was not until
days before Poland formally joined NATO that the former communist
opposition in the Parliament was persuaded to pass a strong law
vetting the past of senior officials, as NATO membership requires.
</P>
<P>
   The former Communists, led by the current Polish president,
Aleksander Kwasniewski, who was also cleared by the court, are
expected to win control of the government in parliamentary
elections likely in the spring. The former Communists said they
intend to re-examine the current government's decision not to allow
the Russian gas giant, Gazprom, to build a second pipeline through
Poland, avoiding Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Naimski's position as a government adviser has also led to
complaints that he should simply shut up and accept the verdict of
the court. To those complaints, he simply shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he considers himself Walesa's enemy _ as Walesa has
charged _ Naimski again looks pained. ``I am not an enemy of
Walesa,'' he said. ``I'm disappointed in him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
