<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-BOS &LR;      08-20 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWEGIAN DIVERS AT SITE OF SUNKEN SUB: RUSSIANS CHIDE LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After reaching a Russian nuclear submarine that sank in
the Barents Sea with 118 men on board, Norwegian divers struggled
Sunday to open an escape hatch but found no signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Russians, meanwhile, chided their leaders for waiting
three days before accepting international assistance after a team
of Norwegian deep-sea divers made it to the Kursk, which sank in
354 feet of water on August 12, in their first day of rescue
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian operation appeared to have been the first time
divers had descended to the Kursk since rescue efforts began a week
ago. Russian escape capsules have tried to reach the Kursk
repeatedly, but even though the Russian navy lacked skilled divers
and undersea rescue equipment, the government did not accept offers
of help from Britain and Norway until Wednesday, four days after
the submarine went down.
</P>
<P>
   New details about the accident, reported Sunday, indicated that
the delay may have cost the lives of anyone who had survived the
explosion or collision _ no one knows for sure what happened _ that
caused the massive Oscar 2-class attack submarine to sink.
</P>
<P>
   For days, the Russian navy had insisted that the submarine was
in good condition, but Sunday, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov
said that ``water almost instantly flooded'' half of the
submarine's hull and that ``the crew in those sections died almost
instantaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that some of the crew might have survived for a while
in the Kursk's three aft compartments, and suggested that the
Norwegian divers had seen evidence that some crew members had tried
to remove the escape hatch from within in a desperate effort to
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Norwegian divers banged on the Kursk's hull Sunday
to see if there were any sign of air pockets, officials said, they
heard no response. Late Sunday, Russian navy spokesman Igor Dygalo
told Russian television the Norwegian team had been taken to the
naval town of Vidyayevo, on the coast of the Barents Sea, to study
a submarine similar to the Kursk to see how they could open the
hatch and enter the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians also added to the growing list of contradictions
among the reports Russian officials have given about the state of
the sub and the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   The divers said the escape hatch on the Kursk could be removed,
contradicting statements by Russian officials after a Russian
mini-sub had failed to latch onto the submarine's hatch in several
efforts last week, that the hatch had sustained extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
   With hopes of finding any survivors all but extinguished, it was
still unclear Sunday night whether the Russian navy would dispatch
a British rescue sub to try to latch onto the Kursk. The Norwegians
said the British sub might help; Klebanov said it would not.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence that the boast had been rapidly torn up by the
accident cast doubt on the assurances issued by Russian officials
about the two nuclear reactors that powered the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have insisted that the Kursk's nuclear reactors
switched off in the accident, but the violence of the collision or
explosion that sunk the boat raised concerns that the reactors
could have been damaged in the explosion. Neither Russian nor
Norwegian authorities have found any evidence of radioactive leaks.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens in Russia during a crisis, conspiracy theories
emerged as some people suggested the government had an interest in
seeing that none of the crew members survived. Many people agreed
with a Moscow-based musician, Alexander Nikolayev, who said ``they
hid the truth from us for days, and that was enough to have tried
to save the crew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is always the way it is in Russia, where the state has
its interests and people don't matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians expressed little trust in the statements by
officials, who kept quiet about the Kursk accident until two days
after the navy found the boat on the seabed. Then, officials termed
the incident a ``malfunction'' and implied that they were in
contact with the crew, although they refused to issue a list of
those on board.
</P>
<P>
   At first officials said divers could not go down because of the
weather. Then, when it became clear Russia lacked its own expert
deep-sea divers, the Russian government did not immediately accept
Norway's and Britain's offer to help (and never accepted a US
offer), instead insisting until Wednesday that the Russian navy had
all the equipment it needed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, four days after the Kursk sank, Putin gave the go-ahead to
ask for Wesern help. After that, the Russian navy had to wait until
Sunday for the divers to get in position. By then, a Russian
admiral had already stated that most of the crew were probably
dead, in what he termed ``the gravest disaster'' he had seen in the
history of Russian submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian deep-sea divers discharged by the navy for
lack of funds say their own offers to help were rebuffed, according
to the Moscow newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kursk incident has seen Russian admirals behaving as if
they were back in Soviet times,'' a Russian defense analyst,
Alexander Golts, wrote in The Russia Journal, an English-language
weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The timing for such a comment could not be more poignant. Monday
marks the anniversary of the collapse of the 1991 coup by Soviet
hardliners.
</P>
<P>
   At that euphoric time, the failure of the putsch was widely
celebrated in Moscow and other cities as the beginning of a new,
democratic era in Russia. Sunday, only a handful of people stood
vigil at a monument for three young men who died during the
three-day coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, everything has changed, but nothing has
changed,'' one man said of the Kursk incident.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, who has been criticized in the
Russian media for not cancelling his working vacation on the Black
Sea during the Kursk crisis, made a public effort to share in his
country's pain Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are aching, all of us,'' Putin said, looking weary
and grim. ``Sometimes events rather than us dictate what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
