<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7281 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-     08-20 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN WEIGHED TO OPEN SUNKEN SUBMARINE'S HATCH WITH CRANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Having found no signs of life more than a week after
the Russian submarine Kursk plunged to the bottom of the Barents
Sea, rescue teams were preparing a plan Sunday to use a ship's
crane to rip a hatch off the giant vessel and begin the grim task
of recovering bodies and a lengthy and dangerous mission to salvage
the submarine's twin nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   In their first full day of work, a team of Norwegian divers
working with the Russians found the rear escape hatch on the
490-foot vessel badly damaged, a Russian official said, and the
divers failed in repeated attempts to muscle it open by hand and
with powerful, special tools.
</P>
<P>
   The divers reported that hatchway valves had been opened from
the inside. It is likely that the body of one of the submarine's
118 crew members lies in the air lock chamber and that the chamber
is filled with water, said Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who
is heading the investigation into the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   His description of the grim discovery was broadcast by Russian
television from the deck of the cruiser Peter the Great and was
consistent with remarks Saturday by Vice Adm. Mikhail Mostak, chief
of staff of Russia's Northern Fleet, indicating that one or more
members of the Kursk crew may have tried to make a desperate escape
from the submarine, only to perish when seawater under great
pressure rushed in.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of frenetic work at a depth of more than 300 feet, the
Norwegian navy team sent back vivid pictures of the escape hatch
that has defied nearly a week of efforts to open it. The divers
pounded with hammers on the hull hoping that their soundings would
locate any remaining air pockets inside.
</P>
<P>
   As they worked in teams of three in six-hour shifts, the divers
sent up requests for special tools to turn the hatch valves, and
some tools were fabricated on board the Norwegian vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, two Norwegian divers flew by helicopter to the
Russian submarine base at Vidyaevo, the Kursk's home port, to
practice opening and entering hatches on one of the Kursk's sister
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Planning was under way to rip the Kursk's hatch cover off by
force, according to Klebanov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joint commission made a decision to open the top hatch of
the rescue lock chamber,'' he said, referring to the escape chamber
that passes through the hull, with inner and outer hatches that
allow emergency exit from the submarine. ``Unfortunately, they
failed to open it for several hours though very powerful tools have
been used.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision was made to try to rip it off with the help of a
crane on the Norwegian rescue ship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials reported that air pockets might still exist in
the compartment below the inner hatch, but they expressed no
expectations that any survivors could be found, though a Norwegian
military spokesman in Oslo, Kjell Grandhagen, said, ``We are still
working on the theory that we are looking for possible survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's Rear Adm. Einar Skorgen, who is directing the Norwegian
rescue contingent, said the timing of the hatch removal was not
set. ``We have to clarify the consequences of opening it,'' he told
Norwegian television.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent cooperative spirit among Russian, British and
Norwegian rescue crews was somewhat undermined Sunday night when
the spokesman for the Norwegian armed forces, speaking in Oslo,
contradicted Klebanov's statements that the escape hatch was too
severely damaged to be opened manually, or with the British LR5
rescue submarine that arrived on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not drawn the conclusion that the hatch is so damaged
that it cannot be opened,'' the spokesman, John Epsen Lien, told
Reuters. ``We think it should be possible to open it with a British
or Russian rescue capsule.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Klebanov had said that video images of the hatch showed
a serious crack in the donut-shaped ring around it that is used to
create an airtight seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we think the British sub will not be able to
dock,'' Klebanov said, adding that he believed that the Norwegian
divers would agree to enter the Kursk after studying the entryway
on one of the Kursk's sister ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their commander is now asking them who will go and it is
already clear that someone will go,'' Klebanov said.
``Psychologically, it is very difficult but there is assuredness
that several people will agree and the operation will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials have yet to confirm that their divers will
enter the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   What lies ahead after the hatch is opened is a complex and
dangerous investigation of the Kursk's nine compartments. Dangerous
battery acids, unexploded weapons and highly radioactive fuel
elements in the Kursk's twin reactors could pose a serious danger
to the recovery operation.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have speculated about plans to lift the rear
section of the submarine with surface ships and drag the vessel to
shallower water for easier access by salvage divers. With winter
already approaching in the Arctic region, it seemed possible that
the salvage operation could carry over to next spring, but Russian
officials have as yet given no definite accounting of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   As the Norwegian divers worked Sunday, Russian President
Vladimir Putin met in Moscow with senior clergymen of the Russian
Orthodox Church and expressed the powerlessness he felt over the
loss of the 118-member crew.
</P>
<P>
   The attack submarine went down Aug. 12 during military
maneuvers. Two explosions apparently ripped through the hull of the
submarine as it was running at periscope depth, and sent it
crashing to the seabed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With sorrow in our hearts and, I do not exaggerate, tears in
our eyes, we are following all that is happening in the Barents
Sea,'' he said. ``The sailors are doing everything they can to save
their comrades, but, alas, sometimes events _ and not us _ dictate
the logic of how a situation develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``until the last minute we will do all that can
be done to save whomever can be saved. We will struggle for the
lives of each of our sailors, and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Putin remained at the Kremlin Sunday, despite calls for
him to travel to Severomorsk, the naval headquarters near the scene
of the disaster, the Russian president held a long conversation
with Igor Spassky, Russia's leading submarine designer.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's public remarks, delivered in an unusually somber and
deliberate tone as he stood in front of the golden brocade walls of
one of the churches inside the Kremlin walls, appeared in part to
be in response to a swell of criticism that the Russian military,
and Putin personally, were too slow to seek foreign assistance in
the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   An investigating commission, headed by Klebanov, announced on
Saturday that preliminary findings showed that the Kursk was
involved in a collision with an object near the surface weighing
8,000 tons or more. He said it was possible that the object was a
ship or a World War II mine.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Klebanov said, some unknown chain of events could have
triggered a massive internal explosion aboard the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Russian officials say most of the crew died in the
first two minutes after the explosion, including all officers on
the bridge. They say that the pressure of seawater rushing in
compressed the air in the hull and reduced the chances for survival
beyond a few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
