<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRUMAN-LIKE STYLE, GORE AND LIEBERMAN PROMISE BROADER HEALTH
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 13,14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. _ Comparing his increasingly populist pitch to that
of Harry S. Truman, but leaving his running mate to
``give-them-hell,'' Vice President Al Gore vowed Sunday to fight
drug companies and health maintenance organizations in bringing
broader and fairer health coverage to all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   At the first of four appearances Sunday in Illinois and Iowa,
all of them in towns along the Mississippi River, Gore said he
would push for a patients' bill of rights to protect HMO consumers
and for adding a prescription drug benefit under the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, we will flat make it
happen,'' Gore promised a crowd of about 3,000 in downtown Moline.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of
Connecticut, used their speeches here to draw on the Trumanesque
imagery that has enthralled Democrats for more than half a century.
But Gore left it to Lieberman to assail the health care record of
his Republican opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore made only passing references to the Republicans,
Lieberman charged that 1.4 million children in Texas do not have
health insurance, that Texas leads the nation in the percentage of
residents who are uninsured and that it ranks next to last in
health care for women.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Bush often responds to criticisms of his state by
saying ``don't mess with Texas.'' But, he asserted, ``when it comes
to health care, it's a mess in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day riverboat tour down the Mississippi, Gore left
the slow-moving ship and traveled by bus Sunday so he could make
all four cities on his schedule. Gore and his wife, Tipper, were
rejoined by Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, who had left the trip
in Wisconsin on Friday to observe the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates clearly have been buoyed by polls showing they
received a significant boost from last week's Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles, and they have been received
enthusiastically by sizable crowds. ``I'm no expert as to what to
make of it,'' Gore told reporters, ``but it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   As in his convention speech on Thursday night, Gore accepted
credit Sunday for the economic health of the Clinton years but said
there was more work to be done. He noted, for instance, that 15
percent of all Americans are still without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some serious problems in our health care system,''
he said, his voice still hoarse from his convention speech, ``and
we've got to fix them without undermining the good things about our
health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would move incrementally toward a system of
universal health care, starting with guaranteed coverage for every
child by 2004. And he said the country owes its older citizens a
prescription drug benefit, a proposal estimated to cost $253
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people have bills for pills that are more than their
Social Security check,'' Gore said, ``it is wrong for our country
to put seniors, the generation that won World War II, in a
situation where they have to choose between food and medicine when
the drug companies have the biggest profits of any industry in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies, Gore said, do not support such plans because
they fear that drug prices will come down. ``Well, they need to
come down,'' he said. ``They need more competition.'' He added:
``I'll be like Harry Truman. I'll tell them the truth and they'll
just think it's hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then switched targets from the drug companies to HMOs that
he charges with making financial decisions that usurp medical
recommendations. ``Some bean counter behind a computer terminal who
doesn't have a license to practice medicine and surely does not
have a right to play god overrules the doctor because the HMO or
the insurance company doesn't want to shell out the money, even
though you've been paying the monthly premium,'' Gore said. ``What
is that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal for a patients' bill of rights, campaign aides
say, would assure access to specialists, would guarantee emergency
room care regardless of when and where the need arises, and would
provide either a right to sue or an alternative appeals process if
insurers deny coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign criticizes Bush's proposed bill of rights
because it would cover only those Americans in federally governed
health care plans, a restriction that Gore aides say would exclude
135 million people with private insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
