<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CRITICS-ESSAY-NYT     08-20 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITICS-ESSAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR THE PIONEER SPIRIT IN AMERICAN CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a few days ago I came across these lines from a letter
Nietzsche wrote in 1884 about an essay by Ralph Waldo Emerson. He
was having it translated into German, he said, adding this lament:
``I do not know how much I would give if only I could bring it
about,  &UR; ex post facto &LR; , that such a glorious, great nature, rich in
soul and spirit, might have gone through some  &UR; strict &LR;  discipline,
a really  &UR; scientific education &LR; . As it is, in Emerson we have  &UR; lost
a philosopher &LR;  ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Why did this stay with me? Because of Nietzsche's near pity for
the man American scholars and critics deem a founding father of our
literature and thought. Nietzsche is telling his philosopher friend
that Emerson is wonderfully gifted but untrained, even culturally
deprived. And, oh dreary irony, this is just what many academic
champions of Emerson today say when they hold him up to face down
lesser-known works by American writers they consider faddishly
multicultural.
</P>
<P>
   These words also struck me because I had been reading some
Emerson a few months before, and without pretending I could judge
him as a philosopher, I had decided that his prose moved
frustratingly between the glorious, the earnest and the mushy. It's
my belief that pioneers of American literature like Emerson,
Thoreau, Whitman and Hawthorne matter not because of the perfection
of their method (Poe's stories come closest to formal perfection)
but because of their need, given the content of their lives and
imaginations, to invent or alter language and form. To an American
scholar, Emerson is making his way through answers and toward
questions in a form he invents as he goes along. To Nietzsche he
was meandering across ideas, a bit like the White Queen in
``Through the Looking Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of criticism can be depressing or infuriating if you
happen to worship its object. But it's also useful. It shows how
even a radical genius like Nietzsche abided by some of the
standards of his day, standards that will eventually be challenged
or thrown out. We all know how the laudable artistic and
intellectual standards of one age become the limiting conventions
of the next.
</P>
<P>
   Readers and writers of the past _ not just the geniuses, either,
the intelligent, alert ones who kept current as we all like to
think we do _ remind us how culture and taste change. And why. What
aesthetic, social and intellectual needs do beliefs serve in their
time? Which ones serve us now and why?
</P>
<P>
   The United States was just an upstart culture in the Europe of
1884; today it is a world power. Americans have long since produced
their own definitions of the strict discipline and formal
perfection Nietzsche invoked. But I believe (and I'm hardly alone)
that what distinguishes American art in all its variety is
idiosyncrasy, improvisation and a willingness, even at the cost of
imperfection, to break old forms and try new ones.
</P>
<P>
   And I think American critics need to live by the same criteria.
For instance, just what do we mean when we use the phrase ``serious
art'' or ``high art''? Does a minor work by a major composer
(Mozart, say) _ played no more than adequately, in a respected hall
under an unremarkable conductor _ qualify as truly high or serious?
No, I'd say: it's ho-hum entertainment and middlebrow art passing
as high art. The difference between it and a respectable but
unexceptional television show? The Mozart exudes cultural virtue;
you are meant to feel worthier because you paid attention to it. It
might send you back (or forward) to better works and performances
of Mozart. And if you're alert enough to be dissatisfied, the
television show might send you on to to better television, film or
theater.
</P>
<P>
   What are we to make of works that flaunt their highbrow
credentials in a style clearly meant to capture a mass audience?
Consider Harold Bloom's best-selling book ``Shakespeare: The
Invention of the Human.'' (Riverhead). It gives us many, many pages
of educated, entertaining and highly particular observations on the
plays. And then Bloom lards them over with a polemic against all
critics who dare to read Shakespeare with the politics and
ideologies of his age _ and ours _ in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Idiosyncrasy belongs as much to criticism as to art. And on
those grounds I can accept sentences like ``Whether we are male or
female, old or young, Falstaff and Hamlet speak most urgently for
us and to us ... When we are wholly human, and know ourselves, we
become most like either Hamlet or Falstaff.'' But Bloom doesn't
appear to think he is just showing off for us; he calls this
universality. It seems that when an academic wants to become a
star, he must become a vaudevillian, performing so outrageously
that to enjoy his skills we must be able to laugh at his
absurdities.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting how often we critics believe ourselves above
and beyond the fallibilities of artists and audiences. In last
week's New York Observer there was a stern denunciation of the
artist Barbara Kruger and her retrospective show at the Whitney
Museum of American Art. The critic, Hilton Kramer, insisted that
Kruger's satire on cultural greed and pretension, embodied in her
photograph of a Howdy-Doodyish face with the slogan ``When I hear
the word culture I reach for my checkbook'' written on it, was
hypocritical. Why? Because her work is commercially successful.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote: ``We all disapprove of other people's greed, but most
of us don't get paid for saying so.'' The ``most'' is all right,
but the ``us'' is a big problem. Critics get paid regularly for
disapproving of other people's greed, taste, judgment and skill.
And some make more money than many of the artists they (excuse me,
we) judge. What will future readers make of us? It's foolish to
hope they will find us infallible. Let's hope they find us
ferociously curious and eager to be educated again and again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
