<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FINDS HIS OWN GROOVE IN A PLACE CALLED CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. _ In the Gore camp, there has been much talk about
the need to gain separation from President Clinton, to set Al Gore
apart as his own man with his own style, message and persona.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, in a most surprising way, Gore took a step toward
doing just that. He did it by becoming more like Clinton, and he
did it best of all in a place called Clinton, a small Iowa town set
back from the banks of the Mississippi River. There, on the lawn of
the county courthouse, Gore put in a performance more reminiscent
of Clinton's two presidential campaigns than of Gore circa 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived hours late, filled his speech with twangy
Southernisms, spoke with a populist passion that had the crowd
roaring, danced with his wife, and then stayed late into the cool
summer night to shake every hand he could reach. Normally not known
to linger at the rope line, Gore plunged again and again toward
knots of onlookers, posing for group photographs, kissing babies,
tweaking a little boy's nose, signing autographs, slapping high
fives _ reveling in the crowd in much the same way Clinton is
famous for doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you with me?'' Gore shouted from the stage. ``Yeah!'' the
crowd yelled back.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign sometimes notable for staging events with the
pizazz of a tax seminar, Gore's appearance in Clinton was one of
his most energetic and effective in more than a year of
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness, gracious,'' said Mary Ruth Michelson, 70, who
waited four hours for a glimpse of Gore, but never expected
anything quite so lively. ``What on earth has gotten into him?''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his speech, Gore and his wife, Tipper, danced
under a spray of confetti, and they looked so loose and natural
that one grizzled union organizer in the audience wondered whether
the notoriously wooden Gore had undergone a body transplant. By
contrast, Iowa's governor, Tom Vilsack, looked stiff and
uncomfortable _ think of the old Gore _ trying to boogie up on a
stage in front of several thousand people.
</P>
<P>
   Then again Gore had a slight advantage. Before his arrival in
Clinton aboard the Mark Twain riverboat, Gore had been dancing with
gusto during a birthday celebration for his wife on the boat's top
deck. In another echo of Clinton, who was known to cultivate
relationships with journalists during his presidential campaigns,
the Gores invited reporters to join the festivities in a rare
extended off-the-record session.
</P>
<P>
   A Day for Faith and Family
</P>
<P>
   In purely political terms, it may not have been the ideal time
to take a day off from the campaign trail. Just as Gore and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, were trying to build momentum
from the Democratic National Convention, just as they were trying
to give their political partnership a memorable national identity,
and right as the campaign held the attention of a large traveling
press corps, Lieberman and his family all but disappeared to
observe the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman dropped off the campaign trail Friday afternoon and
spent much of the next day in seclusion with his family at the
Radisson Hotel in La Crosse, Wis. On Saturday morning, the
Lieberman family attended services at Congregation Son's of
Abraham, the only synagogue in town. In accordance with their
Orthodox faith, which prohibits driving on the Sabbath, the
Liebermans walked the mile and a half from their hotel to the
synagogue. Accompanied by Secret Service agents and a few aides and
reporters, the Liebermans paused along the way to greet residents
who came out of their homes to say hello.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were allowed inside the synagogue, but cameras,
notepads and tape recorders were not welcomed. Lieberman was
invited to read from the Torah, but he avoided making any remarks
that could be construed as overtly political, again in accordance
with his religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, Gore was winding his way down the Mississippi,
delivering forceful, populist stump speeches to thousands of people
in small towns and cities where Lieberman is largely an unknown.
Gore regularly paused to praise Lieberman, but he never felt the
need to explain the reason for Lieberman's absence, a reflection of
his stated desire to incorporate Lieberman's Orthodox practices
into the rhythm of campaigning with as little fanfare as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sabbath is his private time for his faith and his family,
and that's all I'm going to say,'' said Lieberman's campaign press
secretary, Kiki McClean.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides reasoned that regardless the cost of Lieberman
being off the national stage one day every week, many voters will
admire a clear display of commitment to religion above political
ambition. And there was another benefit: On Friday, Lieberman's
voice was raw and hoarse. Sunday morning, when he rejoined Gore in
Moline, his voice was back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for Falling Signs
</P>
<P>
   For those charged with shaping Gore's image, his four-day trip
down the Mississippi has been a feast of useful symbolism. What
better way to convey a politician of mainstream, heartland values
than to put him aboard the Mark Twain riverboat decorated with red,
white and blue bunting?
</P>
<P>
   But even on this tightly scripted journey, events have sometimes
intervened in ways that turned the symbolism upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Take Saturday morning in Dubuque, Iowa, where Gore gave a speech
on a low bluff overlooking the Mississippi. At stage right,
organizers had erected a huge sign that read, ``Gore Iowa 2000.''
Unfortunately, minutes before Gore was to take the stage, the
``Iowa 2000'' part of the sign collapsed to the ground with a thud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
