<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NECE TAKES THE WRITE PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ryan Nece could return to practice today for the
first time since the middle of last week because of a sore left
shoulder. The linebacker insists the injury isn't writer's cramp.
</P>
<P>
   Nece, beginning in June, has written a bi-monthly column -
Nece's Notes - for UCLA's internet site, uclabruins.fansonly.com,
detailing his summer on and off the field, Q&AMP;A sessions with
teammates and concluding with a biblical quotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a good opportunity to show people what
it's like to be a football player and take people inside the locker
room,'' said Nece, whose writing is earnest if not as saucy as the
seminal ``Ball Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans Only, the company that manages all but one of the
Pacific-10 schools' sites, suggested the columns to schools as a
hook to pull in readers during the slow summer months. UCLA sports
information director Marc Dellins thought immediately of Nece.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well spoken, he's intelligent, he's a starter,'' Dellins
said. ``He's got all the tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Nece writes his column on his own computer, then e-mails it to
Dellins who edits it and forwards it to be posted. Dellins says the
only editing he does is for grammar, though in one column he had to
remove the name of a restaurant Nece praised for its low prices and
good food; NCAA rules prohibit athletes from endorsing products.
</P>
<P>
   Among the subjects Nece has written about are the off-season
conditioning program and his trip to Canton, Ohio, for the
induction of his father, Ronnie Lott, into the NFL Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to be creative,'' Nece said. ``But it's hard to come
up with something new. Sometimes I think, did I write about this
last week? Let me know if you've got any ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks like Paus: Cory Paus did nothing in Saturday's
scrimmage to dispel the notion that he'll start against Alabama.
Paus completed 7 of 10 passes for 184 yards and a touchdown, and
Ryan McCann was 6 of 9 for 155 yards, two touchdowns and one
interception during the nearly two-hour scrimmage before 2,000
donors at Drake Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Toledo could name a starter as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   While the first-team defense looked good against the second-team
offense - it went three series without allowing a first down - the
reserve defenders looked shoddy, giving up a number of big plays.
``I was disappointed in the second group,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Just rewards: A pair of seldom-used, fifth-year seniors, running
back Mike Vanis and defensive tackle Kory Lombard, have been
awarded scholarships. They became available, as did one for
starting safety candidate John Hall, when Julius Williams
(academics), Lovell Houston (transfer) and Santi Hall (quit) left
school last week.
</P>
<P>
   Since all three scholarship recipients are seniors and Houston,
Williams and Santi Hall were underclassmen, the Bruins will have
three more to give next year, bumping their current total to 18.
They've received eight oral commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: The time for the Oregon State game Oct. 21 has been
set for 3:30 p.m., meaning the Bruins will have just one night game
this year, Sept. 30 against Arizona State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
