</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FITE-HAMED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMED A LIGHTNING PUNCHER, NOT JUST A CLOWN PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ The punches from the featherweight
champion Naseem Hamed came so fast that even if you were staring at
Hamed's hands, you missed them. One man blindsided by their speed
was Hamed's opponent, Augie Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth round of Hamed's World Boxing Organization
title defense late Saturday night, and Hamed threw a three-punch
connection. Or was it four? With a Hamed fight, replay is a
necessity because the eyes play tricks.
</P>
<P>
   The punches were actually a left, then a right, then a left.
They were enough to end the fight with 2 minutes 34 seconds left in
the round and send Sanchez toward the canvas. Then Hamed threw a
final right for good measure _ a bone-crunching blow that, as it
connected with Sanchez's head, could be heard throughout the arena
at Foxwoods Resort Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was knocked almost unconscious and, as a precaution,
spent the night at a hospital. A hospital spokeswoman said Sanchez
was released early Sunday morning and was in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   So what is worse? Getting hit by a 250-pound National Football
League linebacker or by a punch from the 126-pound Hamed? Neither
is pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanchez fight showed the two sides of Hamed. He displays
scary punching power, which ranks among the best of the lighter
boxers. That power, along with his speed, is the main reason Hamed
is 35-0 with 31 knockouts and 15 title defenses in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is the meatball Hamed, the showboat who sometimes
sacrifices his boxing skills for showmanship. His entrance to the
fight consisted of chants in Arabic, rap music and dancing. The
only thing missing from Hamed's introduction was Elvis
impersonators. But they were at the fight as well, brought by
Sanchez, who was born in Las Vegas. So Hamed was not the only
showoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez (26-2) got serious once the fight began, while Hamed was
still playing the ham. In the second round, Hamed was knocked down,
though it was ruled a slip by the referee, Michael Ortega. And by
the fourth round, Hamed was bleeding from the mouth and nose and
had a swollen left eye.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each time Hamed was knocked down or hit hard, he would smile
at Sanchez, indicating he was not seriously hurt and displaying a
toughness that complements his boxing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what other fighters do,'' Hamed said after the
fight, ``but when I get hit and go down, I smile and I say, `I'm
going to hit you harder than you hit me, and I'm going to knock you
out.' The times I go down and get back up _ that's when I'm the
most dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamed is at a critical stage in his career. First, he faces a
mandatory title defense on Nov. 4 against Koko Kovacs, possibly in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Then there could be two big opportunities to increase his
presence in the United States. So far, boxing fans here have not
flocked to watch Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, Hamed could make his American pay-per-view
debut against the 122-pound Marco Antonio Barrera, a top junior
featherweight. Then in May, Hamed might fight the undefeated Erik
Morales, who would be one of his tougher opponents.
</P>
<P>
   What Hamed is trying to do now is gain more respect from his
critics, many of whom do not rank him among the top 10
featherweights in boxing history despite his record and number of
title defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed also wants to gain more fans in America, but to do so, he
knows he needs to fight better opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed has not demonstrated much maturity in the ring. He often
fools around with his opponents, like a puppy playing with a new
toy, before he finally gets serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will prove myself in America,'' he said. ``I agree that some
of my performances in America, apart from having drama and
excitement, have been a little under my estimation for
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hamed continues to be one of the most exciting
boxers in the sport. With those speedy hands, he can't help but
be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
