<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATES-695&AMP;     08-20 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATES-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 CAMPAIGN AIDES SET STAGE FOR NEXT BIG TEST IN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A senior adviser to Vice President Al Gore
accused Gov. George W. Bush on Sunday of trying to dodge _ or at
least minimize the impact of _ presidential debates, while one of
Bush's top aides said the governor was ready and willing but was
still mulling over the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think George Bush wants to engineer these debates so the
fewest number of people see them,'' said Bob Shrum, the Gore
adviser, on the ABC News program ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrum was referring to the fact that while Bush has pledged to
participate in three debates, he has not agreed specifically to the
three proposed by the bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates, which has sponsored all the presidential debates since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Karen P. Hughes, director of communications for the Bush
campaign, said on the same program that the governor was simply
giving himself time to consider more than 40 debate invitations
from an array of potential sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is committed to debating,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   This inevitable debate over debates, conducted in slightly
raised and sometimes overlapping voices on the Sunday morning talk
shows, was the opening of a new chapter in the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The certain high point of this phase will be the televised,
face-to-face encounters between Gore and Bush. And the weeks
leading to those events are already giving rise to aggressive
public posturing, febrile private negotiations and all-out efforts
from each campaign to make sure its candidate ultimately enters the
arena with just the right build-up.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has been portraying Bush as a neophyte
frightened of any format that requires him to give lengthy answers
and to stray beyond sound bites. Gore's advisers repeatedly note
that Gore has, either formally or informally, agreed to dozens of
debates _ even though such a number is almost logistically
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign moved to blunt that line of attack late last
week by announcing that Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney,
would agree to a total of five debates _ a ``modern-day record,''
as Hughes put it.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes and other officials with the Bush campaign have also been
talking loudly about what a fierce debater Gore is, a clear attempt
to lower the expectations for Bush to the point where he is
guaranteed to exceed them.
</P>
<P>
   And campaign officials have been busily analyzing and
deconstructing videotapes and transcripts of Gore's debates back to
1988, when he ran for the Democratic presidential nomination, a
senior adviser to Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the Republican National Committee, the adviser
said, the Bush campaign has assembled a thick book of research into
Gore's debate performances and has even diagrammed Gore's typical
debate response: an expression of empathy about the issue at hand,
followed by an explanation of the remedy he is offering, followed
by a pointed attack on his opponent's record or proposal.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bush campaign months ago recruited Sen. Judd Gregg,
R-N.H., to prepare for and play the part of Gore in debate
rehearsals. Gregg did the same for Jack Kemp, the Republican vice
presidential nominee in 1996, in advance of his debate with Gore
that year.
</P>
<P>
   The debates have begun to loom larger with the emergence of
signs that the race between Bush and Gore is tightening. A USA
Today-CNN-Gallup poll released Sunday showed Gore moving from a
16-point disadvantage against Bush before the Democratic National
Convention to a one-point advantage after the convention.
</P>
<P>
   That poll, which had a sampling error of plus or minus four
percentage points, reflected interviews on Friday and Saturday with
697 likely voters. It put Gore, who had the support of 47 percent
of respondents, and Bush, with 46 percent, in a four-way contest
with Ralph Nader, with 3 percent, and Pat Buchanan, with 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said Sunday that they had always expected that
Gore would get an enormous bounce immediately after his convention
and that the race would be close to even by about now. They said
that the more meaningful poll results would come around Labor Day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The competing pitches and warring putdowns as aides to Gore and
Bush stormed the television airwaves Sunday morning gave a tidy
preview of the campaign to come.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of fiscal responsibility, Gore's advisers moved to
defend the amount of spending that the vice president had outlined
in his convention speech, while Bush's advisers defended the size
of the Texas governor's proposed tax cut of $1.3 trillion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the chief strategist for the Bush campaign, said on
the NBC program ``Meet the Press'' that Bush, who has yet to offer
a detailed plan for overhauling Medicare or creating a
prescription-drug benefit for the elderly, would be tackling health
care shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the campaign's budget projections for the next decade
showed that Bush still had ``$900 billion for additional spending
and for deficit reduction'' after his tax cut. ``More than
enough,'' he said, for a program to expand prescription-drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our proposals total up to about $400-and-some-odd
billion thus far,'' said Rove, referring to plans that did not yet
include health care. ``We have close to $500 billion unspent.''
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns also tangled over which party and which
politicians deserved the blame for the unfinished business of the
Clinton administration on issues like Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Daley, the chairman of the Gore campaign, who also
appeared on ``Meet the Press,'' told Rove: ``I would just say that
Newt Gingrich and the Republican leadership in the House and Senate
over the last eight years haven't been exactly willing to work with
President Clinton or Vice President Gore, and that's one of the
reasons why we've had a stalemate on important issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Rove said: ``To some degree, Mr. Daley's right. But
the buck stops on the president's desk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Rove added, ``the vice president claims that he's been
part of every important decision over the last eight years. I can
think of very few more important decisions than what is the tone
with which we're going to approach our relationships with
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ABC program ``This Week,'' Shrum, the Gore aide, said the
Bush campaign was not eager for debates, because Bush did not want
to have a substantive discussion of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes shot back, ``That's just outrageous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
