<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS' VIEWS SPLIT ON INTERNET PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN STELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the continuing battle between Internet companies that want to
use customers' personal information to deliver tailored
advertisements and services and privacy advocates who want stricter
controls over how this information is used, consumers themselves
appear to be of two minds.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the finding of a survey whose results were
released Sunday night by the Pew Research Center for People and the
Press, a nonprofit group. While many consumers surveyed expressed
concern about their privacy, many also said they were willing to
share personal information with the Web sites they used. And many
Internet users in the survey sample indicated that they did not
understand how their online activities were observed and did not
take advantage of tools to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which surveyed 2,117 Americans, 1,017 of whom were
Internet users, found that 86 percent of the Internet users favored
``opt in'' privacy policies, which require Internet companies to
obtain people's permission before using their personal data. This
preference is in contrast to the policy recently negotiated by the
Clinton administration, the Federal Trade Commission and a group of
Internet advertisers, which gives Web sites the right to track
visitors unless those users ``opt out'' of being monitored.
</P>
<P>
   On a similar note, 54 percent of Internet users in the survey
said that the tracking of users by a Web site was harmful because
it invaded their privacy, compared with 27 percent who described it
as helpful because it allowed sites to tailor information to
specific consumers.
</P>
<P>
   And 94 percent of the Internet users agreed that any company
that violated its privacy policy should be disciplined _ with 11
percent of the disciplinarians saying the company's owners should
be sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this hard line, the Pew survey revealed a deep pocket of
trust among Internet users. Slightly more than half said they had
provided personal information to a Web site and an additional 10
percent said they would provide it under the right circumstances.
Only 27 percent said they would never provide a Web site with
personal information. Just less than half _ 48 percent _ said they
had bought something online with a credit card and 22 percent said
they had posted personal information on online calendars or online
address books.
</P>
<P>
   As for efforts to protect their privacy, the survey indicated
that many Internet users were either unaware of how they were being
monitored online or unlikely to take steps to prevent being
tracked. The report noted that 56 percent of Internet users could
not identify the primary online tracking tool _ a ``cookie'' file
placed on a user's computer by a Web site _ and only 10 percent of
the Internet users had set their browser software to reject
cookies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NUCLEAR-SPY-NYT &LR;      08-20 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARROGANCE OR ESPIONAGE? U.S. CLAIMS AT LOS ALAMOS TRIAL IN
QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Of all the unusual aspects of what is
shaping up to be one of the most important espionage cases of the
post-Cold War era _ the trial here of Wen Ho Lee _ none is more
striking than the fact that it is not an espionage trial at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a 59-count indictment, Lee, a former nuclear scientist at Los
Alamos National Laboratory, is charged with having illegally
downloaded a virtual library of nuclear weapons design and test
data with the intent of harming the United States. It is a crime
that carries a possible life sentence. But the government has
specifically said it will not raise espionage at the trial and has
acknowledged repeatedly that it has no evidence that Lee ever
handed over nuclear secrets to anyone. In their bill of particulars
the prosecutors said that Lee had taken the data to enhance his job
prospects at scientific institutes in countries like France,
Australia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, Lee struggled, for the third time since his
arrest in December, to be released on bail from the kind of harsh
prison regimen usually reserved for the most nefarious agents. The
government reported that Lee, held in near-solitary confinement in
Sante Fe, is now unshackled during his recreation time, has greater
access to publications and is given more fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing dragged on for three days in the federal district
court here and was characterized by the government's claims that
Lee's crimes were unprecedented in the history of nuclear weapons
spying; that he was the subject of ``classic PRC tradecraft,'' or
Chinese spying techniques, in a mysterious encounter in Beijing 12
years ago; that he might have altered the global balance of
military power; and that he had compromised the United States'
efforts to build a ballistic missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   George Stamboulidis, an assistant United States attorney drafted
from Long Island to prosecute in the trial, said of Lee's actions,
``It's of a caliber where hundreds of millions of people could be
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant result of the government tactic of
characterizing this as an egregious case of espionage may have been
to make the holes the defense punched in the prosecution's case
appear that much more glaring.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most damaging disclosures, an FBI agent conceded
that the government had no evidence that the letters Lee wrote to
the foreign institutes seeking employment in the early 1990s, found
during a search of his home, were ever mailed.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, Robert Messemer, acknowledged that he had incorrectly
described Lee as having resorted to rank deception when he borrowed
a colleague's computer to download the vast trove of weapons
secrets to portable computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer had said in December, in an exchange with the judge,
James A. Parker, specifically cited in his decision to deny Lee
bail at that time, that Lee had told his colleague that he only
wanted to download a resume, when in fact the colleague had made no
such claim.
</P>
<P>
   But this damaging about-face on claims delivered with confidence
at the last bail hearing provided more evidence that two almost
separate exercises are under way in Lee's case _ one highly
personal, the other a policy debate on the nature of nuclear
proliferation and nuclear security in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This split was seemingly buttressed by the judge's surprising
public plea to have the lawyers from each side help him sort out
the long and odd list of issues he must resolve before deciding
whether he will agree to release Lee this time. Some of the issues
relate specifically to Lee's credibility, and others relate to the
hypothetical question of whether Lee might still be able to
transfer some of the secret data to a hostile country, and, if so,
whether it would threaten the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question whether Lee did anything wrong _ his
lawyers all but conceded that he had violated at least some rules
on the handling of classified information. But it is not yet clear
whether what he is accused of doing is a crime worthy of a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been arrogant and he just may have made a stupid
mistake,'' Mark Holscher, one of Lee's lawyers, said in his
summation on Friday, indicating that Lee may have no real defense
for the way in which he downloaded and then handled the data, given
that 7 of the 10 tapes he made are unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The government says that Lee dedicated a great deal of time _
more than 40 hours _ to assembling the secret files, moving them to
an unsecure computer, and then downloading them, but in doing so he
left a lengthy, clumsy paper trail, which he took almost no steps
to cover up. He was even detected during the process, but the
security officer who had monitored the transfer by computer dropped
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue on trial seems to be whether the nuclear test and
bomb feature data that Lee downloaded, is as important as simple
blueprints for constructing bombs, the sort of information
typically prized in traditional spycraft.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, Parker went through some 20 points of concern cited
in his earlier decision, and questioned how many of them should be
re-evaluated light of the new evidence introduced this week, but
gave no indication of when he would make his ruling. And while he
hinted that, at least to some degree, he saw Lee as less devious
now, he also expressed concern about the prospect of the missing
tapes ending up in hostile hands, and how the arcane data might
affect global nuclear policy, a weighty issue for a trial that
supposedly does not concern espionage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
