<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MURMANSK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN THAT LIVES OFF THE SEA MOURNS SUBMARINE DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (MAKES ``Peninsula'' upper case in 8th graf; SUBS 9th graf to
correct attribution;   CORRECTS spelling of town name in 11th
graf)  
 (With RUSSIA-SUBMARINE)  
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURMANSK, Russia _ In this city that lives off the sea, people
know about disaster. But even here, the tragedy of the sunken
submarine Kursk, which entombed 118 sailors, has rattled residents
and brought a hush to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In a corner of the city where most of the navy staff members
live, residents said they noticed an unusual stillness after
officials said on Saturday _ for the first time since the accident
on Aug. 12 _ that most of the crew on the nuclear-powered submarine
probably had died instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood, called Rosta, borders the bay. It is not only
home to many navy people, but also to a navy museum and a submarine
repair factory. Tall grass and bright dots of purple flowers fringe
crumbling cement apartment buildings here. Only a few people were
strolling Sunday afternoon, though the air in this northern city
had warmed since morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so quiet today,'' said Sveta, a 29-year-old mother of
two, wheeling her youngest in a baby carriage. ``We keep thinking
about them, the sailors. The military _ that is the worst
profession. It is bad money and dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   She has lived all her life in Murmansk. Her husband works on a
fishing boat that sails mostly in foreign seas, giving the family
access to much sought after foreign currency. She said that her
husband managed to avoid military service, compulsory in Russia,
after he graduated from college six years ago. Their 10-month-old
son, Dmitri, will follow his father's example when he grows up, if
she has anything to say about it, Sveta said.
</P>
<P>
   The navy has had its share of disasters for vessels from this
fleet. Another nuclear-powered submarine, the Komsomolets, sank off
the coast of Norway in 1989, killing 42 members of the crew after a
fire on board raged out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, federal agents stormed a nuclear-powered
submarine and shot a 19-year-old sailor who had killed eight crew
members.
</P>
<P>
   Many have left this region since the Soviet Union collapsed in
1991, mostly to chase higher wages and better job opportunities
farther south. The Murmansk region, which encompasses all of the
Kola Peninsula, and is home to 983,000 people, has lost about 15
percent of its population since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the region had one of the highest unemployment rates in
the country .According to the state statistics committee, an
average sailor brings home about $85 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the day after the Kursk sailors were declared dead,
residents continued to click on radios and televisions every hour
for the news as the rescue effort dragged on. But Sunday, as they
watched and listened, they seemed numbly resigned to the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Two women behind the counter at the Youth Cafe in central
Murmansk took a break from placing chickens on a roaster to turn on
a radio for news. People in line behind the counter leaned closer
to listen. Few took solace in the fact that foreign rescue crews
began work Sunday. The hospital boat meant for ailing crew members
left for the small town of Vedyaevo, where the sailors' families
are staying. It will instead treat anguished relatives.
</P>
<P>
   There were special prayers in the main church in town Sunday.
The Rev. Andrei Amelin, one of the three priests on duty, spoke of
his past service as a navy officer. The 29-year-old priest served
in the navy for 10 years before joining the church three years ago.
The church began holding special services on Monday as soon as news
of the accident spread.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents said that the mysterious submarine disaster
clearly shows that lives mean little here and that the government
in the Kremlin has lost touch with people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shame, a shame before the whole world,'' said Andrei
Lebedev, a 37-year-old engineer who works on a fishing trawler.
``Everyone knows how much they were being paid. Their lives mean
nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
