<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     08-20 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON WANTS VARGAS AT HIS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ross Thompson doesn't get the whole Fernando
Vargas thing. From his perspective, Vargas is exactly average,
``average speed, average power, basically an average fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an easy fight for me, the way I look at it,'' said
Thompson, a 27-year-old from Buffalo, N.Y., who will try to take
Vargas' IBF junior middleweight title on Saturday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't impress me. He's a decent fighter. I just don't see
nothin' special. I can't understand why people are hyping him up so
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he nuts? Nah. He's calculating.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Thompson, once one of the top amateur fighters in the nation
and now the IBF's No. 1 contender, believes what he's saying. He's
convinced Vargas is overrated. However, he also has been eager to
get under the Oxnard resident's skin for practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to make Vargas angry enough to take him seriously, to
motivate him so when he does the improbable - win the fight - he
will have beaten Vargas at his best.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's how Thompson (24-3-1, with 16 knockouts) has it
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear excuses afterward,'' he said. ``Things
like, 'I wasn't ready when I fought him.' I want him to be up for
this fight. And the only way to do that is get personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make him hate me. I think he fell asleep when he
(barely defeated) Winky Wright. I don't want that to happen. I want
it to be his skill against my skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Thompson, a good boxer, with decent power and an excellent
chin, have enough skill?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   He was among the fine Class of `92 among amateurs, which
included Oscar De La Hoya, Shane Mosley, Vernon Forrest and Stevie
Johnston. He failed to qualify for the Barcelona Games and then won
his first 11 bouts, eight by knockout.
</P>
<P>
   However, he lost the only two big fights of his career, 10-round
decisions to James Page and Oba Carr as a welterweight and hasn't
become a significant figure in the sport as a result.
</P>
<P>
   He had a good excuse in the Carr fight, which took place in June
of 1997. He took the fight weeks after the sudden death of his
father, the third member of his immediate family he's had to bury.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Lamar, a promising pro fighter, died in an
accidental drowning in 1987 and his brother Curtis was stabbed to
death a year later. His father died of heart failure at 52.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he doesn't feel he was prepared psychologically or
physically - he hadn't trained consistently after his father died -
to face a fighter of Carr's ability. Still, he lost a split
decision.
</P>
<P>
   He has won his four bouts since then, three by decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard at the time,'' he said of the deaths in his
family. ``It brought the family very close together. And it made me
want to work harder. God left it to me to carry on with boxing in
the family. My brothers and my father were all boxers and they
weren't able to achieve what they wanted to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe someone in the family was meant to do something
special. I think it's my time.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' response: Apparently, Thompson's strategy is working:
Vargas has taken notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what kind of crack he's been smoking,'' Vargas
said. ``His big mouth has definitely motivated me. I'm always
ready, I always have incentive. I have extra incentive when someone
runs their mouth off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should feel lucky he got a shot at the title. I'm ready to
take this guy out. I want a knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   Think again: For those who are so certain that Evander
Holyfield's victory over John Ruiz was grand larceny, consider
this: 16 of 22 boxing writers who were at ringside had Holyfield
winning (one called it a draw).
</P>
<P>
   These are credible, seasoned boxing writers from all over the
world who are not beholden to promoter Don King, the WBA, Holyfield
or anyone else. They're objective.
</P>
<P>
   So how do we explain the discrepancy among those who were at the
fight and those who watched on TV, who seemed to favor Ruiz?
</P>
<P>
   Simple: Fights often have a different look depending on one's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Those in ringside seats - sometimes just feet from the action -
have a better perspective. Certainly, they have a better feel for
who is in control of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Those at home are seeing the fight through the lens of a camera
and could miss many nuances that are key to scoring. They also hear
the commentary of television analysts, who could cloud their
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   And at least some of Ruiz's own people seemed to think the
decision was within reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny has the heart of a lion and it overcame him,'' Gabe
Mari, his trainer, told the Detroit Free Press. ``Our plan was to
punch and move. He didn't do it. He did it some, but in a lot of
rounds he wanted to fight the guy. Holyfield made it a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Daily News scored it 115-113 for Ruiz
</P>
<P>
   off television.
</P>
<P>
   Action fight: Kevin Kelley will replace Guty Espadas as Erik
Morales' opponent on Sept. 2 in El Paso, Texas, on HBO. Espadas,
the WBC featherweight champion, somehow broke his collarbone in
training and cannot fight.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley probably won't give Morales the fight Espadas would have.
However, it could be immensely entertaining as long as it lasts:
Both fighters like to bang.
</P>
<P>
   The winner likely will face Espadas.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, Kelley probably won't take part in many more fights with
championship implications.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Corrales defends his junior lightweight title against
Angel Manfredy in another compelling bout on the card.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: The World Boxing Hall of Fame, the West Coast
equivalent of the East's International Boxing Hall of Fame, is
expected to open a museum at the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall is collecting memorabilia from its inductees and former
and current world champions. ...
</P>
<P>
   Acelino Freitas of Brazil, one of the more intriguing prospects
in the world, will defend his marginal WBO junior lightweight title
on Showtime's Sept. 23 card in Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Freitas, whose opponent is yet to be determined, has won all 26
of his bouts by knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the card, Harry Simon will defend his WBO junior
middleweight belt against Rodney Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
