<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart, Gordon collide; Wallace wins
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Jeff Gordon threatened last week to put Tony
Stewart ``in the wall'' the next time the two were driving close
together in race. But it was the other way around in Sunday's Pepsi
400, and by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace was the winner at Michigan Speedway. By winning
two of the last four events, Wallace has moved up one position to
fifth in the point standings. He is well within striking distance
of his second Winston Cup championship, 352 points behind leader
Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``The points are definitely on my mind,'' Wallace said. ``I see
myself in the points race until the very end. I just need some of
those other drivers in front of me to have some bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between Wallace and runner-up Ricky Rudd over the
final 33 laps was exciting, but the fans seemed more enamored by
the incident involving Stewart and Gordon on lap 37. It was the
second race in a row in which the two drivers collided on the
track. After the one last week at Watkins Glen, Stewart and Gordon
engaged in a heated argument in the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the only public display of emotions was by the crowd.
Both drivers were booed during driver introductions, with Stewart
recieving the louder feedback from the Michigan fans.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty laps into the event, Stewart and Gordon were actually
working together in the draft to move up among the leaders. The
trouble began when Stewart was racing Dale Earnhardt Jr. for second
place.
</P>
<P>
   The two cars appeared to brush against each other approaching
the second turn. Stewart said his car then ``got loose.'' His No.
20 Pontiac turned sideways as it headed toward the outside wall,
clipping Gordon before it reached the barrier.
</P>
<P>
   As Stewart slowly drove his mangled car down pit road to exit
the track, fans applauded his early departure. Similar to Watkins
Glen, Stewart took the blame for the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I crashed a bunch of people that I didn't mean to crash _ it
was my fault, I just flat-out lost it,'' Stewart said calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's No. 24 Chevy was never the same after the wreck. It was
taken to the garage area for extensive repairs. Gordon returned to
the race but dropped out with seven laps remaining to finish 36th.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gordon was disappointed with the outcome, he expressed
no frustration toward Stewart. He made it clear that Sunday's wreck
had nothing to do with the confrontation at Watkins Glen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had been praying a lot lately, but I'm going to
start praying a lot more,'' Gordon said, managing a smile. ``As far
as I'm concerned, we've just got to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
