<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SMOKING-CANCER-NYT     08-20 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SMOKING-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY IS BIGGEST CONTRIBUTOR TO CANCER-DIAGNOSIS STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City is about to become the largest
contributor to a broad medical study to determine the effectiveness
of an experimental X-ray screening test for diagnosing and treating
the early stages of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The city's contribution of $4 million will come from its share
of the settlement cigarette manufacturers reached with New York
state and other states as compensation for the treatment of
smoking-related illnesses among Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   The study will be the first large-scale look at how effectively
a new generation of X-ray machines, known as spiral CT scanners,
can spot lung tumors that are too small to be seen with a
conventional chest X-ray, said Dr. Maria Mitchell, president of
Academic Medicine Development Co., a nonprofit consortium of 35
academic health centers, research institutions and medical schools
coordinating the statewide project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to determine whether or not this is an effective
screening device in finding early-stage cancers, and whether or not
there are effective interventions at an early stage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year project is to involve as many as 10,000 men and
women 55 or older, most of them from New York City, who smoked on
average a pack of cigarettes a day for 10 years or longer, Mitchell
said. Each participant will receive at least two CT scans, which
normally cost $300 to $700 and are not covered by most health
insurance plans. Participation is free.
</P>
<P>
   In search of the $9.7 million needed to finance the study,
Mitchell and the deans of several of the city's medical school
wrote to Deputy Mayor Anthony P. Coles, a senior adviser to Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, and in January the doctors met with the mayor to
outline their project, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor was supportive,'' Coles said. ``The object of the
program is to help as many people as we can to survive lung cancer.
I think it's going to save many, many lives in New York City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
