<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SPANISH-LANGUAGE-TV-2     08-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPANISH-LANGUAGE-TV-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH-LANGUAGE TV IS ATTRACTING MORE VIEWERS, AND DRAWING MORE
CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On any given Saturday night, a television host known as Don
Francisco holds sway in hundreds of thousands of American homes for
four straight hours with a throwback to American variety shows of
the 1950s, and more. The Miami-based television show ``Sabado
Gigante'' (Giant Saturday) grabs viewers with a mix of musical
performances, contests, comedy, interviews and audience
sing-alongs.
</P>
<P>
   On weeknights, millions of viewers tune in to ``telenovelas,''
the short soap operas with rags-to-riches plots. The genre has been
spiced up considerably this year with the addition of ``Xica'' from
Brazil, which features nudity and a love story between a willful
slave and her former master.
</P>
<P>
   And on weekdays, there is ``Laura en America,'' a Peruvian talk
show where Jerry Springer meets Mother Teresa. The hostess, Laura
Bozzo, is a legal scholar and women's rights advocate who is also
known as the Eva Peron of Peru for creating a foundation to help
the poor and unfortunate, many of whom appear on her show to slap
and shove each other.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the fastest-growing television audience in the
nation watches on Univision Television Network and Telemundo
Network Group, the two Spanish-language networks. In major markets
like New York, the Univision affiliates now outperform some
English-language broadcast stations in the Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The high ratings reflect the steady growth of Latinos in this
country, now estimated to be about 32 million, but as they draw
more viewers, Univision and Telemundo are drawing more criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic organizations boycotted the four big English-language
networks last year for the scarcity of Latinos in television and
got a few commitments to increased diversity. Now, some of the same
groups are pressuring the two Spanish-language networks to address
concerns like the invisibility of dark-skinned Latinos on and off
the air and the preponderance of imported programming that all but
ignores Latinos in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewership is fighting many different barriers to equality
in this country and I think one is entitled to expect a little
better from these folks given that reality,'' said Juan Figueroa,
president and general counsel of the Puerto Rican Legal Defense and
Education Fund in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Univision, which dwarfs Telemundo by capturing about 80 percent
of the Spanish-language television audience in the United States,
is the fifth-most-watched television network in the nation, after
NBC, Fox, ABC and CBS. But while the Big Four have been bleeding
viewers, Univision has been gaining hundreds of thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the Spanish-language programs are essentially
versions of the popular English language formats: the talk show
``Cristina,'' the tabloid show ``Primer Impacto'' (``First
Impact'') and the early morning show ``Despierta America'' (``Wake
Up America''). But newscasts on Spanish-language television, for
which Univision has won two Emmy Awards, offer more coverage of
Latin America and Latinos in this country than anything available
in English.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike the major networks, Univision and Telemundo anchor
their prime time on ``telenovelas,'' offering a block of three,
four and even five in a row on weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, it seems, cannot get enough of them. Of the 20 top
rated shows in Spanish nationally, 15 are telenovelas, Nielsen
figures in early August showed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the English-language soaps, which can last generations,
telenovelas typically wrap up their tortuous plot lines in less
than a year and thus offer a beginning, middle and end.
</P>
<P>
   Hernan Velez, 40, a truck driver from Queens, N.Y., who is a fan
of ``Xica,'' said he watches it as an escape. ``It's a way to
forget about work,'' he said. ``I just relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young Latinas who list shows like ``The West Wing'' and
``Sex and the City'' as favorites somehow find themselves
hopelessly addicted to telenovelas, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say I won't watch the one that's getting started but
I do and I get hooked,'' said Yesenia De Avila, 28, an
entertainment editor at the magazine Latina, who was born in the
United States to Colombian and Honduran parents.
</P>
<P>
   She even admits to clicking on ``Sabado Gigante'' on a slow
Saturday; she said most of her Hispanic friends who were born in
the States find the show ``cheesy,'' but she cannot resist it.
</P>
<P>
   But not all viewers are happy with their choices. Many are
rankled by the dominance of programming from Mexico, Venezuela and
elsewhere in Latin America that has little to do with the lives of
people in this country. Critics say that Spanish television should
play a larger role in familiarizing immigrants with the American
way of life and to link Latinos of different nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   But the only original sitcom or drama currently dealing with the
Latino experience in the United States on Spanish television is
Telemundo's ``Los Beltran,'' which is set in Burbank, Calif., and
features a first-generation Cuban-American family with a daughter
married to a Mexican-American and with a gay couple as neighbors.
(Both Univision and Telemundo have announced two new original
sitcoms for the fall season based on Hispanics living in the United
States.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alex Nogales, president of the National Hispanic Media
Coalition, a watchdog group, points out that this country is full
of story lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a Mexican-American man who meets an immigrant woman
and the clashes of culture?'' he said, naming one. ``They're not
doing enough programs that take into consideration the culture, the
education and legal institutions that are here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say the networks buy foreign shows because they
are cheaper than creating new ones and because people watch them.
Telemundo officials, who said they import 60 percent of their
programming, said that not only do many Latin American countries
have television industries that produce quality programming, but
that the foreign product is also widely accepted in the United
States because of the multinational makeup of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Accents, for instance, are not the big issue for Hispanic
viewers that they are for most English-speaking Americans, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NBC could produce novelas in Ireland that would work in the
United States for a third of the cost, they would do it,'' said
Joaquin F. Blaya, a former president and director of both Univision
and Telemundo who is now chairman and chief executive of Radio
Unica Communications, a national Spanish-language radio network.
</P>
<P>
   But Univision and Telemundo viewers often get a dose of
old-fashioned sexism, racism and stereotypes. The telenovelas, for
instance, have had the tendency to stick women to the traditional
role of mothers or ``Cinderella,'' as in poor young girls whose
only goal in life is to bag the upper-class leading man. Gay men
are often depicted as caricatures. And servile roles are usually
reserved for black, indigenous and dark-skinned actors.
</P>
<P>
   And the stars are so white and blond, critics like Figueroa
said, that they seem to hail from Eastern Europe rather than
Hispanic countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the Mexican novelas and you compare them to the
Mexican people you see in New York, you'd think they were from two
different Mexicos,'' agreed Charlotte Castillo, 28, a colleague of
De Avila at Latina magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike De Avila, Castillo said she seldom watches Spanish
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like `E.R.,' `The Practice,' `Once and Again,''' she said.
``You don't find these types of programs on Spanish-language
television. I don't think it's very smart. Spanish-language
television is like a decade behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Telemundo's ``Xica,'' a telenovela from Brazil that broke
with tradition by having a black woman as its star, is too
unpalatable for some viewers. Loosely based on the true story of
the Brazilian slave Xica da Silva, who won her freedom and rose to
a position of power thanks to her wit and wiles, the drama, which
is dubbed in Spanish, stands out for the nude scenes (albeit in
blurred, censored images) involving Xica and the other slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, as a black woman you're seen as an object of
oversexuality,'' said Evelyne Laurent-Perrault, a founder of
Encounters, Inc., an East Coast group of black Latinos that
advocates racial inclusion. ``To me it isn't any improvement of
television.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also complaints that some Hispanic groups are
underrepresented on Univision and Telemundo. Marco Camacho is
president and chief executive of Hispanic Television Media Network,
a network begun from Texas this year to focus on Mexican-American
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho noted that Mexican-Americans account for more than 60
percent of the nation's Hispanic population but are a minority
among the hosts and actors in productions made in the United
States, which come mostly from Miami, where Univision and Telemundo
have their studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican market doesn't have the same likes and dislikes as
the Cuban or Puerto Rican markets,'' he said. ``They want to hear
jokes that they can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the National Hispanic Media Coalition in New York and
Los Angeles said that over the last year they had met several times
with Henry G. Cisneros, Univision's president until he resigned
this month to form a housing company, to voice their concerns. With
revenues approaching $1 billion a year, critics said, it is time
for Univision to produce more of its own programs, or at least have
more say in what is produced abroad, and deal with the issue of
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Univision's chairman and chief executive, A. Jerrold Perenchio,
does not give interviews and forbids network officials to do so, a
policy cited by the network's publicists for declining requests for
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   James McNamara, Telemundo's president and chief executive, said
his network would have more original productions as its target
audience _ Latinos from 18 to 49 who speak only or mostly Spanish
or who are bilingual _ grew. But McNamara said Telemundo needed to
compete ``head on'' with Univision by offering telenovelas and
other imported programming.
</P>
<P>
   Nely Galan, producer of ``Los Beltran,'' said that the time had
also come to put the onus on the viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Galan said she had counted herself among the networks' critics
until she became Telemundo's president of entertainment in 1998 and
got ``a reality check.'' At that time Telemundo took the
telenovelas off the prime-time lineup to experiment with new
programming like documentaries and original productions.
</P>
<P>
   By August 1999, the telenovelas were back and most of the new
shows were out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the demand is not as high as you'd think for
original productions,'' said Galan, who noted that ``Los Beltran''
survived but that its audience was slow to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are used to watching the same things,'' she said.
``It's time to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Galan said Spanish-language programming was bound to improve as
English-language television started mining the bilingual market
with shows like Showtime's ``Resurrection Boulevard.'' But she said
competition can only do so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have to make people understand the power they have
as viewers,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
