<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE ACCENTUATES THE POSITIVE AFTER LATEST YANKEE DEBACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre can share his unedited emotions with the
world every day to condemn, confront or blame, as manager of the
Yankees. But he seems to sift carefully through his thoughts, to
identify the most presentable, and he might have required a giant
mental colander after the Yankees gave away another game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led Anaheim, 3-0, when Torre replaced David Cone
after six innings Sunday. The bullpen allowed four runs in the
seventh and another in the eighth and was responsible for a 5-4
loss at Yankee Stadium, the second time in three days the Yankees'
bullpen blew a sizable lead.
</P>
<P>
   Torre plaintively answered questions afterward. He reiterated
how excited he is about how Cone is pitching now; what Torre did
not say, as his decisions indicated, is that his confidence in Cone
is not restored fully. Torre mentioned again how important reliever
Jeff Nelson is to the bullpen, and how he expects Nelson will work
through his recent inconsistency; he did not elaborate on Nelson's
unhappy response to being taken out Sunday, or how he intends to
address Nelson's mounting frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has credited the bullpen time and again for much of the
Yankees' success this season. He did not offer the reality that
right now, his middle relief is something of a mess, and somewhat
responsible for the Yankees' inability to pad their slender lead in
the American League East. They are 5-5 in their past 10 games,
playing mediocre teams in the Rangers and the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Torre said of Sunday's loss, ``but it's
not that we're going to do anything different. We'll still send
those guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   They probably should have walked away from this four-game series
with Anaheim with four victories. They could have beaten the Angels
Friday, if they had not blown a five-run lead in the ninth inning _
only the second time the Yankees had done that in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They could have added a fitting finish Sunday, Whitey Ford Day.
The Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, who takes these sorts of
events seriously, was in the clubhouse for the first time in weeks
and greeted most of his team's most recent acquisitions by
extending a handshake and a slap on the shoulder _ David Justice
and Jose Canseco and Glenallen Hill _ and spoke glowingly of what
they had added to the team. ``How could anyone debate that?''
Steinbrenner said rhetorically. ``What they've done is
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was touched by his ceremony, shook hands with Cone before
throwing out the first ball, and Cone pitched well, changing
speeds, striking out the side in the first inning. He fell behind
in the count at times, but did not allow a hit until the fourth.
Clay Bellinger, filling in for the injured center fielder, twice
drew walks and scored on run-scoring hits by Luis Sojo. The Yankees
led, 3-0, after five, although they could have had at least one
more; Sojo had run through the stop sign raised by the third base
coach Willie Randolph and was thrown out at the plate in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Cone threw 79 pitches in the first five innings, and after
Orlando Palmeiro singled with one out in the sixth, the interim
pitching coach Billy Connors visited the mound. Cone appeared
annoyed by this, turning his head with exasperation when he saw
Connors and relievers warming up in the bullpen. He had allowed two
hits and a walk to that point and knew he was on the verge of being
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had 96 pitches after six innings and with the left-handed
slugger Mo Vaughn scheduled to lead off the seventh, Torre _
intending generally to replace him at about 110 pitches _ decided
to replace him. Cone lobbied to stay in the game, ``for the first
time in a long time,'' without success.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's ``response to me was, `You're starting to crawl now and
you're breaking into a jog and you're on your way. Let's take the
positive and I'm going to get you out of there,''' Cone said.
``Sure, maybe there is a little bit of a mixed message there. But
Joe has his reasons and I'm not going to second-guess him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton took over in the seventh, walked Vaughn and allowed
a two-run homer to Tim Salmon. Two batters, two runs. After Garret
Anderson grounded out, Nelson relieved Stanton and walked Troy
Glaus on four pitches _ the eighth time in Nelson's past 13
appearances he has allowed a walk or a hit to the first batter he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus stole second easily, taking advantage of Nelson's big leg
kick. Nelson whiffed Bengie Molina, but Adam Kennedy poked a
grounder inside the third base line, Glaus scored the tying run,
and the booing was loud and pointed.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitter Kevin Stocker was scheduled to bat next, and
Torre preferred to force Stocker to bat from his weaker side, as a
right-handed batter; he also was wary of Kennedy swiping second. So
Torre called on the left-handed rookie Randy Choate. Nelson said
something to Torre before he left the mound, an expression of
unhappiness. Nelson explained afterward that he feels he should be
used more, that this would give him a better chance of sorting
through his recent wildness.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was asked if he feels Torre has lost confidence in him.
``I don't know _ it doesn't bother me if he does or not,'' Nelson
said. ``I mean, who else is he going to go to? I think I've been
one of the most consistent guys down there, so if that's the case,
then we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Choate threw to first once, driving Kennedy back to the base,
but word is out that Choate has trouble holding runners. Kennedy
stole second uncontested, and when Stocker fought off a good pitch
and flipped a blooper over Sojo's head, Kennedy scored.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden allowed a run in the eighth, and Anaheim led, 5-3,
negating the solo homer hit by Hill in the bottom of the inning,
Hill's 10th in only 51 at-bats for the Yankees. The Yankees had a
couple of runners on base with two out in the bottom of the ninth,
but Paul O'Neill lined to left to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have benefited from the most significant midseason
makeover in the history of baseball, and almost every player they
have added has made major contributions. But check Monday's
standing: The patchwork Boston Red Sox are only a few good days
away from overtaking the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Torre may or may not be concerned about the Red Sox, about
Nelson, about his middle relief. He sees the big picture and says
good things. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
