<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-BISHER0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger pulls it off
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The world of Tiger Woods didn't come tumbling
down Sunday, but the foundation got a good shaking.
</P>
<P>
   It came from a most unlikely source, a journeyman player who had
to leave for another continent to find his game. Bob May himself
was a teen-age prodigy, like Woods, youngest player to qualify for
a PGA Tour event _ the Los Angeles Open when he was 16.
</P>
<P>
   All is known of Tiger, who was last seen with a smile a yard
wide, cuddling the Wanamaker Trophy, a bauble that usually gets
lost in the foderol of the PGA Championship, for which it stands.
But who is this Bob May, who came within a stroke of the upset of
the year, who rattled Woods' cage, and who put pressure on him
where the Big Guns had failed, Els, Love, Duval, Montgomerie,
Mickelson and that high-powered lot?
</P>
<P>
   Peculiar as it May seem, Bob May grew up on a similar hotshot
level as Woods in Southern California. He was the hottest amateur
in that part of the land, but his career never took off like
Woods'. He played on the NCAA championship team at Oklahoma State.
He played on the Walker Cup team in 1991_ with Phil Mickelson,
David Duval and Franklin Langham. But after he turned pro, he never
built on it.
</P>
<P>
   He held a PGA Tour card for a year, but lost it and took off for
the European Tour, and there played for four years. When his
earnings hit a peak over there and he won the British Masters last
year, he decided it was time to bring his game home. He made it
back to the tour, finishing 13th in qualifying school and has made
himself at home. He barely missed winning the Open at Memphis and
his earnings were just short of half-million coming in to Valhalla.
And he came here directly from England, where he'd returned to
defend his British Masters title. He finished fifth. He is still
listed in the PGA Tour Guide under ``Other Prominent Players.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, to come face to face with the child prodigy who wiped out
all his amateur records in California. ``I was 16, playing 18 holes
when Tiger was nine, playing nine holes. As he grew up I kept
reading that he was shooting for Bob May's records, and he shot for
them and he got them.
</P>
<P>
   So here they were. On the surface, it was a heavily titled
mismatch. ``Last night I played all the holes in my sleep. I really
slept well, but when I woke up I'd played 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when Tiger teed off and he hit his first drove over those
trees on the first hole, I knew I was in for a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth hole, lo and behold, May had a two-stroke lead.
Going into the 17th hole he still led by a stroke, but this was
about to change. May reached the green in two out of the thick
stuff, but had a cross-country putt to save par, and did, but Woods
rolled a birdie in on top of him and they were tied.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open, the British Open, they were cake-walks for Woods.
He was never pressed. It was in this 82nd PGA Championship that the
24-year-old felt real heat. May was carving out his third round of
66 in a row, ``and when you shoot three 66s, you ought to win a
major championship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But all this did was bring out the tiger in Woods. In the
three-hole playoff, a new PGA of America gimmick _ and one much
worthier than sudden death _ Woods birdied the 16th hole, but it
still wasn't over. It was a dogfight to the last two-foot putt he
sank for a half, and victory on the oddly-shaped 18th green. He
came out of woods, out of tall grass, out of sand. He was called on
to use every shot in his bag to win by a hairy stroke. May's last
desperate putt barely missed the cup by two inches.
</P>
<P>
   Now Woods has mounted the pedestal. He has his three majors this
year. He has won two PGA Championships in a row, first since the
long-gone Dinny Shute of the `30s. He has created his own
particular kind of universe, and there reigns supreme. He is open
to all challengers, and only Bob May, the least of the suspects,
has been gutty enough to bring the fight to him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
