<HEADLINE>
CAN THE TROJANS HACK IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Preseason college football polls are like bad
haircuts. Not only are they embarrassing, but you gotta wait at
least a month to see if they shape up.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they're just a tease.
</P>
<P>
   Which seems to be why, faced year after year with high falootin'
expectations, USC ends up looking like it's been attacked by a
Flo-be.
</P>
<P>
   It's no different in 2000. The Sporting News' pigskin preview
edition, for example, has the Trojans rumblin' through a 12-0
season and stumblin' to a No. 4 ranking, heading to the Rose Bowl
and ...
</P>
<P>
   Awwwwright, where do they get off with !ital!that kinda
prediction? Can't they wait until after the Penn State game?
</P>
<P>
   --On the field, the Trojans do have the horses.
</P>
<P>
   But on the sidelines, a reason for realistic optimism this time
might be in who coach Paul Hackett has assigned to saddle 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   It started with canning high-profile QB coach Ken O'Brien and
shifting offensive coordinator/running backs coach Hue Jackson
over. Finally, Hackett and Jackson are on the same page with Carson
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   To finish that move, in came Kennedy Pola, a no-nonsense former
Trojans fullback, to toughen up the running game - keying on Sultan
McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Morton, with 25 years coaching experience, was shifted
from tight ends coach to the offensive line, the position he
handled at the University of Washington for seven seasons. The
tight end spot was filled by 26-year-old Brian Schottenheimer, son
of Marty.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's A.J. Christoff, hired last February to work with
the linebackers, bringing in 27 years experience from places like
Colorado, Notre Dame, Alabama, Georgia Tech, Stanford, Oregon and -
egads, even five years with UCLA's secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, another 25-year coaching vet, Dan Farrigno, is on for
special teams and wide receivers. He's already got kicker David
Newbury comfortable going back to his old style.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for those who've seen the staff work with the players the
past few weeks in Irvine, it's been pretty impressive. Enough to
make some more lofty predictions?
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way, if you're worried about another terrible
Trojans trim to start the season, just think of it as a favorable
bowl cut. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Forget Tiger Woods' made-for-TV event a week from today
against Sergio Garcia. Just replay the last five holes from
Sunday's PGA Championship. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Actor Joe Pesci and radio personality Rick Dees, who once were
financial backers for Tiger chaser Bob May, will be releasing their
stock tips this morning. ...
</P>
<P>
   --By Wednesday, we'll know how serious Tom Lasorda is about
adding Orel Hershiser to the U.S. Olympic team. That's the day when
the team is supposed to be officially announced. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The IMAX flick ``Michael Jordan to the Max'' has already
generated more than $10 million in box office revenue since its
release in May.
</P>
<P>
   With today's ticket prices, that translates to about 400 paying
customers. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Did ya notice a horse named Sickly finished last in Saturday's
Arlington Million? ...
</P>
<P>
   --And there's an Arizona State psychology professor who
professes that, while many of us assume die-hard sports fans are
lonely, pathetic sorts in search of some self-esteem, just the
opposite is the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes possible to attain some sort of respect and regard
not by one's own achievements but by one's connection to
individuals of attainment,'' said Robert Cialdini in a recent New
York Times story.
</P>
<P>
   So, in other words, a true sports fan will always see the
bandwagon as half full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
