u s BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE0821-COX     08-20 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the winner is - Woods!
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ After proving at both the U.S. Open and
British Open that he could blow away his opponents in laughable
fashion, Tiger Woods won one the hard way Sunday at Valhalla Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Ernie Els's, the Davis Love's and the Phil Mickelson's of
the golf world couldn't get Woods to notice them all summer, but
little known Bob May, the world's 48th-ranked player, pushed the
world's No. 1 as far as possible.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond that, if May could have found a fairway or two late
in the day, indeed it might it have been him kissing the Wanamaker
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Woods. Again. But this time with drama totally
missing at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   After 72 holes of sweating, pressure-packed regulation play and
three playoff holes, the 24-year-old Woods secured a second
straight PGA Championship title Sunday, capturing three majors in a
season for the first time since Ben Hogan in 1953. He also became
the first player to win back-to-back PGA title since Denny Shute in
1936-37.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will be trying for a three-peat next August at the Atlanta
Athletic Club in the 2001 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   After both Woods and May tied at 18-under 270 for 72 holes,
establishing a new PGA Championship scoring record, Woods
eventually wrestled away a win, 13-12, for the three playoff holes,
just implemented into the tournament's format this week. Woods'
25-foot birdie putt at the 16th hole to start the playoff emerged
as the difference. Just before, May had miraculously placed a
50-yard shot from the rough to six inches to clinch a par.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who now holds the scoring record in all four majors,
clinched the championship at the 18th green, blasting to a foot
from the right greenside bunker after May's 35-footer up the ridge
on the treacherous, tired green just missed by inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one memorable battle today,'' Woods said. ``I think
it's got to go down as one of the best duels in a major
championship. I enjoyed it and I'm sure Bob did, too. It was a very
special day. . . Both of us shot 31 on the back nine. I played the
last 12 holes in 12-under. Not too bad. . . It was
birdie-for-birdie, shot for shot _ going right at each other.
That's as much fun as it gets right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark's Thomas Bjorn finished third with a 68 at 13-under 275.
Stuart Appleby (69) and Greg Chalmers of Australia (69) tied for
fourth at 276, along with Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal (69).
</P>
<P>
   Woods earned $900,000 for the win _ his fifth pro major
championship and fourth of the last five _ and pushed his 2000
earnings to $6,692,821, raising the possibility of a $10 million
season with three first prizes in the $1 million range remaining,
including Nov. 2-5 in the Tour Championship at Atlanta's East Lake
Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   The win merely added to a growing domination that is unmatched
in the sport. It was Woods' 15th win in his last 28 official
events. For his career, he's 20-2 when he's held at least a share
of the 54-hole lead.
</P>
<P>
   May, whose $540,000 paycheck was the largest of his career, shot
a 66 to catch Woods at the end of regulation, knocking in a
12-footer at the 18th that first looked short and right, then
curved back left and into the cup. Woods answered with a 5-footer,
bringing a a vigorous fist-pump and setting the tone for the
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's No. 1 in the world,'' said May. ``I never
counted him out all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his horrible driving _ five fairways missed in the last three
holes of regulation and in the playoff _ May said, ``I never
completed my backswing. I felt like I was chopping wood there for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   May had his chance to prevent the playoff at all. He yanked a
5-footer at the 15th hole for birdie, missing an opportunity to
lead by two shots with three holes to play. Moments before, Woods
rammed in a 10-footer for par after missing the green.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
