u s BC-GLF-PGA-NYT &LR;      08-20 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS OUTDUELS MAY IN A PGA PLAYOFF AND TIES HOGAN IN RECORD BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Facing a courageous challenger who refused to
give in, the world's best golfer showed the world just how good he
is.
</P>
<P>
   Winning his third consecutive major championship, and winning
his second consecutive PGA Championship, Tiger Woods prevailed
Sunday by one stroke in a three-hole playoff over Bob May. For
drama, it ranked among history's most exciting major championships,
with one memorable shot after another, as Woods and May engaged in
a brilliant shotmaking duel.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Woods became only the second player to win
three majors in one year, joining Ben Hogan, who won the Masters,
the U.S. Open and the British Open in 1953. Woods also became the
first back-to-back winner at the PGA Championship since Denny Shute
won the PGA in both 1936 and '37.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods' historic year has been even more dominant than
Hogan's year in '53. Woods won this year's U.S. Open by a
record-setting 15 strokes, he won the British Open by eight
strokes, and Sunday, Woods and May set the PGA Championship scoring
record (18-under-par 270), breaking the previous mark of 17 under
set by Steve Elkington and Colin Montgomerie in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Woods holds the scoring record at all four major
championships _ the Masters (18 under), the U.S. Open (15 under),
the British Open (19 under) and the PGA Championship (18 under).
And at age 24, he has won five career majors faster than anyone,
and he is the first player in history to win four of the previous
five majors, dating back to last year's PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone expected what happened to day _ Woods being pushed
to the brink of defeat by a player who had never won a PGA Tour
event, let alone a major championship. But when May forced Woods to
play his best, Woods was brilliant. Woods forced the playoff by
making a pressure-packed five-foot birdie putt at No. 18. He then
closed the playoff by making a wonderful up and down from the
green-side bunker at No. 18 to protect his one-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
   An extraordinary effort by May was not enough to defeat the
game's most extraordinary player. Woods could not remember being
tested more severely, which made the victory even more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably one of the greatest duels I've ever had in
my life,'' said Woods. ``To see two guys playing at a level that
you're probably only going to attain when you're concentrating that
much was really special. Birdie for birdie, shot for shot, we were
going at each other. That's as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods (66-67-70-67) and May (72-66-66-66) both finished at 270,
five strokes ahead of Thomas Bjorn, who finished third. But on the
back nine, the other contenders dropped away, unable to keep up
with the torrid pace set by Woods and May at Valhalla Golf Club, a
course that has been maligned for lacking history, but a course
that will now be linked to one of golf's most electrifying
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Both players shot sizzling five-under 31 on the back nine, the
kind of display rarely seen anywhere, particularly at a major. And
there were many key moments, although several stood out. May almost
won at No. 18 in regulation, when he made a sensational 15-foot
birdie putt from the back fringe to take a momentary one-stroke
lead, forcing Woods to make a five-foot birdie putt to keep the
tournament alive.
</P>
<P>
   Woods never flinched, making the putt, pumping his fist, shaking
May's hand and marching onward to the three-hole playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things were going, I had to figure he was going to
make his putt,'' said Woods of May's putt. ``So I had to step up
there and bury mine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first hole of the playoff, Woods took a one-stroke lead
for good at the par 4, No. 16, making a 15-foot putt for birdie,
after May hit a great chip to save par. Then on the final hole, the
par-5 No. 18, after Woods and May both pulled their drives left and
failed to reach the green in two shots, Woods hit a tremendous
bunker shot to within a foot, leaving May with a tough 30-foot putt
uphill for birdie that he needed to keep the match going. May's
putt for birdie just missed, and Woods tapped in for victory,
taking the first-place check of $900,000, and setting a
single-season earning record of over $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, May was proud of his effort, knowing he did
everything in his power to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I proved to a lot of people that I could play under
the heat,'' said May, who heard plenty of support from the noisy
gallery following the final group. ``I think people started rooting
for me about the second hole, when I made birdie, and Tiger made
bogey. I think they figured, `Okay, this is going to be a little
bit interesting.' They probably thought Tiger was going to do what
he usually does, run away,''
</P>
<P>
   But May would not go away. Starting the day one stroke behind
Woods, May actually built a two-stroke lead through six holes, but
Woods birdied No. 7 and No. 8 to tie. However, a key turning point
came at No. 15 in regualtion, when Woods made a 15-foot putt to
save par, then May missed a four-foot putt that would have given
him a birdie. If Woods had missed his putt, and May had sunk his,
May would have held a three-stroke lead with three holes to play.
Instead, Woods remained just one stroke back, and he pulled even at
No. 17, hitting a huge drive, then hitting a beautiful sand wedge
shot from 96 yards to within two feet for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things that happened today, the putt I made at No.
15 may have been the biggest,'' said Woods. ``If I made that putt,
I figured his putt would get a little longer. But if I had missed,
and he makes, he's up three with three to go, and I'm not looking
too good.''
</P>
<P>
   But after winning another major, Woods' career accomplishments
looked spectacular. He has a chance to become the first player to
win four consecutive professional majors at next year's Masters,
but that could wait Sunday night. Woods wanted to savor a victory
that he will not forget because of how he won and because of how
severely he was pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wanted to see drama return to the major championships
got their wish. Instead of a runaway, this was a thriller. However,
the phenomenal player who keeps adding to his legacy simply refused
to lose. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
