u a BC-OBIT-EDELSTEIN-NYT     08-20 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EDELSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID EDELSTEIN, JUDGE IN IBM AND TEAMSTERS CASES, DIES AT 90 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ U.S. District Judge David N. Edelstein, who in his 48
years on the bench presided over two of the Justice Department's
most historic undertakings _ the antitrust action against IBM and
the ongoing effort to rid the Teamsters union of corruption _ died
on Saturday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed by President Truman on Nov. 1, 1951, Edelstein served
as chief judge of the Southern District of New York from 1971 to
1980 and for years was the longest-sitting active judge in the
country. He became eligible for senior status, a sort of
semiretirement, in 1975 but did not take it until 1994, and he
continued to hear cases until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Still among his caseload was U.S. v. the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, the landmark lawsuit first brought by the
Justice Department in 1988, and he continued to play an active role
in the efforts to monitor the union. In June, he rejected the rules
proposed by the union and the Justice Department for next year's
Teamsters elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The submissions are a farrago of ill advice and misguided,
inept, controversial and confused argots,'' he wrote in language
that reflected his reputation for being one of the most thoughtful
and irascible personalities on the bench. ``Their program has the
potential of bringing grief, strife, controversy and corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was one of countless decisions by Edelstein aimed at
keeping the powerful truckers' union free of criminal influence. It
was Edelstein who approved a review board decision in 1998 to expel
Ron Carey, the union's former president. And it was a decision by
Edelstein in March 1999 that cleared the way for James P. Hoffa to
take the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District, said
Sunday: ``Judge Edelstein was a dedicated jurist who was dogged in
his pursuit of justice. His work, in particular on the Teamsters
litigation, will stand as an impressive legacy to his judicial
courage and intellect.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein's reputation for doggedness stemmed from his long role
in the government's antitrust action against International Business
Machines, which was first brought in 1952 when the company's main
business was punch-card technology. In 1956, he signed a consent
order under which IBM agreed to modify some of its business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Justice Department's current action against Microsoft,
the IBM case had been considered the most important antitrust
action in modern judicial history. But in the end Edelstein was
apparently too dogged, and in 1995 a federal appeals court granted
IBM's request and ordered him off the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it manifestly clear that a reasonable observer would
question the judge's impartiality on the pending issue,'' Chief
Judge Jon O. Newman of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals wrote
in a rare rebuke of a fellow judge. The appellate decision ordered
the case re-assigned.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Edelstein had been overseeing the IBM case for
about 43 years. Before his removal, he had opened an inquiry into
why the Justice Department wanted to drop its case against IBM and
had refused to approve several orders jointly proposed by the
company and the Justice Department to throw out billions of pages
of documents that had accumulated over the years.
</P>
<P>
   David Norton Edelstein was born on Feb. 16, 1910, into a
middle-class family in New York City. He attended public schools
and then Fordham University, earning a bachelor's, a master's and a
law degree.
</P>
<P>
   He paid his way through college and law school by working as a
page boy at the New York Stock Exchange from 1929 to 1932 and was a
firsthand witness to the devastating effects of the great crash.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in private law practice in New York and in the claims
division of the Justice Department before becoming an assistant
U.S. attorney in 1945. He became a special assistant to the U.S.
Attorney General in the lands division in 1947 and was assistant
U.S. attorney general in the customs division from 1948 until 1951
when he was appointed to the bench after Truman's first choice
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   His nomination was opposed by the American Bar Association, the
Association of the Bar of the City of New York and the New York
State Bar Association, which said that he lacked trial experience.
Nevertheless, he was confirmed by the Senate in April 1952 and went
on to one of the longest careers on the bench in what is arguably
the highest profile District Court in the country.
</P>
<P>
   He became chief judge in 1971 on the basis of seniority, and
remained in the post until 1980 when, at the age of 70, tradition
dictated that he step aside. But he remained an active judge,
overseeing the IBM saga and numerous other cases, including the
1984 trial of state Sen. Joseph R. Pisani of New Rochelle on
charges of tax evasion and embezzling campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   The jury convicted Pisani on 18 of 39 counts and acquitted him
of 11 counts, but it was unable to reach a verdict on 10 counts
that made up a large chunk of the government's case, including
allegations that Pisani used $20,000 in state funds to buy a summer
house. Edelstein declared a mistrial on those 10 counts. Pisani's
convictions were reversed on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Edelstein showed particular disdain for
perpetrators of crimes of greed. In 1983, he ordered six wholesale
bakers that had been charged with price-fixing in supplying
doughnuts and pastries to coffee shops and restaurants to provide
the needy with up to $1,200 worth of free baked goods each week for
two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, at the sentencing of David P. Bloom, a financial
adviser once called a Wall Street ``whiz kid'' who had been
convicted of defrauding investors of nearly $15 million, Edelstein
called the 24-year-old defendant a predator and imposed an
eight-year prison term. ``I find that Bloom is remorseless,
completely lacking in conscience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein, who lived in Manhattan, is survived by his wife of 60
years, the former Florence Koch, and two sons, Jonathan and
Jeffrey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
