<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-NOTEBOOK-     08-20 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH MAY TEST ELBOW IN MINORS; CELEBRATING NO. 16; WILLIAMS
RESTS; CONE FEELING BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' leadoff batter, may be
within a week of returning to the team. He threw from 90 feet
Sunday, taking ground balls and making throws from second base to
first, and took batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch is recovering from tendinitis in his right elbow, and
if he does not have any setbacks in the next few days, he could
begin a minor league rehabilitation toward the end of the week.
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said there was a
``real possibility'' that Knoblauch could rejoin the Yankees before
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has not played since Aug. 2, and the Yankees have
missed his presence at the top of their lineup, his ability to
elevate pitch counts and create offense. Knoblauch's elbow trouble
did not prevent him from hitting before he was placed on the
disabled list for the first time in his career; it did cause deep
pain when he threw.
</P>
<P>
   By waiting until Sept. 1 to activate Knoblauch, the Yankees
could avoid making a roster decision to make room for him, because
all major league rosters expand on that date. But the Yankees have
failed to increase their lead over the Boston Red Sox recently, and
each of their remaining 42 games is taking on increased importance;
they will need Knoblauch as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The most vulnerable player on the 25-man roster would appear to
be outfielder Luis Polonia, who has not performed well since
joining the Yankees and does not have a clear-cut role now that the
roster is stocked with David Justice, Glenallen Hill and Jose
Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, the right-hander who is on the disabled list
because of weakness in the back of his right shoulder, will begin a
throwing program Monday, as he works his way back to the active
roster. Mendoza's status is crucial to the makeup of the Yankees'
bullpen, because he has proven to be so useful in the postseason in
recent years. The Yankees hope Mendoza will be back in early to
mid-September, to give him enough appearances to establish his
command before October.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating No. 16 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whitey Ford joked that he had never been so nervous since he
faced Ted Williams for the first time. The occasion was Whitey Ford
Day at Yankee Stadium and the numeral 16 was painted near the
first- and third-base foul lines _ Ford's number, the only Yankees
number retired in honor of a pitcher. Ford, a left-hander who won
236 regular-season games and 10 more in the World Series, was
inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen former teammates were on hand, including Yogi
Berra, Phil Rizzuto and Luis Arroyo. Ford mentioned his late son
Tom in thanking his family, his voice clutched by emotion. ``I've
had some wonderful days here,'' he said. ``But this tops them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a Yankee for 53 years,'' Ford continued, ``and I'll
be a Yankee forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 71, finished radiation treatments he had been undergoing
after the removal of a cancerous brain tumor last November. Ford,
who went through a similar procedure five years ago, has said he is
feeling a lot better. Sunday, he smiled on the field and laughed
and appeared to wipe away a few tears. ``I'm so overwhelmed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Rests
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center fielder, was out of the
lineup for the second consecutive game because of a twinge in his
right side. He initially felt the pain while taking batting
practice before Saturday's game. ``I feel better today,'' Williams
said before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has had a rib-cage injury before and said that his pain
in this instance is nowhere close to what it was the last time he
was hurt. ``I'm not really worried about it,'' he said. ``But I'd
rather be out there playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fact that the Yankees need him as they prepare for
the final 42 games of the season, Williams has reasons of his own
to return as soon as possible. He is considered one of the American
League's top candidates for the most valuable player award, and
with 107 runs batted in he is 23 short of the single-season record
for switch-hitters, established by Mickey Mantle in 1956 and later
tied by Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher, also was out of the starting
lineup and did not participate in batting practice, taking a full
day off from his regular pregame work to rest. During his last
at-bat Saturday, Posada tore a fingernail while batting, stepping
out of the batter's box to flex and test his hand at one point.
Posada pinch-hit in the ninth inning Sunday, grounding out, and he
expects to be back in the lineup Monday afternoon when the Yankees
play the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Cone Feeling Better
</P>
<P>
   David Cone struck out the first two batters in the first inning
Sunday, Orlando Palmeiro and Scott Speizio, and when the count
reached full on the first baseman Mo Vaughn, the Yankee Stadium
crowd began clapping and cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the mound, Cone looked around for an instant, as if
to feed off their emotion, and he finished off Vaughn with a
split-fingered fastball, the third of his six strikeouts on the
afternoon. Cone's confidence, hurt by his long winless streak,
seems to be returning.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Cone made vague references to the end of
his career during his slump, but he is beyond that now. His record
is 3-10. But he said that anyone who really believed he had pitched
like a 3-10 pitcher this season had not been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been better than 3-10,'' he said, a reference to the
games when he has pitched well enough to win but has not done so.
``I just feel good about what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Over his last four starts, Cone has compiled a 2.74 earned run
average, allowing seven earned runs in 23 innings in winning both
of his decisions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
