<HEADLINE>
FOR VERIZON WORKERS AND THEIR CUSTOMERS, RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (With VERIZON-RDP)  
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leo Hernandez had not been planning to wake up at
5:30 Monday morning to go to work. Old-timers at the phone company
had told him that if a strike lasted more than two weeks, it would
be a long one. Hernandez had been preparing to wait it out.
</P>
<P>
   But an agreement reached Sunday, as the walkout entered its
third week, meant the end of picket lines and paycheck worries for
about two-thirds of the more than 86,000 Verizon Communications
workers on strike in 12 states and Washington. And it meant hope
for thousands of customers stranded without service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy,'' said Hernandez, a switchman at the Manhattan
headquarters who has worked for the company for five years. Though
he did not know the details of the agreement between Verizon and
two unions, the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, he said he was
certain any settlement would address his main concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the company's ability to organize workers in the
wireless sectors and management's ability to transfer workers at
will, which are both addressed in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that at least the people from my local that I
know personally did a good job representing us,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, at the L'Enfant Plaza Hotel, leaders of the
unions said they had accomplished much of what they had sought to
achieve when they went on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached a fair agreement and everybody's happy,'' Angel
Feliciano, a leader of Local 1101 of the CWA, said in the lobby of
the hotel, where the talks took place.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the union had won in the contracts, James P. O'Hare,
president of Local 1118 in Albany, N.Y., replied: ``Stock options
are nice, but the major goals are transferring our work,
protections against contracts, no layoffs, no downgrades. You can't
beat that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Verizon workers said they were prepared to face the
backlog of repairs and other jobs that had piled up in their
absence. ``We're not afraid of hard work,'' said Annie B. Bowie, a
30-year veteran, as she volunteered at CWA Local 1101 in Manhattan
Sunday night, preparing checks for union members who had done
picket-line duty. ``For a good day's wage, we will give a good
day's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Though forced overtime was one of the complaints the unions
brought to the bargaining table, a local union president in Boston
said overtime restrictions would be rolled back this week to allow
technicians to chip away at the accumulated work requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of them, especially the younger ones with children,
it's good money for them,'' said the official, Edward T.
Fitzpatrick of IBEW Local 2222.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon customers said they were relieved the strike was over,
but somewhat skeptical that an end to their wait for service would
soon follow. Rachel Karr, the office manager for Digital Club
Network in Manhattan, said that because of a delay in installing
digital phone lines, she had been able to provide only eight phone
lines for more than 60 employees.
</P>
<P>
   When told that the strike had ended, she said, ``They were late
before they went on strike, so I'm not happy until everything's
done. Maybe they'll answer the phones now, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Bullinga, an architect, said she had been without phone,
fax or e-mail service since she moved into a new office in SoHo
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually a very lonely, disconnected feeling, when you
can't do business or get in touch with anyone,'' Bullinga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
