<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN THE END, TIGER WON THE HOGAN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE , Ky. _ As a youngster, Tiger Woods taped a list of
Jack Nicklaus' accomplishments on the wall of his room. And after
having played with Nicklaus in the first two rounds of the 82nd PGA
Championship, he was asked if he could play with two other golfers
of history in a mythical foursome, who would they be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan and Jones,'' he said quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones died before Tiger Woods was born but when Woods,
after winning the 1997 Masters as a PGA Tour rookie, arrived to
play in the Colonial Invitation in Fort Worth he hoped to meet Ben
Hogan, who was ill at home there. Valerie Hogan didn't want Tiger
to see her husband in his condition, but she arranged for him to
take Tiger's phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they talked about,'' she would say before
her death in 1998, ``but I heard Ben say, `I feel the same way
about you, Tiger.' And when Ben died two months later, I received
the nicest note from Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Tiger Woods has finally met Ben Hogan in golf's history
books. With his PGA victory in a theatrical three-hole playoff with
Bob May Sunday, the reigning U.S. Open and British Open champion is
the first golfer to win three major titles in one season since
Hogan won the Masters and the two Opens in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   For all his dazzling shots Sunday, Woods really won the Hogan
way, the hard-work way.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever other golfers asked Hogan for his ``secret,'' the
little Texan would say, ``The secret is in the dirt,'' meaning the
dirt below the grass of the practice range and the practice green.
Nobody in his era worked any harder to hone his talent than Hogan
did. And for all of Woods' gifts, nobody works any harder now than
he does.
</P>
<P>
   In the dirt is where Woods won this PGA _ in the dirt of the
Valhalla practice range and practice green long after sunset
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave there until 8:56,'' Woods said, alluding to
tuning his game with his swing guru, Butch Harmon. ``I worked on my
swing and my putting. I got so I felt more steady over the ball.
And before the round, I warmed up well. I got off to a slow start,
but I figured it was only a matter of time before it all came
together.''
</P>
<P>
   After two bogeys in the first six holes, Woods suddenly found
the swing and the putting touch that he had worked on Saturday
night. With birdie putts on the 17th and 18th holes for a 31 on the
back nine and a 5-under-par 67, he forced the three-hole playoff
that he won by one stroke by one-putting for a birdie and two pars.
</P>
<P>
   With his fifth major at age 24, Woods has also won four out of
the last five majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is doing right now,'' Nicklaus said after watching
Woods shoot 66-67 in the first two rounds, ``I think he is a better
player than I ever was.''
</P>
<P>
   That's powerful praise from the golfer who is generally
considered to be the best in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is doing it with regularity and he is doing it with so
much left in him, so much more power to burn.'' Nicklaus said. ``I
don't think I have ever seen anybody do what he is doing that much
within himself. He doesn't have to extend himself at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, did need to extend himself against May, who
until the weekend here had been a virtual unknown on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing,'' Nicklaus said, ``I always had Arnold
Palmer, Gary Player, Lee Trevino, Tom Watson, guys that won quite a
few majors. They were not afraid to win a tournament. Tiger not
only has the ability to be so much better than the other guys, but
the other guys are not sure they can win. He's got everything
sitting in front of him, plus that factor that is a big factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus mentioned another factor, that Woods is using clubs and
balls that are much more high-tech than when the Golden Bear was at
his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never hit my irons anywhere near as hard as Tiger hits his
irons, nor as far,'' Nicklaus said. ``I never tried to. I hit my
irons basically the same distance now as I did in my prime; maybe
not the 1-iron and the 2-iron, but 25 years ago I hit a 5-iron 175
yards and I hit a 5-iron 175 yards now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Tiger is hitting 175 yards, it's a 7-iron or 8-iron,
most likely an 8-iron. That is just a different way of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you can do that with the golf ball we used to
play with because it had so much spin on it. Today you can tailor a
golf ball to your game a little bit more than you could then. You
can get a low spin-rate ball, whatever you want. We couldn't do
that. We played with what was available.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Nicklaus enjoyed watching Woods play golf, he also
enjoyed Woods the young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pleasant young man to play with; he couldn't have been
nicer,'' Nicklaus said. ``He has a good sense of humor. He enjoys
joking around a little bit. If I'm passing the baton, I couldn't
pass it to a nicer young man who is obviously the cream of the crop
right now by a mile.''
</P>
<P>
   And a young man with the Hogan work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the tape,'' Tiger Woods said, alluding to
Sunday's duel, ``I already know what I need to work on, but maybe
I'll see something else to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan would appreciate that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
