   (NYT12) COOS BAY, Ore. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ORE-LOGGING-2 -- For
places like Coos Bay, Ore., once the largest wood-products shipping
port in the world, there are some painful twists in the form of
technological advancement. These computer oriented jobs are not for
everybody. Some who have worked around trees or at the port all
their lives said they could not imagine being cooped up all day,
staring at a computer screen. A Coos Bay log-yard worker who tags
and sorts giant logs all day. (Shane Young/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) COOS BAY, Ore. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ORE-LOGGING-1 -- As
high-tech companies face an acute shortage of workers in many urban
areas, they have begun to branch out to areas of the country that
had been passed over by the boom, bringing jobs and training and
making inroads on the ``digital divide'' between America's urban
and rural regions. George Sjostrom, 59, is one Coos Bay, Ore.,
log-yard worker who has no plans to make the transition to a
computer job. ``I'm out of my world. I wouldn't have any idea what
to do with a computer,'' says Sjostrom, who tags and sorts giant
logs all day. (Shane Young/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MOLINE, Ill. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- GORE-3 -- Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore and his vice-presidential running
mate, Joseph Lieberman, rendezvoused in the Midwest on Sunday,
bringing their populist message and post-convention momentum to
America's heartland. Lending his post-convention stump speech a
decidedly populist appeal, the Democratic presidential nominee
continued: ``Here's why I'm running. I want to make it better for
your kids and for you. I'm standing up here without any ulterior
motive. I'm standing up here because I want to fight for you and
your family and your future.'' (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MOLINE, Ill. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- Accompanied by
the throbbing percussion of a youth drum corps, Democrats Al Gore
and Joseph Lieberman promised more than 5,000 Illinois residents
help paying their bills and battling their insurance companies,
Sunday. ``Our ability to do something about health care depends on
whether or not we're going to keep our economy in good shape,''
said Gore. Vice President Gore and his wife, Tipper, left, and his
running mate, Joseph I. Lieberman, and his wife, Hadassah, Sunday
at the campaign rally in Moline, Ill. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) COOS BAY, Ore. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ORE-LOGGING-3 -- For
many workers in remote Coos County, Ore., where the historical
economic pillars of logging and fishing have been severely battered
and where the unemployment rate was in the double digits as
recently as last year, an improbable savior has emerged, in the
form of technology. The company is CyberRep.com. Still, many
outdoors workers, like Zeldon Linn, front, often express
ambivalence about the nature of the work and the sweeping economic
forces that have taken them out of the woods or off the seas and
placed them in small workstations in a boxy warehouse. (Shane
Young/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CLINTON, Iowa. -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- GORE-1 -- The first
weekend after the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles
took on a festive tone, as Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore
celebrated wife Tipper's 52nd birthday in Clinton, Iowa, late
Saturday night. Tipper Gore shares her birthday with Gore's
political mentor, President Bill Clinton, who turned 54 this
weekend. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAMSAT, Turkey -- AUG. 20, 2000 -- TURKEY-MODERNIZE-2 --
Up and down the Euphrates and Tigris Rivers in southeastern Turkey,
villages inhabited since the beginning of civilization are being
flooded into watery oblivion by a vast dam system. For tens of
thousands of people, those who live in places of great
archaeological value and those in historically insignificant
hamlets like Samsat, a way of life is being erased. ``We are
missing very much the old Samsat,'' says Fevzi Kural, sitting in
his yard in the relocated village of Samsat, drying tobacco.
(Staton R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAMSAT, Turkey -- AUG. 20, 2000 -- TURKEY-MODERNIZE-1 --
The Turkish government is in the final years of its largest public
works project, an ambitious effort to quench an insatiable appetite
for electricity, irrigate arid land and bring jobs to this
impoverished region. But in recent months the imminent drowning of
sites with archaeological appeal has sparked an outcry across the
world that Turkey is cannibalizing its history. The village of
Hasenkyf will be under water after a dam is built, with only the
top of the minaret showing. (Staton R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- FOREIGN-POLICY-MEDIA -- No
longer will Foreign Policy, the 30-year-old publication of the
endowment, concentrate on articles about relations between
governments, on military policy, or on the domestic politics of an
important American ally. Instead, the magazine, remade from its
elegant slim size into a bigger, flashier format that resembles the
celebrity magazine Talk, will concentrate on ``global politics,
economics and ideas.'' Moises Naim, editor and publisher of Foreign
Policy, with redesigned covers in Washington. (Justin Lane/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ROCK-RADIO-MEDIA -- As the
latest releases from Korn, top, and Limp Bizkit, far right, are
played alongside older songs from bands like Pearl Jam, ``the lines
between radio stations that play alternative rock and those that
play traditional rock are blurred,'' says Steve Kingston, program
director at K-Rock in New York. ``The landscape changed,'' he says.
``You need to be more of a specialist.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The
New York Times)
</P>
