<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-CONTRACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (EXCLUSIVE; 10:00 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.)  
(With VERIZON-RDP) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENGTH OF CONTRACT: Three years.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIZATION: The unions will be able to organize more easily in
Verizon's wireless division, and union members will have the
opportunity to do more work in fast-growing areas like the
installation of high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   COMPENSATION: A 12 percent raise over the life of the contract:
4 percent in the first year, 3 percent in the second and 5 percent
in the third. In addition, full-time employees will receive 100
stock options and part-time workers will receive 50.
</P>
<P>
   JOB STABILITY: The number of Verizon employees who can have
their jobs transferred to a different region as a result of the
Bell Atlantic-GTE merger is limited to seven-tenths of 1 percent
each year.
</P>
<P>
   JOB STRESS: Customer service representatives and operators will
receive up to five 30-minute periods each week in which they can do
work other than taking calls.
</P>
<P>
   OVERTIME: Mandatory overtime is lowered for most customer
service representatives and operators.
</P>
</TEXT>
