<SLUG> BC-OLY-VOLLEYBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WANTS VOLLEYBALL RENAISSANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USA Volleyball dusted off its history books to
regain its status as the world's dominant men's team.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Beal coached the United States to its first Olympic medal,
a gold at the 1984 Los Angeles Games. He left in 1986 to coach an
Italian club team, but the foundation was built. With primarily the
same players, the U.S. won every major international event, capping
the run with a second gold at the 1988 Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But the '90s were not kind.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. managed a bronze in '92 at Barcelona then crashed to
ninth in Atlanta four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Beal returned to the national team in 1997 shortly after the
Atlanta debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the most important points of emphasis for me to
our team right now is that they don't need to be like the 1984 or
1988 teams. They need to be like the 2000 team,'' Beal said.
</P>
<P>
   By Atlanta, the international edge the U.S. had over the world
wasn't the only problem as Olympics veteran Mike Lambert explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Beal) has brought some order to our chaos,'' said Lambert,
one of five 2000 members who played on the 1996 team. ``We are a
bunch of good athletes, and we have some good skills. He has
brought a system where we can all play together. I think he has
brought this team together in the sense that instead of being six
individuals out there, we are all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Beal's 1984 team featured a hybrid of veterans and hungry young
players that was blended into a gold-medal team.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 version has the aforementioned core group that has
played in the Olympic spotlight. The youth movement is led by
Highland High of Palmdale graduate Ryan Millar and former
Pepperdine standout George Roumain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very diverse team,'' Beal said.
</P>
<P>
   And a dangerous one. The Americans went 10-2 in the prestigious
World League, which includes the world's top teams, before
faltering in the league's championship tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. is ranked sixth in the world and was drawn into a
difficult Olympics pool with world No. 1 Italy and No. 2 Russia.
But the U.S. should be a medal threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team is a very competitive team (and can compete)
with anybody in the world,'' said Beal, whose staff includes former
Pepperdine coach Marv Dunphy, the head coach of the 1988 Seoul
gold-medal team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are the best team in the world, but I think
we're moving up. I think we're improving at a faster rate or at as
fast a rate as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, Pepperdine product Jeff Nygaard and the other '96
veterans are hoping to redeem themselves after a disappointing
Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out there and play with a lot of fire, emotion and
intensity, then teams have to play to compete with us,'' Lambert
said. ``I think we set the standard now for where the match is
going to go when we play our best. Teams have to try and keep up
with us. We're still kind of a young team, and we haven't peaked
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney would be a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   While Italy, Russia and defending gold medalist Cuba are the
favorites, there figures to be plenty of pressure on the Americans
to return to a sport they dominated in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect they are going to be edgy and anxious; that's part of
sports and you have to manage that emotion,'' Beal said. ``The
great players and the teams that achieve at a high level manage
that environment successfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
