<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STL     08-20 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN WEIGHED TO OPEN SUNKEN SUBMARINE'S HATCH WITH CRANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct spelling to Vidayevo in 7th graf; inserts new graf
re British mini-sub in parentheses after 14th graf; changes WWII
mine to `old' mine in 3rd-to-last graf.)  
(ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Having found no signs of life more than a week after
the Russian submarine Kursk plunged to the bottom of the Barents
Sea, rescue teams were preparing a plan Sunday to use a ship's
crane to rip a hatch off the giant vessel and begin the grim task
of recovering bodies and a lengthy and dangerous mission to salvage
the submarine's twin nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   In their first full day of work, a team of Norwegian divers
working with the Russians found the rear escape hatch on the
490-foot vessel badly damaged, a Russian official said, and the
divers failed in repeated attempts to muscle it open by hand and
with powerful, special tools.
</P>
<P>
   The divers reported that hatchway valves had been opened from
the inside. It is likely that the body of one of the submarine's
118 crew members lies in the air lock chamber and that the chamber
is filled with water, said Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who
is heading the investigation into the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   His description of the grim discovery was broadcast by Russian
television from the deck of the cruiser Peter the Great and was
consistent with remarks Saturday by Vice Adm. Mikhail Mostak, chief
of staff of Russia's Northern Fleet, indicating that one or more
members of the Kursk crew may have tried to make a desperate escape
from the submarine, only to perish when seawater under great
pressure rushed in.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of frenetic work at a depth of more than 300 feet, the
Norwegian navy team sent back vivid pictures of the escape hatch
that has defied nearly a week of efforts to open it. The divers
pounded with hammers on the hull hoping that their soundings would
locate any remaining air pockets inside.
</P>
<P>
   As they worked in teams of three in six-hour shifts, the divers
sent up requests for special tools to turn the hatch valves, and
some tools were fabricated on board the Norwegian vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, two Norwegian divers flew by helicopter to the
Russian submarine base at Vidayevo, the Kursk's home port, to
practice opening and entering hatches on one of the Kursk's sister
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Planning was under way to rip the Kursk's hatch cover off by
force, according to Klebanov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joint commission made a decision to open the top hatch of
the rescue lock chamber,'' he said, referring to the escape chamber
that passes through the hull, with inner and outer hatches that
allow emergency exit from the submarine. ``Unfortunately, they
failed to open it for several hours though very powerful tools have
been used.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision was made to try to rip it off with the help of a
crane on the Norwegian rescue ship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials reported that air pockets might still exist in
the compartment below the inner hatch, but they expressed no
expectations that any survivors could be found, though a Norwegian
military spokesman in Oslo, Kjell Grandhagen, said, ``We are still
working on the theory that we are looking for possible survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's Rear Adm. Einar Skorgen, who is directing the Norwegian
rescue contingent, said the timing of the hatch removal was not
set. ``We have to clarify the consequences of opening it,'' he told
Norwegian television.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent cooperative spirit among Russian, British and
Norwegian rescue crews was somewhat undermined Sunday night when
the spokesman for the Norwegian armed forces, speaking in Oslo,
contradicted Klebanov's statements that the escape hatch was too
severely damaged to be opened manually, or with the British LR5
rescue submarine that arrived on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not drawn the conclusion that the hatch is so damaged
that it cannot be opened,'' the spokesman, John Epsen Lien, told
Reuters. ``We think it should be possible to open it with a British
or Russian rescue capsule.''
</P>
<P>
   (British officials said in London early Monday that Russia had
asked Britain to send its rescue mini-submarine down to the Kursk,
Reuters said.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Klebanov had said that video images of the hatch showed
a serious crack in the donut-shaped ring around it that is used to
create an airtight seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we think the British sub will not be able to
dock,'' Klebanov said, adding that he believed that the Norwegian
divers would agree to enter the Kursk after studying the entryway
on one of the Kursk's sister ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their commander is now asking them who will go and it is
already clear that someone will go,'' Klebanov said.
``Psychologically, it is very difficult but there is assuredness
that several people will agree and the operation will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials have yet to confirm that their divers will
enter the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   What lies ahead after the hatch is opened is a complex and
dangerous investigation of the Kursk's nine compartments. Dangerous
battery acids, unexploded weapons and highly radioactive fuel
elements in the Kursk's twin reactors could pose a serious danger
to the recovery operation.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have speculated about plans to lift the rear
section of the submarine with surface ships and drag the vessel to
shallower water for easier access by salvage divers. With winter
already approaching in the Arctic region, it seemed possible that
the salvage operation could carry over to next spring, but Russian
officials have as yet given no definite accounting of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   As the Norwegian divers worked Sunday, Russian President
Vladimir Putin met in Moscow with senior clergymen of the Russian
Orthodox Church and expressed the powerlessness he felt over the
loss of the 118-member crew.
</P>
<P>
   The attack submarine went down Aug. 12 during military
maneuvers. Two explosions apparently ripped through the hull of the
submarine as it was running at periscope depth, and sent it
crashing to the seabed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With sorrow in our hearts and, I do not exaggerate, tears in
our eyes, we are following all that is happening in the Barents
Sea,'' he said. ``The sailors are doing everything they can to save
their comrades, but, alas, sometimes events _ and not us _ dictate
the logic of how a situation develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``until the last minute we will do all that can
be done to save whomever can be saved. We will struggle for the
lives of each of our sailors, and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Putin remained at the Kremlin Sunday, despite calls for
him to travel to Severomorsk, the naval headquarters near the scene
of the disaster, the Russian president held a long conversation
with Igor Spassky, Russia's leading submarine designer.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's public remarks, delivered in an unusually somber and
deliberate tone as he stood in front of the golden brocade walls of
one of the churches inside the Kremlin walls, appeared in part to
be in response to a swell of criticism that the Russian military,
and Putin personally, were too slow to seek foreign assistance in
the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   An investigating commission, headed by Klebanov, announced on
Saturday that preliminary findings showed that the Kursk was
involved in a collision with an object near the surface weighing
8,000 tons or more. He said it was possible that the object was a
ship or an old mine.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Klebanov said, some unknown chain of events could have
triggered a massive internal explosion aboard the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Russian officials say most of the crew died in the
first two minutes after the explosion, including all officers on
the bridge. They say that the pressure of seawater rushing in
compressed the air in the hull and reduced the chances for survival
beyond a few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-GORE-0821-1STLD-COX     08-20 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0821-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: add new 6th-14th grafs, of Gore, Lieberman campaigning on
Sunday, picks up with graf beginning xxx '''Fun Al'' first appeared
Friday morning . . . '
 &HT;    'FUN AL' EMERGING AS DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL NOMINEE SURGES IN
POLLS
 &HT;    (950&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, Iowa _ If you think you know Al Gore, you should have
seen him just around midnight this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After an impassioned speech late Saturday night, the denim-clad
Gore suddenly grabbed his wife Tipper and boogied on stage as a
local rock band cranked up a hot blues number and confetti rained
down upon the dancing couple.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which had gathered hours earlier, roared its delight.
Some in the crowd marveled: Who is this guy?
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in accepting the Democratic Party's presidential
nomination last week, assured voters that he is his ``own man'' and
that in the coming weeks they would see ``who I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fun-loving Al Gore that has rocked the Mark Twain
campaign boat down the Mississippi River the last three days is
somewhat of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   He managed to be serious enough on Sunday, however,
rendezvousing with his vice-presidential running mate, Joseph
Lieberman, and again promising to take on special interests on
behalf of working families and outlining plans ranging from
providing seniors with a prescription drug benefit under Medicare
to giving patients a bill of rights on their own health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to know the facts?'' Gore asked a crowd in
Muscatine, Iowa, to which they shouted, ``Yes!'' ``Am I giving you
too many specifics?'' he said. ``No!'' they roared back.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said a key goal of the new Democratic administration
would be to reach out to the 44 million Americans without health
insurance, many of them children.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman noted that under Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee, Texas had among the highest rates of
uninsured women and children in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush says don't mess with Texas, but when it comes to
health care, it is a mess in Texas,'' said Lieberman, who joined
back up with Gore after his Sabbath observance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fired-up demeanor on the weekend was shared by the
crowds, which have swelled in recent days. Many of those in
attendance have been recent converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are getting on board,'' said Terry
Willits, a 42-year-old Iowa attorney who was at the rally for Gore
in Clinton near midnight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched his convention speech with friends, and I remember
someone saying, 'He looks like he took a personality pill,''' she
to the Reuters news agency. ``He was great, and he told us exactly
what he planned to do as president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, I was worried. I didn't think Al Gore had a
chance. Today, I think he is going to win,'' Willits said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun Al'' first appeared Friday morning as he and Lieberman
boarded the Mark Twain for the four-day, 400-mile trip down the
Mississippi River through five Midwestern swing states.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters asked him whether he was trying to send any kind of
signal to the voters with the lingering kiss he gave Tipper just
before his acceptance speech the night before in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to send Tipper a signal,'' he replied,
mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early Saturday afternoon, Gore burst unannounced into the
press section of the campaign riverboat to catch a group of
television producers and camera operators in a game of poker.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed mock horror and, tongue-in-cheek, demanded
``campaign journalism reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, during an evening birthday party for his wife on the open
top deck of the boat, Gore occasionally used a bullhorn to make
small talk with campers and other people in sparsely populated
areas along the banks of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice shirt,'' he called to one person in the river darkness, a
scene reminiscent of Bill Clinton's microphone chit-chat _ ``I like
your dog!'' _ with people who lived along the tracks his
slow-moving campaign train took through the Midwest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need your help,'' Gore shouted to another group in the
darkness of the river. Then, with the bullhorn off, he added,
almost in a whisper: ``The boat is sinking.''
</P>
<P>
   And even later Saturday, when his campaign boat pulled into the
dam and lock just north of this Iowa city, hundreds of well-wishers
looked a bit surprised when they heard the Rolling Stones's
sexually suggestive song ``Brown Sugar'' and its famous ``just
around midnight'' refrain blaring from the boat's sound system.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing prepared Gore's campaign entourage for the sight of
Al and Tipper boogie-ing on the stage in Clinton. No one, not even
longtime aides to the vice president, could recall him ever dancing
at a campaign event _ at the Clinton-Gore inaugurations, sure, but
not at a campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is finding his own voice,'' campaign spokesman Chris
Lehane deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with his presidential campaign stumbling, Gore got
unsolicited advice from Clinton: ``Have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And ever since embarking on his Mississippi trip, Gore appears
to be having the time of his political life.
</P>
<P>
   A big contributor has been the unprecedented bounce he has
received in the polls since the convention, such as the CNN-USA
Today Gallup poll released Sunday. That poll had Gore at 47
percent, Bush at 46 percent, Green Party candidate Ralph Nader at 3
percent and Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 697 likely voters taken Friday and Saturday had an
error margin of (+/-) 4 percentage points. That same poll right
before the convention showed Bush 16 points ahead of Gore, 55
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush communications director Karen Hughes, appearing on ``Fox
News Sunday,'' cautioned against putting ``too much stock in the
instant polls taken in the immediate aftermath of a convention.''
She noted that Walter Mondale surged ahead of Ronald Reagan in 1984
in some polls but eventually lost the race.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   History aside, Gore's newfound giddiness in the trail is
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   During his speeches, Gore works in the messages from homemade
signs he sees in the crowd into his remarks. Sometimes, he engages
members of the crowd in a brief conversation before going on to the
issue of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the speeches, he remains as long as his
schedule will allow to shake hands, reaching deep into the crowds
that have swelled with each day of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   He slaps hands with children and toddlers and tweaks the noses
of babies.
</P>
<P>
   He poses for pictures and signs autographs.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike previous campaigns, he hugs and hugs and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be fired up,'' said Julia Heinzelman, a
middle-aged high school teacher in Dubuque, Iowa, one of the
riverboat stops. ``So much politics happens on TV, and TV is
supposed to be a cool medium. But I'm tired of the coolness. It's
time to get hot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting warmed up,'' Gore remarked to one crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's closest friends have long insisted that the vice
president is fun-loving and funny, but the American public has
rarely gotten a glimpse of ``Fun Al.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Gore insists that the presidential contest with
Texas Gov. George W. Bush is not a personality contest, you can
expect to see more of ``Fun Al'' after his life on the Mississippi
is over.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's E-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
