<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TAKE ADVANTAGE OF DODGERS' GIVEAWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the ninth inning of a close game, there was
nobody sitting in the front row of seats beside the camera box near
the Mets dugout at Dodger Stadium. So when Mark Grudzielanek hit a
foul pop and Mets catcher Mike Piazza tumbled over the fence to
catch it, he landed on the concrete ground.
</P>
<P>
   A phalanx of Mets bolted from the dugout. Piazza was bruised,
but fine. He emerged with the ball in hand, and Manager Bobby
Valentine slapped him five. Moments later, Armando Benitez finished
off a 9-6 Mets victory. The Dodgers had handed them the game in the
eighth, and it is hard to blame their fans for bolting the crime
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won 21 of the last 27 games, and have not lost two
games in a row in a month; as Valentine noted, they made their own
breaks in the decisive inning. With the score tied, 6-6, Mike
Bordick and Darryl Hamilton singled off Terry Adams to open the
eighth. Lenny Harris bounced a ball back to Adams, and, as Harris
said, ``Everything collapsed right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick was running from third on contact, and Adams had him
nailed. The pitcher threw to third baseman Adrian Beltre, but
Beltre's throw floated high over catcher Todd Hundley's head,
skipping to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Two runs scored there, and another came in after Grudzielanek
let a grounder scoot through his legs. The Mets gave a three-run
lead to John Franco and Benitez, and as usual, the game was
essentially over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is foolish enough to believe people are invincible or
can't be gotten to, but there's no doubts when that situation
arises,'' said Mets first baseman Todd Zeile. ``I think everyone's
as confident as could be in those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco worked a perfect eighth and Benitez a perfect ninth for
his 33rd save. Turk Wendell (6-4) pitched two innings for the
victory, and Dennis Cook got an important out to end the fifth
after the Dodgers had taken a lead off Bobby J. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidence every time,'' said Benitez, who, like
Franco, has not allowed an earned run since June 21. ``I can trust
all those guys in the bullpen, and they can trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can not trust themselves. They are one game over
.500 since trading Piazza to Florida in May 1998, and just two
games over .500 despite a $98 million payroll this year. ``We can't
make the plays when we need them,'' said Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson. ``You can't be a championship club that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are looking more and more like a champion, despite
losing a game on their wild card lead, which is three and a half
games over Arizona. On a day when Piazza - who also collided with
the concrete back wall to make a catch in the second _ went 0 for
5, teammates like Harris picked him up.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was 2 for 4 with a home run that briefly gave the Mets a
lead in the sixth inning. He romped around the bases after his home
run, tearing through a lineup of high fives as he came back to the
Mets dugout. He is 35 years old and his energy is boundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get late in the season, you need someone to kind of
get guys going, get people pumped up,'' said Hamilton. ``It was
flowing with him today. He was excited.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a measure of this game's wildness that so much action
happened in the ninth spot of the Mets' order, which was first
occupied by Jones, who is 0 for 31 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones came up in the second inning with a runner on second and
one out. He struck out, but Hundley missed the pitch and Jones
reached first on a passed ball. A single by Lenny Harris knocked in
a run, and when Hundley threw wildly to center on a stolen base
attempt, Jones scored to put the Mets ahead, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley made amends in the bottom of the inning with the first
of two home runs, and a run-scoring double by Shawn Green cut the
Mets lead to 4-3 in the third. They seemed poised to break things
open in the fourth, when Jones came up as the leadoff batter and
walked.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort looked distraught, removing his cap and wiping his
brow. He walked Harris on four pitches, and Derek Bell sacrificed
the runners. But Dreifort got tough, striking out Edgardo Alfonzo _
who earlier slugged an opposite-field, two-run homer _ and getting
Piazza to fly to the center field warning track.
</P>
<P>
   That was the second of three times Piazza flied to the center
field track; other Mets had to do the bashing Sunday. That happened
in the sixth, when Bubba Trammell pinch-hit for Cook, who had
relieved Jones after a Karros single gave the Dodgers a 5-4 lead in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort fell behind Trammell, 2-0, and Trammell crushed a
sinker into the left field bullpen for his second Mets homer.
Harris followed with a home run deep into the bleachers in right,
finishing Dreifort's erratic outing and putting the Mets up, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, a single by Green eluded Harris in left field,
and his error brought in a run to tie the score. But Wendell picked
Green off second _ ``If he slides, he probably safe,'' Wendell
said. ``He wasn't off the bag by much'' _ and the Dodgers had
scored for the last time. Franco and Benitez made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how good our bullpen is,'' Hamilton said. ``If we can
give it to those guys, we're sitting pretty.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
