<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7389 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-SOUTH-1STLD-WRIT     08-20 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-SOUTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN DEMOCRATS ARE KEEPING GORE AT ARM'S LENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.C., S.C., Ga., Tenn., Fla., Ark.)  (Eds: Subs 3rd graf to correct `this' week to last week.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As if Vice President Al Gore did not have enough
trouble in his native region, several prominent Southern
politicians of his own party have been keeping their distance from
him as they begin their own general election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates for governor in North Carolina and for
senator in Georgia have avoided appearing with Gore and skipped
last week's Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles. The
governor of South Carolina left the convention early and has
dismissed Gore's chances in his state. Each has his own
explanation, and no one will confess to a deliberate snub of the
national ticket. But taken as a whole, their decisions seem to
illustrate the South's general indifference to Gore's appeal and
demonstrate how hard he will have to work to capture even a few
states in the region.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, held a rally in downtown Atlanta on Aug. 10, there was
no sign of Georgia's newest statewide Democratic candidate, Sen.
Zell Miller, the state's former governor. Miller was recently
appointed to replace the late Paul Coverdell, and has only a few
weeks to campaign to keep the job in a special election in
November. But rather than attend the convention, or spend the time
campaigning, he chose to spend last week on a private, unannounced
tour of Georgia's military bases, unaccompanied by reporters or
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate for governor of North Carolina, state
Attorney General Mike Easley, chose not to appear with Gore during
a June visit to meet with flood victims, although the two men met
privately. Easley has made it clear in various interviews that
campaigning with Gore is not a priority for him. Easley, in a
conference call, spoke to the North Carolina delegation at last
week's convention but was criticized by some delegates for not
appearing in person and for distancing himself from the ticket.
Campaign officials said he was too busy campaigning to go to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hodges, the Democratic governor of South Carolina, left the
convention rather conspicuously on Tuesday, before the acceptance
speeches of Gore and Lieberman. Hodges, who has had a rocky
political relationship with Gore, was quoted in The State, the
Columbia newspaper, as saying that Gov. George W. Bush has a ``99
percent'' chance of winning South Carolina, adding that he was not
planning to work hard for the ticket. Hodges is not up for
re-election this year, but is commanding a major campaign for a
November referendum to create a lottery in the state that would
provide more money for education.
</P>
<P>
   According to a series of recent polls taken before the
convention, Gore was behind in every Southern state except his
native Tennessee. Gore may be doing better after his convention
appearance, but the earlier polls showed that he had been hurt by
President Clinton's unpopularity in the region, and his own
positions on issues like gun control and the environment are seen
as less congenial in the South than those of Bush. By contrast,
Democrats like Easley and Miller are the heavy favorites in their
races, and Hodges is a popular figure in his state. All three seem
painfully aware that voters in the region continue to distinguish
between national Democrats and Southern Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always happens, and you can bet it's going to happen in
this year's races _ the Republicans are going to try to tie the
state Democrats to the unpopular head of the national party,'' said
Bill Moore, a professor of political science at the College of
Charleston. ``From their point of view, it's just pragmatic
politics to appear as independent from Gore as they can be.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Hodges said he was not trying to be aloof by
leaving the convention early; he said he had made a commitment to
attend a fund-raiser for a state Senate candidate. But he obliquely
suggested that Southern voters have different priorities from those
voiced at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moderate Democratic candidates can win in the South, if they
focus on a core set of issues that voters care about,'' Hodges
said. ``Too often, Democrats at the national level are identified
with more liberal causes that send voters to the Republicans.'' He
backed off his earlier assessment that Gore had no chance in South
Carolina, saying Gore's selection of Lieberman and his positions on
education and Medicare might help him if he chose to campaign in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But many Southern Democrats are grumbling more openly that the
Gore campaign has spent little time and money in the South,
essentially freeing up candidates to go off on their own. Richard
A. Harpootlian, the chairman of the South Carolina Democratic
Party, said the Bush campaign was still reaping the benefits of
having spent at least $4 million in the state during the hotly
contested Republican primary in February, while the Democrats have
spent about $5,000 in the state so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The successful Democrats in the South have fought hard and
swam against the current to win their elections,'' Harpootlian
said. ``If the national Democrats want to come here and spend some
money and work hard, they can do it, too. But so far, they're
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley, the candidate for North Carolina governor, said much the
same in a recent interview with The Charlotte Observer. ``I want
them to commit the resources, commit the effort,'' he said of the
Gore campaign. ``If they do that, I think they can win the state.''
But in the absence of a strong national presence, Easley said, he
has to run his own race, because ``there's not any room on the
ticket for a weak campaign, top or bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign insists it can be competitive in the South _
particularly in Tennessee, Florida and Georgia, and possibly North
Carolina and Arkansas _ and plans to devote resources to the
region, although Douglas Hattaway, a campaign spokesman, said he
did not know precisely where Gore would appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a Southern New Democrat who has long favored a
strong defense, welfare reform, fiscal responsibility, and values
like that,'' Hattaway said. ``Those are the kind of issues that are
important to Southern voters and New Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Dent, a spokesman for Miller, said it might be the
Southern Democrats who wound up helping Gore, a reversal of the
conventional coattails theory. Miller, as a new senator, has been
too busy learning the job and gearing up for his campaign to appear
with the national ticket, Dent said, and has never been terribly
interested in partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to Washington to play partisan games,'' Dent
said. ``But he is a strong vote-getter, and it may just be that
some of his supporters will decide to vote for Mr. Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
