<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID DELAYS AND CANCELLATIONS, LABOR SECRETARY TO MEET AIRLINE
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A record number of flight delays and cancellations
has prompted officials in Washington to call an unusual meeting on
Monday in the hopes of finding ways to ease conditions for
beleaguered air travelers.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of a growing outcry from airline passengers,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has summoned airline
executives, union leaders and airport officials to discuss ways to
improve airline travel. Officials from eight major airlines have
said they will attend.
</P>
<P>
   The delays and cancellations, coming at the peak of vacation
season, have fueled a debate that the nation's air system may be
approaching gridlock. With 48,448 delayed flights, June was the
worst month ever for on-time performance, the Federal Aviation
Administration said. In July there was a slight improvement, with
only 44,401 delays, but that was still far more than the 25,672
recorded in the same month two years ago. Those figures do not
reflect the thousands of flights that were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Sunday that they hoped the meeting would help
forge a consensus among the various parts of the nation's air
system on how to deal with the problem and end months of
finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that the secretary can use his power and influence
to help the groups to come together and walk away with specific
action items for the different groups,'' said Mary Trupo, a
spokeswoman for Slater.
</P>
<P>
   Trupo added that the meeting was intended to highlight, and
hopefully build on, some successes in recent months, like the
slight decrease in delays in July from June.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the nation's air travel have grown as the number
of passengers has increased. The already overloaded air system has
been further buffeted by stormy weather and labor problems.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, the world's largest carrier, is locked in a
dispute with pilots who are refusing overtime shifts. The dispute
has forced the airline to drop 4,800 flights from its summer
schedule and to cut 2,000 flights in September.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Slater flew to Chicago to meet with both sides of the
United dispute but appeared to do little to advance a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The two federal agencies that monitor the airlines, the Federal
Aviation Administration and the Department of Transportation, have
also been criticized. A study released by the department's
inspector general in July found that since 1988 the FAA and the
Department of Transportation had underestimated the amount of time
lost by passengers by a total of 247 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
