<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ELS, AN END TO THE RUNNER - UP STREAK; WATSON STILL GOING
STRONG; NO SURPRISE BY MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With GLF-PGA)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ One by one, disappointed players came off the
course, knowing the year's final opportunity to win a major
championship had passed them by.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, who finished second in the year's first three majors,
finished the PGA Championship well back in the field at 3-under par
Sunday. At least he didn't have to deal with another second-place
finish, but he was hoping to finally finish first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two days, I totally lost it with my putting stroke,''
said Els, the world's No. 2-ranked player and a two-time U.S. Open
winner. ``I don't believe I have ever putted as bad in all my life.
I missed everything and had a terrible time on the greens. It's a
bit disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been playing well this year. It's obviously very
disappointing to play like this. All in all, I have to look at my
year, and I played very well. I've had a good time. I could have
done better here and there, but I can't complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson and Davis Love III tied for ninth place at
9-under par, but both players faded over the weekend when they had
a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly disappointed,'' said Mickelson, at age 30
looking for his first major championship. ``I would have loved to
have won here at Valhalla. It's a course I felt very comfortable
on. I felt like I had been playing well this year and would have
loved to have won a major.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson Still Going Strong
</P>
<P>
   At 50, Tom Watson shot 68 to finish nine under par for the
tournament, good enough to tie for ninth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with the way I played and the way I competed,''
Watson said. ``After not really striking the ball well Sunday, I
was a little bit tentative about how I was going to hit the ball
today. I changed something on the practice range today and it
worked. After the first couple of holes, I was very confident with
what I was doing as far as my golf swing was concerned. After a
start of 76, it wasn't a bad tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   No Surprise By May
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, who knows Bob May well, was not surprised by
May's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the average fan looks at Bob May, they just see a good
young player,'' Mickelson said. ``When I was growing up in San
Diego, Bob May dominated. He was a couple of years older than I
was, and he won every Southern California PGA junior championship
there was. He qualified for the L.A. Open when he was 15 or 16
years old, and he has been a top, top player at every level of the
game. It's just taken him a little while to get out on the PGA Tour
and to win. He is a very tough competitor. He was one of the most
difficult guys to beat head to head as a junior.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
