<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-NYT     08-20 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS AGAIN RENEW THEIR BERTH IN WNBA FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ By now, after winning three straight league
championships, the Houston Comets might seem blase about a chance
at a four-peat. Not so Sunday against the Los Angeles Sparks, who
were left stunned at being swept from the Western Conference finals
by a Houston team they dominated in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets were as gritty in victory as they were giddy in
celebration, knocking off the Sparks, 74-69, with clutch shooting
and defense in the final minute to win the series, 2-0. As Janeth
Arcain, the Comets' unlikely star, clinched Houston's fourth
consecutive trip to the WNBA finals with three free throws, her
teammates gleefully danced around as though they were experiencing
something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one step closer to our ultimate goal, but winning
never gets old,'' Cynthia Cooper said with a huge smile.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who has announced her plans to retire after these
finals, led the Comets with 29 points. Arcain, averaging only 8
points in the playoffs, scored 16 points on 6-of-8 shooting. Tammy
Jackson came off the bench to add 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Houston won despite a poor game from Sheryl Swoopes, the WNBA's
most valuable player, who became nauseous and dizzy in the locker
room before the game. She finished with eight points, but handed
out six assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets will play the New York Liberty or the Cleveland
Rockers, who are tied at one game apiece in the Eastern Conference
finals. The deciding game is Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The last professional sports team to win four straight
championships was the National Hockey League's Islanders, who won
four Stanley Cups from 1980-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the game goes, you have to tip your hat to
Houston,'' Los Angeles Coach Michael Cooper said. `That's why
they're the three-time defending champions. They know what it takes
to win. They made the necessary plays toward the end to pull this
one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved our effort. I thought there were some things that we
could have done, some shots that didn't go in that normally fall
for us, but that's the way it goes. We wish them well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed, 67-64, with three minutes to play, but
Tamecka Dixon sank a 3-pointer to tie the score. After the teams
traded baskets, the Comets delivered two key plays.
</P>
<P>
   With 39 seconds remaining, Arcain provided the game-winning
basket, drilling a running jumper as the shot clock ticked below
three seconds to give Houston a 71-69 lead. With 22 seconds left,
Jackson provided the game-saving play, swatting away DeLisha
Milton's short jump shot, which could have tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to stay whichever way Milton went,'' Jackson
said. ``She's good going to both sides. It was an opportunity that
presented itself, and I was there to block her shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper said: ``Can you pick a better time to block a
shot? Wow, that was something.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcain then made three of four free throws to finish the Sparks,
who had beaten the Comets in each of their three meetings en route
to a league-best 28-4 record during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks also lost on the day Cooper was honored as the WNBA's
Coach of the Year in a pregame ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were probably determined not to lose to us again,'' said
Lisa Leslie, whohad 12 points and 14 rebounds for the Sparks. ``I
think it's really hard to judge based on one or two losses that
we're not a championship-caliber team. We feel like we did a great
job this year. We just lost to a very good and very experienced
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika led the Sparks with 19 points, Dixon scored 17 and
Milton added 12. Although the Sparks had a 34-25 edge in rebounds,
they were held to 35.4 percent shooting, making only 23 of 65
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Houston made 29 of 59 shots, 49.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets quickly established that their 77-56 romp in Game 1
in Houston was not a fluke. That loss last Thursday was the Sparks'
worst this season, but Sunday they broke to a 12-6 lead. The Comets
answered with a 12-0 run and led by as many as nine points in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a lot more experience, especially in the last two
minutes,'' Arcain said. ``That's why we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes said: ``The satisfying part was that we beat them once
at home and once here. I'm sure Michael Cooper's award had them
fired up and excited, but we hung in there, played well and got the
job done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
