<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WANNABE? MO SAYS IT AIN'T SO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A headline in Sunday's New York Post said Anaheim
Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn ``wants to be a Yank.'' The story
says Vaughn ``admitted he craves for the opportunity to play for
the Bombers'' and quoted him saying how exciting it would be to
play for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn grew up in Norwalk, Conn., as a fan of the Yankees and
attended prep school in Pawling, N.Y. But he said Sunday he does
not want to be traded to the Yankees. He is in the second year of a
six-year, $80 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime I come here they (New York writers) ask about coming
back to play in New York,'' Vaughn said. ``It (his comments about
playing in New York) wasn't meant at all to say I didn't like it
here (with the Angels). Understand, I'm happy where I am. This team
is an up-and-coming team. I want to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angels have taken care of me. I'm happy where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival throws in bullpen: Closer Troy Percival, on the
disabled list since Aug.5 with an inflamed nerve in his right
elbow, threw a bullpen workout Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His velocity was there, the sharpness on his breaking ball was
there, but his command is something he's going to have to deal
with,'' Scioscia said. ``I think he's making strides.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival will return to Southern California and begin a rehab
assignment at Single-A Lake Elsinore on Tuesday. If all goes well,
he could be activated toward the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad out: Darin Erstad missed Sunday's game because of a tight
left rib cage, only the third game he's missed this season. Erstad
left Saturday's game after three innings when he began having
muscle spasms in his side.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia said Erstad ``probably'' will sit out
tonight's game against the Red Sox as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to Saturday I feel great,'' Erstad said. ``It wasn't
worse when I woke up, which is an encouraging sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster move: The Angels are expected to send pitcher Brian
Cooper back to Triple-A Edmonton because they don't need a fifth
starter until Aug. 29 and could use an extra arm in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper continues to struggle with his mechanics, resulting in an
inability to locate his pitches. Since throwing a three-hit shutout
against the A's on June 30, Cooper is 1-6 with a 10.02 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
