<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ROCKERS-LIBERTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY BRUISE ROCKERS TO EVEN SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  By   LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's playoff game between the Cleveland Rockers and New York
Liberty was not staged on the court in Madison Square Garden, but
in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to throw the first punch,'' said Liberty
forward Vickie Johnson, who had ice bags on her sore left shoulder
and sprained right ankle after the battle, which the Liberty won,
51-45. ``The thing we wanted to do was send a message in Madison
Square Garden, our home. They want to talk about physical, we'll be
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Having lost the first game of the Eastern Conference finals by
yielding to the board-crashing, body-blocking Cleveland Rockers,
the Liberty was determined not to be bullied again. Facing
elimination in the two-of-three-game series, the Liberty drove
straight into the Rockers in the first half, pummeling them into
submission and leaving them scoreless for an 11-minute stretch that
helped give New York a 19-point halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second 20 minutes, the Liberty players hung on in
desperation. They scored only 15 points while earning two technical
fouls. While the technicals may have served as badges for the
players' wounded pride, they were barely able to outlast the
surging Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was able to even the series and force tonight's game
in the Garden for the right to play the Houston Comets, the
three-time defending champions, in the Women's National Basketball
Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty has won 12 straight on its home court, three of them
at the Rockers' expense. Cleveland's Merlakia Jones, who scored 14
of her 18 points in the second half, said that her team's late
effort gives it confidence going into Monday night. ``It's going to
be an all-out war,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Her prediction could have stemmed from an incident late in the
game. After coming away with a steal, Weatherspoon was incensed
with the attitude from the Rockers' 6-7 rookie center, Ann Wauters,
a 19-year-old from Belgium. Weatherspoon said Wauters was staring
her down, walking toward her as if to antagonize her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to back down from anyone,'' Weatherspoon said.
``That's not my style. If you're in my home, too, for a youngster
to walk in my face, I'm not taking it from anyone.'' Weatherspoon
practically challenged Wauters to spar, which resulted in a
technical for the Liberty guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's combative attitude was clear from the game's
opening minutes. With New York trailing, 5-2, Johnson drove through
the lane and drew a foul from Mery Andrade, the Rockers' enforcer.
Later in the first half, the Liberty was literally able to take
Andrade out of the game for a while when she sprained her right
thumb in a collision with New York's Tamika Whitmore.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade left at 9 minutes 13 seconds to get X-rays. In her
absence, the Liberty launched a 19-0 run to take a 24-7 lead, and
the Rockers could not recover. During that stretch, the Rockers
missed 17 straight shots. For the first half, the Liberty shot 57.1
percent from the field and took a 36-17 lead into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Liberty began to play on the fumes of
its emotion, rather than relying on rebounding and defense. ``We
got a little relaxed and lost focus,'' Johnson said. ``I think it
was like we were trying to kill them, trying too much, and
sometimes it works against you. We just needed to settle down and
play Liberty basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   While this was the physical play the Rockers expected, Andrade,
who played 26 minutes yesterday and is expected to play tonight,
said she was surprised that some Liberty players reacted the way
they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have veteran people on that team that should not act the
way they act,'' she said. ``The way we were aggressive, it wasn't
in a mean way to get people hurt. And if you notice, nobody got a
technical foul on Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's Crystal Robinson earned a technical foul because
she thought Andrade was the one trying to inflict pain with dirty
play. ``Andrade gets you away from the ball, just with elbows in
the throat, and she trips you,'' Robinson said. ``You try to run,
she clips you with her feet. I had had enough of it. I told the
referee if he didn't stop it, I would do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson added a few ``choice words'' to that statement and was
assessed a technical with 11:23 to play. At that point, the Liberty
led,43-28, but started to let the lead slip. Down the stretch, Tari
Phillips steadied the Liberty, finishing the game with 12 points
and 6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Hammon, who led the Liberty with 13 points, made two foul
shots and her jumper with 6:22 to play kept the lead at 11 points.
The Rockers missed three 3-pointers in the final 1:53, and the
battle was extended to another game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
