<HEADER>
A7398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-65     08-20 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO FINDS NEW FRIENDS IN DEMOCRATIC STRONGHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. _ Vivian and Salvatore Frisicaro were wearing
Hillary stickers, but when Rep. Rick Lazio strode past them at the
Pulaski Day parade on Sunday afternoon, they did not voice
fist-waving contempt or even grimace like the longtime Democrats
they profess to be.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the Frisicaros let slip a secret: They were
apostates, Lazio fans who had turned against their party's Senate
candidate, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need help, economically, medically,'' explained Frisicaro,
69, a retired teacher's aide who said she had put on the sticker as
a courtesy to a friend who handed it to her in this suburb of
Buffalo. ``I think she had her try when President Clinton was in,
with the health-care plan. And health care is still going down the
tubes.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Frisicaros', the political allegiances of Erie County,
a classically blue-collar Democratic redoubt in western New York,
are not always predictable. The county has increasingly become one
of the most crucial swing areas in New York, and if the number of
Lazio backers who lined the route Sunday was any indication,
Clinton cannot assume the county is a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic organization in Erie County is more formidable
than any in the state outside New York City, but it has faced some
unexpected defeats in recent years. It lost the county executive's
office last year and could not stop Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican, from winning the county in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lazio and Clinton have identified Erie as vital to their
campaigns, and although Clinton skipped the parade, which
celebrates Polish-Americans by honoring the Revolutionary War hero
Casimir Pulaski, she arrived late Sunday afternoon for a visit to
an arts festival that followed the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was greeted enthusiastically as she mingled with people
before taking the stage to dance a polka with her daughter,
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   She also served kielbasa at a food stand, conducting a taste
test that compared the local variety with one her campaign had
brought from Westchester, her new home county.
</P>
<P>
   In brief comments to reporters, Clinton did not directly address
her chances in Erie, though she expressed fondness for the people
of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign aides disputed the idea that Lazio had a chance
here, saying that wayward white, working-class Democrats like the
Frisicaros would return to the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a swing area that it's important to win, and I'm
confident that we will do so,'' said Howard Wolfson, a spokesman
for the Clinton campaign. ``We have devoted an enormous amount of
time upstate. And we are the only candidate in the race to have an
economic plan to bring new jobs upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   It also might be argued that some of those at the parade could
have been smitten by Lazio because he took time to shake their
hands or pose for photos with their children. Still, it was not
difficult, in more than 20 interviews with Democrats at the parade
to find people leaning toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's New York state born,'' said Adolph Rakowski, 62, a
retired custodian who recalled that the only Republican for whom he
had voted in recent years was Pataki in 1998. ``I don't think that
we should have a carpetbagger running. She does not know where
western New York is. If she learns where western New York is, maybe
we can vote for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby was Ray Full, 79, a retired painter, who said it would be
unthinkable to vote for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Full said he had supported a Republican in the past _ Rep. Jack
Quinn, who has close ties to labor _ but would not do so this time.
``Hillary is going to win,'' Full said. ``Most of the time the
Democrats get in around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after he marched, Lazio said the response
pleased him. ``If this today is any indication of the level of
support that we have in a county that has a Democrat registration
edge, we are going to do very well,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Lazio used the day to express his appreciation for
the county and for Polish-Americans, though he seemed to evince a
little confusion about geopolitics when he said in a short speech
that he had favored Poland's entrance into the North American,
rather than North Atlantic, Treaty Organization, or NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and his aides continued to attack a Spanish-language radio
commercial that is being sponsored by the Democratic State
Committee in support of Clinton. The commercial declares that Lazio
has always voted in Congress against the interests of Hispanic
people on government spending, the military's use of a bombing
range in Puerto Rico and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an attempt to bring out the very worst in people,''
Lazio said of the commercial. ``It's beyond distorting the record _
it's an outright fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed his criticism and his demand that the
commercial be withdrawn, saying that it was factually correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``National Hispanic groups have given him a zero for his voting
record,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
