<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPER NAMED WNBA COACH OF YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Former Laker Michael Cooper, a Los Angeles
Sparks assistant last year who took over the helm in November, was
selected the WNBA Coach of the Year after leading the Sparks to a
league record 28 victories in the regular season and their second
consecutive post-season appearance.
</P>
<P>
   League president Val Ackerman presented Cooper with the award
before the Sparks game against the three-time defending champion
Houston Comets Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He was the overwhelming choice with 37 votes. Cleveland's Dan
Hughes had nine and New York's Richie Adubato had six. Houston
coach Van Chancellor, recipient of the previous three honors,
garnered a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper is no stranger to success. He won five NBA championship
with the Lakers, was the Defensive Player of the Year in 1987, and
a five-time first-team member on the All-Defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ranks amongst the best,'' Cooper said. ``This is special
because it's a new kind of breaking ground. Women's professional
sports is on the rise and I am so honored and pleased to be sort of
the base foundation of it. I followed the WNBA since its inception
as far as 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talked a little bit with Johnny. I interviewed for the first
job that they had here. He told me that, Mike the timing wasn't
right.' And it wasn't. Now that the timing was right I was able to
fit in a groove and I just wanted to push women's sports,
especially professional basketball, to let people know that these
women can play the game at a very high level. I'm very, very glad
to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to thanking Laker and Sparks owner Jerry Buss,
president Johnny Buss and general manager Penny Toler and his
family, Cooper acknowledge his assistant coaches and players.
Sparks guard Allison Feaster said it was ``no-brainer who was going
to be the Coach of the Year. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing the respect that he commands. He's not a man
of many words, and that's good. He says exactly what he feels. The
most important thing about our player-coach relationship is the
trust that we have in him and the trust that he has in us,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is really it for Cynthia: After scoring a game-high 29
points to lead the Houston Comets to a 74-69 victory over the
Sparks and into the WNBA Finals, Cynthia Cooper reiterated that she
would be retiring after the season. No if, ands or buts about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last season, my last playoff, this was my last time
playing in the Great Western Forum in Los Angeles,'' said Cooper,
who won two NCAA championships a USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely an emotional game for me. Yesterday marked
one year that Kim Perrot passed away. Oh man, I prayed before the
game that God allowed me to play hard, just play hard and play
well. I really wanted her to be proud of me and my mom to be proud
of me. So if nothing else I wanted to leave it all out on the court
today to see if I still have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot was the inspirational leader for the Comets for two years
and Cooper's best friend before succumbing to brain cancer Aug. 18,
1999. Perrot's death preceded Cooper's mother, Mary Cobb, who died
of cancer in February last year.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Sears presented a check for $352,551 to the
National Alliance of Breast Cancer Organizations on behalf of the
Sears WNBA Breast Health Awareness program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-00 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
