<DOCNO> NYT20000820.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     08-20 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE A REMINDER OF PAST DODGERS GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers may want to consider a new promotion:
Blindfold night.
</P>
<P>
   This would allow fans to shield their eyes from hideous moments,
like the one that took place in the eighth inning Sunday and
typified a season gone wrong, and pretty much gone, period.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had runners on first and third with no outs when Lenny
Harris hit a nubber along third that Adrian Beltre fielded cleanly.
But Beltre proceeded to lob the ball over the head of catcher Todd
Hundley, allowing one runner to score, and when no one bothered to
cover home as Hundley chased the ball to the backstop, the second
runner scored all the way from first.
</P>
<P>
   That was only one of several gory moments best shielded from the
view of small children during the Mets' 9-6 win. Like the second
inning, when catcher Hundley suffered a passed ball on a called
third strike and moments later misfired on a steal attempt. Those
miscues were worth two runs.
</P>
<P>
   There was a Mark Grudzielanek error that added a third run in
the eighth. There were the back-to-back homers Darren Dreifort
allowed in the sixth after the Dodgers had tied the game. There was
Shawn Green getting picked off second in the seventh inning,
leaving the Dodgers with one run to show from two hits, two walks,
a Met error and a stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst moment of the whole day might have been that TV
picture of Mike Piazza and Mets manager Bobby Valentine standing on
the lip of the Mets dugout and sharing a chuckle during that
R-rated eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Both are ex-Dodgers, of course. Reminders of the club's past
surround it like a moat, prickly thornes that accentuate its
current lost and clueless situation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough that Piazza is hitting .345 with 32 home runs
and 100 RBI. While Hundley was struggling defensively (he did hit
two homers), Piazza Sunday turned in two (set ital) defensive (end)
gems, catching a foul popup in the second while sliding knee first
into a cement curb, and catching another in the ninth while going
head-first into the first row of seats.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is a different matter entirely. He was never a great
Dodger player like Dusty Baker, everyone's first choice to replace
poor Davey Johnson, but Valentine considers the Dodgers his first
family.
</P>
<P>
   When Tommy Lasorda was inducted into the Hall of Fame, the
ex-Dodger manager said Valentine was the best manager in the game.
That caused internal problems that still impact the club today. But
such is the state of the Dodgers misery that the concept of
Valentine someday becoming the Dodgers manager should be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is manipulative, cocky and not beyond telling a fib or
two, and those opinions come from people who like him. Valentine's
resume includes zero divisional titles and a reputation for being
disingenuous. He and Mets General Manager Steve Phillips have been
waging a personal war for two seasons that seems destined to end
with Valentine moving on, regardless of what happens in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine's Mets won 97 games last season to earn a wild
card berth and advance to the NLCS, where they lost to the Braves
in six games, with three of the four losses by a run.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, the Mets are 74-50, trail Atlanta by 1 games in the
N.L. East and lead the wild card race by 3 games over Arizona and
10 over the Dodgers. Valentine's team has won eight consecutive
series, are 26-12 since the all-star break and 21-6 in their last
27.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets won Sunday with ex-Dodger Harris -- ad infinitum
nauseaum -- posting two runs, two hits and two RBI, and with
Valentine going through five pitchers to secure the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby is a lot like Tommy,'' said Harris after the win,
``except more aggressive. He will put on a lot of plays, so much so
that you never know what to expect. He's a soldier, and he's in
charge of this locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll make that extra move with the bullpen. He'll give a
starter a day off and give a guy like me a chance to play. We get
things done. We can't always depend on a home run from Mike. We
have to do the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have played the entire season without a regular left
fielder and with a 27-year-old rookie, Jay Payton, in center.
Valentine has used catcher Todd Pratt more than one would expect
with Piazza on the same roster, gotten a terrific season from a
player, Derek Bell, who was considered tainted, and played more
little ball than you'd think with seven double-digit home run
hitters on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Bobby for 27 years, and he's never been arrogant
around me,'' said Lasorda. ``He's a little cocky. He's got a lot of
self-confidence. What's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brilliant tactician who knows how to run a ball club.
He won 97 games last year and the most wins any starter had was 13,
and one of those guys was Bulldog (Orel Hershiser). What does he do
wrong? You can't tell me, because there isn't anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda thinks someone in the media who didn't like Valentine
created a reputation that has since taken on a life of its own --
just as Lasorda was once considered a rookie-killer, ``despite the
fact that the Dodgers had nine rookie of the year winners when I
was manager,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misread anything into Lasorda's comments. He wasn't
stumping for Valentine as a replacement for the beleaguered
Johnson, who is simply mortified at this stage of the season, he
was just responding to questions about Valentine's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to imagine the Dodgers being any worse off with
Valentine as manager as they are today. Regardless of any
trepidation over his style, he'd at least demand pride for the
uniform and organization, something the team isn't getting now.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't a Lasorda-Valentine ticket, as G.M. and manager, be
preferable than the out-of-towners and out-of-synch duo of Kevin
Malone and Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, Siegfried and Roy would be a better duo. But
that's what Dodger baseball has become, a circus act with a G.M.
culled from the Expos, blindfolds for the fans, and consideration
of things and people, like Valentine, never before imagined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
