<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-NYT &LR;      08-20 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER OUT, BUT DAWES AND CHOW MAKE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shannon Miller went twisting into the air during her
first vault Sunday night but found herself too low in the air and
too short on her landing. With a horrendous thud, her legs jammed
into the padding like post-hole diggers.
</P>
<P>
   Her 23-year-old body buckled on impact. Suddenly, Miller, the
most decorated female gymnast in U.S. history, was flat on her
back, staring at the rafters of the Fleet Center as her coach,
Steve Nunno, and the U.S. coach, Bela Karolyi, circled her. They
spoke, but their words did not register. In her daze, she was more
stunned than injured, more mortified than hurt. With stiff legs,
Miller got up and finished her only event of the night with an
awkward second vault.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a distraught Miller scratched from the
competition. The doctors cleared her, but it was obvious Miller
could not put on a show that would be in synch with her golden
image. Still, she was looking for a miracle appointment to the
Olympic team, hoping Karolyi's belief in her had not eroded,
believing her body of work might be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was room in the selection committee's subjective
rules to put her on the six-woman team, Karolyi and company chose
the two other remaining members of the 1996 Olympic gold team, Amy
Chow and Dominique Dawes _ alongside with new generation gymnasts
like Elise Ray, Kristen Maloney, Morgan White and Jamie Dantscher.
But they left off Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Miller wiped the tears from her face, knew her career was over
and exited the building.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the end to Miller's comeback simplified the selection
process. If Miller had completed the trials with a solid but not
spectacular performance, if she had finished out of the top six, or
even top 10 at the trials, controversy would have erupted had she
made the team. As it was, Miller's presence caused an undercurrent
of tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if someone says they deserve to be on the team like
she did _ at least that's what I read, I wasn't in her interviews _
then I guess people assume she'll be on it,'' said Dawes, who began
her comeback in April. ``I don't think I deserved to be on the
team. I came her and wanted to prove I belonged. Just because you
made it in '92 and in '96, that doesn't give you the right to think
you belong in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee agreed. They could not rationalize placing Miller
on the team and leaving off someone like Dawes, who finished
seventh, but leapfrogged sixth-place Vanessa Atler to land on the
team. Atler's omission from the team _ with eighth-place Alyssa
Beckerman named as the alternate _ was the major shock of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Atler was mentally unprepared to perform at her best, and she
knew it. For some reason, her heart was not in this meet and it
showed with scores that left her 10th in the trials. Sunday night,
she just bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone else wanted it for me more than I did,''
Atler said. ``When they named the team, it was sort of a relief. I
knew I wasn't ready. I was messing up all over the place. It's not
my time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have any fun here. I don't know, I just wasn't
into it. The performance I put out there is not Olympic materia.
Maybe that's why I'm not as upset about this as I could be. That's
why I'm not taking this too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler was even smiling. There were tears everywhere _ some for
joy and some out of disappointment _ but there was very little
controversy. No one had a gripe with the selection procedure.
Although Miller vanished afterward, she did speak during the meet
after she scratched from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no injury,'' Miller said. ``I just jammed my legs.
They've seen what I can do, and they saw what I did in verification
on Tuesday and then on Friday. If they need me to be ready for the
team, I'll be ready. Obviously I wanted to compete tonight, but I
didn't want to risk an injury. I didn't want to go out there not
looking my best.''
</P>
<P>
   The last image of Miller at the Olympics will have to sustain
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent is not enough,'' Karolyi said. ``In two back-to-back
performances, on Friday and tonight, she could not prove she was
capable of representing her country.''
</P>
<P>
   There are six women Karolyi believes can try to defend the gold
that Miller led the women to in 1996. Two of the Magnificent Seven
remain, Chow and Dawes. And four young women will circle around
them in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the most colorful and dramatic trials ever,''
Karolyi said. ``I didn't know how it was going to turn out. I
believe I was right with this process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are medal contenders. This is a strong team. If
they perform to their potential, they can win a medal.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
