<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY TRIES TO GET EVEN, BUT FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When they were growing up in Southern
California as junior golfers, Bob May set records that Tiger Woods
would break.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were juniors,'' May recalled, ``I was 16 and he was 9,
so he was still playing nine holes and I was playing full rounds.
But later on, in some newspaper articles he would say, `I'm going
to beat Bob May's record,' which he pretty much proceeded to do. He
kept on saying it and doing it, so I was hoping maybe I could get a
chance to get back at him.''
</P>
<P>
   May got that chance in Sunday's final round of the 82nd PGA
Championship, and he almost did get back at Woods.
</P>
<P>
   With a desperate 15-foot birdie putt from the fringe of the 18th
green for a third consecutive 66 to Woods' 67, the 31-year-old May
forced a three-hole playoff that Woods eventually won with a bunker
shot within a foot on the same 18th hole, the final playoff hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it ended,'' May said, ``Tiger told me: `It was a great
match. You played incredible.'''
</P>
<P>
   May, who earned a total of more than $700,000 in previous PGA
Tour and European Tour events this year, played the round of his
life against the world's No. 1-ranked player in one of the most
dramatic duels in a major golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you shoot three 66s in a major, you should win,''
May said, ``but you are playing against the best golfer in the
world, and he proved that is not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In earning $540,000 as the runner-up with a record-sharing
18-under-par total for 72 holes, May at least fulfilled his own
expectations &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You might say that if I shot maybe 62 today and three 72s, it
was kind of a fluke,'' he said. ``But I shot 72 the first day and
then three rounds of 66 on a pretty good golf course. So I don't
think there is any fluke involved in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had won, it would have been a dream come true. Not only
to win a major, but to beat _ well, we can't say Tiger is the best
ever to play, it wouldn't be fair to a lot of other players, but
when he is done, he may be the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   May trailed Woods by one shot after 54 holes. In the tension of
being in contention in a major tournament for the first time, he
had a strange night of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played so much golf in my sleep,'' he said. ``I mean,
I slept great until the alarm clock went off, but all I was doing
was playing these holes in my sleep. I was like, wow, I'd play that
hole again and I'd wake up _ well, not really wake up, just kind of
turn over. It was weird. But I never played a hole out. I just kept
on seeing holes, but I never hit a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit shots Sunday _ shots that had the gallery rooting for him
as the underdog. When he birdied the 535-yard second hole as Woods
bogeyed, May suddenly led by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they started rooting for me then,'' May said. ``I
think they thought, `This is going to be a little interesting.' And
they seemed to root for me all day. It's tough out there. I turned
to Tiger and said, `Is this what you get every week?' and he said,
`You got it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see how he can be a little irritable at times, and
people think he's not being kind to people. But it is tough when
you get that four or five and a half hours a day. But it's great to
have fans. Fans make the golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   May's home is in Las Vegas with his wife, Brenda, and their son,
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason my wife wasn't here,'' he said, ``is that she's due
with our second child in four and a half weeks, maybe five weeks.
The doctor doesn't let her fly anymore. But my parents were here,
and I had several other friends come in to support me. I probably
had a dozen people I knew personally who came from all over the
country to support me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not counting Tiger Woods. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
