<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HAMPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACHING HAMPTON SAYS HE'LL SKIP START; HAMILTON HURTING; WALLACE
QUIET ON FUTURE; FIRST IN A WHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Hampton said Saturday that if he felt better
Sunday, he expected to work a bullpen session. If things went well,
Hampton might then be cleared to start on Tuesday in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, the plan changed. Hampton, who left his start
last Thursday because of a stress fracture in his right ribs, threw
lightly in the outfield and did feel better. But he did not throw
in the bullpen, and he will not start on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Hampton said, when asked if he will make the start.
``Maybe over the weekend. We'll come up with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Mahomes, who threw six and two-thirds effective innings in a
spot start last week, would be the logical candidate to fill in.
The Mets have little flexibility on their roster, making it
difficult to recall Grant Roberts or Bobby M. Jones from Triple-A
Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's injury, which he believes stems from a high school
football game 11 years ago, is not the kind that worsens the more
he pitches. The Mets believe it is simply a question of how well
Hampton can tolerate the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they want to give it a few more days to heal,''
Hampton said. ``I guess if I'm feeling a lot better after two days
with not a lot of activity, maybe a few more might get us further
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said he would make a final decision on
Hampton's status Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Hurting
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Darryl Hamilton, who has not gone more than a day
without starting since coming off the disabled list on Aug. 9, sat
for the second game in a row Sunday. Lenny Harris started in left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has experienced discomfort in his arthritic left big
toe since playing a game on wet grass during the Mets' last
homestand. He singled as a pinch-hitter in the seventh inning and
was removed for a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want it to be an issue every day,'' Hamilton said.
``It's going to be there the whole year, and I understand that. I
have good days and bad days. Hopefully, I can hold on to the good
days so later in the year, I can go out for a good amount of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Quiet On Future
</P>
<P>
   Like manager Bobby Valentine and general manager Steve Phillips,
the Mets' coaches all have contracts that expire after this season.
Dave Wallace, the pitching coach, could be attractive to other
teams, and a report in The Los Angeles Times said the Dodgers want
to bring him back. Wallace coached for the Dodgers from 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Phillips would not allow other teams to interview
Wallace, who was under contract. ``I like Dave, and he's an
important member of our organization,'' Phillips said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was noncommittal about whether he wanted to return to
the Mets. ``Steve and Fred have been very good to me,'' he said,
referring to Phillips and Fred Wilpon, the co-owner. ``I don't
really concern myself with that stuff. We've got six tough weeks
ahead of us. Those are my only concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who came to the Mets as an adviser to Phillips, joined
Valentine's staff after three coaches were fired last June. Asked
about his relationship with Valentine, Wallace said, ``Since we've
started working together, things have kind of moved along pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   First in a While &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander Bobby J. Jones lasted 4 2/3 innings Sunday, the
first time he has failed to pitch five innings since returning from
an assignment to Triple-A Norfolk. He is 7-2 with a 3.26 earned run
average in 11 starts since then. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
