<HEADER>
A7516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NYPD-CHIEF-NYT     08-20 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPD-CHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FIRST DAY, NYPD'S NEW CHIEF ASKS FOR `A CHANCE'  
</HEADLINE>
  By JUAN FORERO    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after being named New York City's new police
commissioner, Bernard Kerik took the first step to fulfill his
pledge to reach out to the city's minority residents, who are among
the department's harshest critics.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday _ along with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Joseph Dunne,
the new first deputy commissioner _ Kerik visited a black church in
East New York, Brooklyn, where he asked about 60 congregants to
give him a chance to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik also spent the first hours after his appointment meeting
patrol officers in the 41,000-member department, visiting precincts
in Manhattan and Brooklyn, including the Midtown South precinct,
where he was a rookie officer, and the 50th Precinct, which covers
the Riverdale section of the Bronx, where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, 44, who comes to the nation's largest police force after
serving as commissioner of the city's Department of Correction, is
being closely watched by community groups and city leaders because
of strained relations between the department and blacks and
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kerik's predecessor, Howard Safir, a crime drop that had
begun in the early 1990s accelerated, but relations between the
police and the city's minority residents worsened after the torture
of Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant, in a Brooklyn precinct house
and the fatal shootings of Amadou Diallo and Patrick Dorismond,
both unarmed black men.
</P>
<P>
   In the visit to Bright Light Baptist Church on Sutter Avenue,
Kerik vowed to work with community leaders while striving to ensure
that officers were respectful of all city residents.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, a former undercover detective who won commendations for
valor, said that he already had told officers that wrongdoing would
be punished. But he also said that mistakes by officers need not
inflame relations with the community if there is understanding and
respect on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik told the congregation that in visits yesterday morning to
the 33rd and 34th precincts in Washington Heights, he had advised
officers: ``If you do something and you do something by accident,
if you do something that you didn't mean and it wasn't intentional,
I need to be able to go to the community and say, `I need help.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In order for me to do that, they've got to believe
in you. They've got to trust you. You've got to show them respect.
And, I'm sure if you show them that respect, you're going to get
the respect back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerik also had something to say to those, including the Rev. Al
Sharpton, who were critical of his appointment, though he did not
single out anyone by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've listened to the nay-sayers,'' he said. ``I've listened to
all the derogatory comments in the last 24 hours. It's somewhat
humorous. They don't even know me. They never met me.''
</P>
<P>
   And he asked the churchgoers to tell others to support him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to tell them one thing: `Give him a chance,''' said
Kerik &UR; .  &LR;  The pastor of Bright Light, the Rev. H. Devore Chapman,
and many church members said they had known and respected Dunne
since the early 1990s, when he was commander of the neighborhood's
precinct, the 75th. Therefore, they said, theirs was a community
that was willing to listen to the new commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a community for him to start in, to work with him,''
Wooten said after the service.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, in remarks at the church, said that the new leadership
in the department would provide ``a chance to try to improve on
things, to do things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   He also stressed that it was imperative that the community
respect the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to improve with the way the police deal with the
community, and the community has to improve with the way they deal
with the police,'' he said. Kerik also spent time demonstrating his
support for rank-and-file officers in the department, where morale
has been affected by criticism and what many officers see as low
wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know, as your boss and commanding officer, I
support you and understand your job,'' he told about 15 officers at
the 50th Precinct station house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
