<SLUG> BC-NYPD-CHEIF-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS :  KERIK'S APPOINTMENT TO NYPD TOP SPOT LEAVES SOME
WONDERING
</HEADLINE>
 By ERIC LIPTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
rejected the advice of the departing police commissioner and the
wishes of much of the rest of the department hierarchy. But the
leadership team he installed in the city's highest profile agency
makes perfect sense, if viewed through the mayor's prism.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new police commissioner, Bernard Kerik, is someone the mayor
trusts, and whose loyalty, like that of the outgoing police
commissioner Howard Safir, he need not question. The mayor expects
that Kerik, who brought order to the once-chaotic city jails, will
move with alacrity to tighten the Police Department's financial
management.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Dunne, the 31-year department veteran whom Safir backed
and who many had predicted would get the top job, is now first
deputy commissioner, the department's second in command. He can use
the relationships he has established with rank-and-file officers
and the department's top brass, as well as his rapport with some of
the city's minority leaders, to help Kerik pursue his goals.
</P>
<P>
   And at City Hall, the mayor keeps at his side the third finalist
for the commissioner job, Dennison Young Jr., one of his closest
and most trusted aides. Since the administration began, Young has
helped coordinate law enforcement matters, and keeping him there
effectively ensures the mayor can maintain his supreme command over
a department whose crime-reduction campaign has so defined his
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the arrangement mixes the best skills of each,
assuming the team can work together for the 16 remaining months the
mayor has in office. ``The city is going to have the good fortune
of having all three of them working together,'' the mayor said on
Saturday. ``It's a wonderful team.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor showed obvious pleasure at his decision. But as he
articulated his choice on Saturday, it became clear that the
effusive praise he had offered Safir _ repeatedly calling him the
city's greatest police commissioner _ might have been too generous.
If not, why then would the mayor appoint a new commissioner who has
implied he wants to curtail overtime spending, make Police
Department managers more accountable and improve department morale,
while also pushing to ease tension between the department and
ethnic groups?
</P>
<P>
   The community relations campaign got under way yesterday
morning, as Giuliani, Kerik and Dunne together went to the Greater
Bright Light Baptist Church in Brooklyn for the Sunday service at
the predominately black church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the department to reach out more, and we want the
people of the city to understand that we expect from them that they
are going to respect the police more,'' Giuliani said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   By passing over Dunne, 52, who as chief of the department had
been the top uniformed officer in the 41,000-person force, the
mayor demonstrated his concern that a man who had spent his entire
career within the department might be too caught up in the
traditional ways and too closely allied with his department
colleagues. For the mayor, these questions of loyalty are
particularly important now, as his administration presses the
Police Department unions to accept money-saving changes in
personnel rules and to switch to a merit-based system of pay
raises. The department's largest union is resisting such changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure most New Yorkers will agree that New York City's
police officers have been productive and we will leave the rest of
the negotiations to the bargaining table,'' said Joseph Mancini, a
spokesman for the 27,000-member Patrolman's Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, 44, and Giuliani first met when Kerik worked as a city
narcotics detective and Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, was
making his first run for mayor. Kerik coordinated Giuliani's
security detail on weekends during his second campaign, and shortly
after the mayor went into office in 1994, Kerik became the first
deputy commissioner at the Department of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   His success in reshaping the city's troubled Correction
Department _ where inmate stabbings and violence against officers
had surged _ is largely what earned him his new job. Kerik, who
became correction commissioner in January 1998, shares the mayor's
obsession for numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He applied this data-driven approach to Correction, measuring
employee performance on more than 130 statistical yardsticks, from
inmate violence to officer overtime and sick time and the speed at
which broken equipment was repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik was able to get more out of correction workers and ``at
the same time build their morale by holding them accountable,'' the
mayor said yesterday. ``That is the sign of a truly effective
leader, in the modern day in which you have to accomplish all of
those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerik clearly intends to take some of his same management
techniques to the Police Department. ``It'll give you a way to get
to see every little bit of the agency, every area where you may be
lacking,'' Kerik said on Saturday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some city officials and former police administrators
question how effective the commissioner will be at accomplishing
these goals. He served as a city police officer for only eight
years before leaving for the Correction Department, and his quick
rise to the top of the nation's largest police department may
result in some resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds, or perhaps thousands, of supervisors or
commanders in the Police Department who have seniority to him,''
said City Councilman Sheldon Leffler, D-Queens, who is chairman of
the Public Safety Committee. ``That has often made it difficult for
someone assuming command to get people under him to follow his
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerik is also known to be temperamental, and his willingness to
demote and replace subordinates who do not live up to his
expectations may heighten resistance. Kerik comes out of a
department where the customers are under lock and key. He will
suddenly be serving the city at large, running an agency that has
four times as many employees. And Kerik, who does not have a
college degree, is now leading an agency that wants its
rank-and-file officers to have college experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is OK to be the commissioner without college, but you can't
be a cop without college,'' said Rafael Collazo, first vice
president of the Latino Officers Association, which represents some
correction officers and police officers. ``It is outrageous. If we
are holding out a standard for police, it should start from the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, by not naming Dunne, who earned a high degree of
respect from black leaders in the city when he was a Brooklyn
precinct commander, the mayor has already inspired some criticism
that he is not adequately committed to repairing the relationship
between the police and minorities, which has suffered following
recent shootings of unarmed black men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that the mayor felt there was a need to build
bridges,'' said City Councilwoman Annette Robinson, a Brooklyn
Democrat who is black. ``Joe Dunne could have done that. I am
saddened that he was not given that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton echoed that view, but Giuliani rejected the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win with some people,'' the mayor said, laughing.
``We're doing everything we can to reach out. There are some people
that make their reputations and money on criticizing the Police
Department. You are never going to please them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
