<HEADER>
A7537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CYRANO-THEATER-REVIEW     08-20 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYRANO-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CYRANO DE BERGERAC': NOT JUST A NOSE, BUT A STATE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  By BRUCE WEBER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   In the light mist that suffuses
the black-box stage of the Clark Studio Theater at Lincoln Center,
the Aquila Theater Company's production of ``Cyrano de Bergerac''
begins with an engaging series of directorial ideas. Actors enter
and begin building a makeshift theater out of rudimentary props: a
platform on a pushcart, a closet-size proscenium with light drapes
for a curtain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Collapsed umbrella skeletons, lonely-looking on the floor, are
raised high by a pulley, their arms spreading, tiny lights along
them illuminated: Voila! Chandeliers! And the babbling Parisians
who arrive for a theater performance in the opening scene of
Rostand's comic melodrama are portrayed by a shuffling scrum of
actors holding puppets, the frivolous repartee traded among the
animators and the animated.
</P>
<P>
   The clear message is that this is to be a conceptual ``Cyrano,''
the vision of Robert Richmond, associate artistic director of the
Aquila, a nine-year-old, half-British, half-American touring
company based in London and New York. Richmond, who also directed
the company's ``Comedy of Errors'' that was enthusiastically
received in New York this summer (I didn't see it), has adapted the
script as well as directed this production, and he sets a high
standard for charm and invention in his opening sequence, which has
a precociously witty feel.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappily, it is only intermittently matched thereafter, as the
tether of the auteur tightens around the collar of the production,
and both actors and script are held in thrall to an inconsistent
welter of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Written in the late 19th century and set in the 17th, ``Cyrano''
is of course the defining parable of the
appearance-versus-character question, the story of the world's most
competent, honorable and manly man whose gifts and accomplishments
are dwarfed only by his nose _ the shame of which keeps him from
declaring love for the beautiful Roxanne, makes him defensive and
bitter, and consigns him to a martyr's loneliness. With its
gloriously highfalutin speechifying, its unabashedly outsize
passions and its elbow-in-the-ribs spirit, it has always been
attractively ripe for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is that Richmond doesn't seem to have settled
on a tone for the show, which waffles among broad farce,
anachronistic sitcomesque jokiness and, particularly in the
soliloquies of Cyrano himself (Anthony Cochrane), straightforwardly
formal melodrama. His script adaptation mixes modern colloquialisms
and occasional vulgarity _ Cyrano's colleagues, the Gascon guards,
are prone to flatulence jokes and flourishing their middle fingers
_ with Rostand's more sophisticated tongue-in-cheekiness, an
undermining flirtation with sophomoric baseness.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond does create a handful of effective tableaux _ as in the
famous scene in which Cyrano, speaking for handsome but
inarticulate Christian (Alvero Heinig), woos Roxanne (Lisa Carter)
beneath her window _ in which the actors are positioned to play to
the audience rather than one another, a simple idea that pays
dividends to the performers, connecting them to their characters in
a way that Richmond's more heavy-handed tricks do not. His
swordplay scenes, in slow motion, replete with smoke and effusive
lighting, are merely grandiose.
</P>
<P>
   In sum there's a showoffy quality to this production:
independent scenes informed by separate ideas (Hey, watch this!)
rather than a firm grip on the play as a whole. But Richmond's
reins are tightly held throughout, and the actors are victimized by
his sacrifice of sustained wit for mere jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting players particularly appear to be roped firmly
into broad comic performances their gifts don't support Sean Fri,
as De Guiche, the privileged military officer who has designs on
Roxanne, and Heinig (who plays the fop humiliated by Cyrano's
eloquent recitation of nose jokes, as well as Christian) overplay
the wimpy card with conventional mugging.
</P>
<P>
   Most egregiously, Jenny Israel, as Roxanne's maid, for some
reason employs the overexcited accent of a Southern yahoo, as if
she reported to work from the set of ``The Andy Griffith Show.''
Even Carter, who, as Roxanne, is poised when in serious mode
(despite a hoop dress that consists of only barrel staves and
exposes her undies), becomes frivolously cartoonish when Richmond
unnecessarily wants her shallow attraction to Christian
underscored.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the play Cochrane gives a game performance
here; his verbal aptitude for Cyrano's eloquence is apparent (a
Scot, he has the voice and accent for it) and shows himself capable
of both the seriousness of Cyrano's torment and the glibness of a
Seinfeld. But the nature of the production has him shuttling back
and forth between impulses, as though he's changing masks; in his
several long speeches he does a lot of pacing, which feels less
like a character's nervous release of energy than an actor's
desperate search for a center.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's performance Cochrane had the added burden of
keeping his makeup glued on. His nose fell off twice before he
finally put it in his coat and finished the play without it. He
provided one glitteringly timed ad-lib, patting his pocket when he
would otherwise have pointed to his face, but otherwise his
performance was improved for his not having to worry about it.
Cyrano's nose was better off in his head, not on it. Like a lot of
obvious elements in this production, it was only calling attention
to itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
